<SLUG> BC-GLF-USOPEN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STEWART LEADS OPEN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients) 
By Michael Madden 
c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ For all the reasons Payne Stewart is not only
leading the 98th US Open but also is the only golfer under par,
this may be the most telling: There have been 294 double bogeys
through three rounds, but none by Stewart.
</P>
<P>
   Swirling winds and bright sun that firmed the fairways so that
the slightest miss caused shots to roll off them and into the
ever-deepening rough have humbled all who have teed it up at The
Olympic Club; all, that is, except Stewart.
</P>
<P>
   So Stewart is the improbable leader, firing a par 70 Saturday
that kept him in the same position at day's end as at day's
beginning _ 3 under par. Virtually all other golfers lost ground to
Stewart as he has a four-stroke lead over Tom Lehman (68_211) and
Bob Tway (73). His four-shot lead is the largest entering the final
round of the Open since Tony Jacklin also led by four in 1970.
</P>
<P>
   Nick Price (71) and Lee Janzen (73) are tied for fourth at 212.
Seven other golfers are within eight strokes.
</P>
<P>
   Improbable leader? Well, Stewart may have won the Open in 1991
at Hazeltine outside Minneapolis, but he has won only one other
tourney in the US in the eight years since (the 1995 Shell Houston
Open, beating Scott Hoch in a playoff). Stewart may have won
$8,465,062 in his career and may be the seventh-leading all-time
money winner, but tour wins have been scant, and few since he beat
Scott Simpson in a playoff to take his second major. He won the
1989 PGA Championship.
</P>
<P>
   If he wins Sunday, said Stewart, ``it would tell me that I still
have the ability to compete in a major championship. It would be
very, very special.''
</P>
<P>
   And it is precisely Stewart's consistency (``I'm just a
plodder,'' he says) that has nudged him to the top here, since even
the slightly errant shot is penalized so harshly. The way he looks
upon Olympic, said Stewart, ``is that par is a heck of a score on
every hole here.'' Little daring, nothing glamorous.
</P>
<P>
   Well, except for No. 1 perhaps, the par-5 533-yard hole that
Stewart has owned all three days. He eagled it Saturday (5-iron to
20 feet) after making birdie the first two rounds. ``It's wonderful
to get off to such a nice start,'' he said. ``It gets you in a good
frame of mind.''
</P>
<P>
   Which Stewart promises to be in Sunday. ``I'm a big advocate of
self-motivating myself and I just say to myself, `I've been here
before; I've done it; you're a champion,' and `There's no reason
why you can't be a champion again.'''
</P>
<P>
   One of the few golfers to make up ground on Stewart was Tom
Lehman, one of only three golfers to break par Saturday. Lehman, of
course, has been extremely close to winning the last three Opens _
third in 1995, second in 1996, and tied for the lead at
Congressional last year when his shot found the water on the 17th
hole on the final day and he finished third.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, I don't think the Open owes me one,'' said Lehman. ``I
think I owe myself one, though.''
</P>
<P>
   Lehman had walked off the 18th on Friday extremely angry, one of
the many players who complained about the pin placement atop a
slope on the 18th green. ``I was ready to take someone's head
off,'' he said. ``But (Saturday), I walked off the 18th feeling
very happy; it was a very good day.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Good'' because Lehman _ unlike so many other golfers _
``didn't shoot myself in the foot.'' Reflecting on his three close
calls the last three years, ``I think I've learned a lesson that I
have to be patient on Sunday.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the many golfers who took a free fall Saturday, one of the
most painful was by amateur Matt Kuchar, who will turn 20 Sunday.
Kuchar was alone in second place, 1 over par, when he teed off on
the 14th hole, but he proceeded to three-putt the hole, the first
of four straight bogeys, which dropped him off the leaderboard.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was my first real opportunity for a birdie out there,''
said the amateur, ``and I really goosed it. I got a little too
excited, and I hit it way too hard.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Brad Faxon of Barrington, R.I., to whom the Open
never has been kind, was in ideal position Saturday to make his
first mark on an Open leaderboard as he started the day at 1 over,
four shots behind Stewart. Faxon needed only to play a consistent
round of near-par golf to be in the thick of the battle.
</P>
<P>
   But Faxon started the day with a bogey ``and I got off to a bad
start,'' he said. What followed was a ghastly front nine of 7-over
42. ``What I learned is that if you're not psyched and not in clear
focus out here, you're looking at a lot of bogeys,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Faxon double-bogeyed the the 438-yard fourth, but he really ran
into trouble on the 437-yard sixth, ``when my 6-iron went into some
hard ground and I really felt a jolt to my back,'' he said. ``I
couldn't loosen my back for a few holes.''
</P>
<P>
   Faxon, though, had a fine recovery on the back nine and came
home in a scintillating _ for this day of winds _ 34. ``I hit it as
good as I could hit it on the back nine,'' he said after finishing
a truly bizarre round of 76, leaving him 7 over for the tourney and
10 shots behind Stewart.
</P>
<P>
   So the Open Sunday clearly will be Stewart's to lose, since it
is extremely unlikely any golfer within sight of Stewart will go 4
or 5 under par. ``My mother is staying with me,'' said Stewart,
``and I'm sure I'll get a good night's sleep ... unless my mother
snores, that is.''
</P>
</TEXT>
