<HEADER>
A9130 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAR_DRAGRACINGDEER-AZ     06-21 0774
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR_DRAGRACINGDEER-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK ARMIJO  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   With Rob Deer, there rarely was a middle ground.
</P>
<P>
   Deer either smacked a pitch far over the outfield wall or struck
out mightily, the buttons on his shirt nearly bursting on every
swing.
</P>
<P>
   In 11 Major League Baseball seasons, Deer cranked 230 career
home runs. But he also struck out 1,409 times in 3,881 official
at-bats.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a philosophy when I went up to the plate,'' said Deer,
who retired after the 1996 season. ``Swing as hard as you can, just
in case you hit it.''
</P>
<P>
   Makes you wonder how the 6-foot-4, 245-pound Deer will fare in
his post-baseball career, which at the moment, is drag racing.
</P>
<P>
   Deer either will blow the doors off a rival or get his 1955
Chevy BelAir off the starting line too early and red light, causing
an immediate disqualification.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hmmm, I hadn't thought about that,'' Deer said.
</P>
<P>
   Doesn't matter. Deer, 37, is having too much fun and has too
many goals to worry about drag racing's hits and misses.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I always knew I'd pursue this sport once my baseball
career ended,'' said Deer, who began his career in the San
Francisco Giants organization, but spent most of his career with
Milwaukee. ``My dad (Bob) always loved fast cars. He loved anything
fast.
</P>
<P>
   ``He used to hide me in the trunk of the 1962 Chevy Impala that
he raced and sneak me into (defunct Orange County Raceway). He'd
put me in the grandstands and I'd watch him race. I fell in love
with it.''
</P>
<P>
   When Deer retired, he renewed that love and purchased a 1967
Chevy Camaro, which he raced in the National Hot Rod Association's
super street sportsman category.
</P>
<P>
   Later, he talked his parents into moving from California to
Mesa, where Deer has lived for several years, and persuaded his dad
to resume his own drag racing career.
</P>
<P>
   ``It probably had been 30 years since I last raced a car,'' said
Bob Deer, who is 60. ``I remember making my first pass out at
Speedworld (Motorplex) and thinking maybe I was in over my head. I
thought maybe I had lost some of my coordination. It's not like you
just get in these cars and step on the gas. There's a lot of things
to worry about.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I've made several passes since then and now I kind of
think my car is too slow. It goes about 130 miles an hour, but I
want to go faster.''
</P>
<P>
   Bob Deer now is driving the Camaro and Rob recently purchased a
1955 Chevy BelAir and competes in super gas.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just got a new motor for it,'' Deer said. ``It's got 540
cubic inches and 900 horsepower. It cost about $15,000. But we're
serious about this sport. I'm trying to earn enough points to
qualify for the World Finals.''
</P>
<P>
   Bob Deer, who still works full time at Falcon Field, will travel
with his son next month to Sonoma, Calif., and compete in a
national event at Sears Point Raceway. Primarily, however, the
elder Deer's plans are to compete only locally at Speedworld,
Firebird International Raceway Park or Southwestern International
Raceway in Tucson.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if this has brought us closer together because
Rob and I have always had a close relationship,'' Bob Deer said.
``But I can't tell you how much of a thrill it is to go up to the
starting line and see your son over in the next lane.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know how many fathers and sons get to do something
like that. It's really fun and a special feeling. I beat him the
first time, but he's beaten me every time since.''
</P>
<P>
   Rob Deer understands his dad's excitement, because he's
experiencing the same inner sensations.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've hit some home runs in my career that were pretty big and
memorable,'' Deer said. ``I remember I hit one on Easter Sunday in
'88 when I was with Milwaukee that helped us win our 13th straight
game to open the season. That still gives me goose bumps. The next
week, I was in a store and I saw my picture on the cover of
``Sports Illustrated.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But you wouldn't believe how exciting it is to win a round
against another driver in a drag race. The cars are so loud and the
window gets fogged up when you're there at the starting line. It's
a real kick in the pants.
</P>
<P>
   ``Baseball was my life for 20 years, but I was thinking about
racing even when I was playing. I remember Robin Yount and I used
to talk about racing a lot. Whenever the Indy 500 came on every
year, Robin made sure it was on the television in the locker room.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was never that much into that kind of racing or even NASCAR
racing. What I really like are these (NHRA) door slammers. That's
my future right now. That's all I'm thinking about.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
