<HEADLINE>
MESSED UP IN HEAD 
 MARINERS, ACE STRUGGLE WITH MENTAL SIDE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PEDRO GOMEZ  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   By just about anyone's account, the Seattle Mariners are not a
very good team right now. Expected to win the American League West,
the Mariners are languishing in their division's cellar with a
30-44 record.
</P>
<P>
   The easy culprit to blame for Seattle's awful season is the
bullpen, which has been atrocious since the first week of the
season. This club's real problems, however, lie in the front
office.
</P>
<P>
   Unwilling to pull the trigger on the trade that would have sent
Randy Johnson to Los Angeles for Ismael Valdes and Wilton Guerrero
this month further sent Johnson spiraling deeper into the funk he
had been in since before spring training.
</P>
<P>
   Other players followed Johnson into the abyss they've been in
since the trade was nixed, allegedly by one of the Mariners'
owners, Microsoft executive Greg Larson, who owns 30 percent of the
club, which is 4-14 the deal was killed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The worst part is that (Larson) doesn't realize what it does
to us,'' Ken Griffey Jr. said. ``It leaves us all in a situation
that no matter how Randy pitches, if he pitches well or doesn't,
there's still a chance he'll be traded. The uncertainty is bad for
our team.''
</P>
<P>
   The mental side of baseball is a fragile aspect of the game that
is rarely talked about, but it plays a tremendous part.
</P>
<P>
   ``The game is all frame of mind,'' Oakland right fielder Rickey
Henderson said. ``Any time you let the game get into your mind,
you're going to get into trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson's head is messed up right now, the direct result of the
front office's game of yo-yo with him. It's no wonder Johnson is
6-6 with a 5.17 ERA, numbers well below the standards he has set in
the past five years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Randy's trying, but it's tough,'' Griffey said. ``It's tough
on the team, not knowing. It hurts the focus. It's not that we're
flat. It's like we're playing with something on everyone's mind.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Anything to escape &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Florida has had mild interest from other clubs concerning third
baseman Todd Zeile, the other part of the Mike Piazza deal that
sent Gary Sheffield, Charles Johnson and Bobby Bonilla to Los
Angeles last month.
</P>
<P>
   So Zeile has taken it upon himself to help his cause in trying
to escape the Marlins' sorry situation. Zeile is brushing up on his
old catching skills, which he believes could help speed a trade.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't make a whole lot of sense for me to make the move
(to catcher) right now,'' said Zeile, 32. ``But if someone wanted
to make a commitment to me, it's certainly a possibility. I haven't
caught in a while, so my legs are fresher than somebody my age. I'm
sure I could do it. . . . I miss some parts of catching, calling a
game and working with pitchers.''
</P>
<P>
   Zeile, a catcher throughout college, the minors and his first
two seasons in the majors with St. Louis, is being paid $3.2
million this season and is guaranteed $3.3 million next year. He
recently caught Livan Hernandez during a bullpen session and said
Baltimore and another club have inquired about his ability to
switch back to catching. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Precursor to the Series? &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The two best clubs in baseball, the New York Yankees and
Atlanta, are scheduled to play four games against each other this
week, two in each city.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love to play the Yankees for one reason: for revenge, the
payback,'' Atlanta catcher Javier Lopez said.
</P>
<P>
   Braves third baseman Chipper Jones said: ``Everybody's making a
lot out of that series. You know, it's just four games in the
middle of June. It doesn't really mean anything. Maybe it will be a
preview of the World Series. Maybe neither one of us will get
there. You don't know, in the grand scheme of things.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Numero Uno? &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Dennis Martinez and Juan Marichal exchanged words recently over
who is the best Latin American-born pitcher. Two weeks ago,
Martinez tied Marichal with 243 career victories. Marichal, along
with Dave Stewart the best pitchers never to win a Cy Young Award,
was perturbed after Martinez said he was the best pitcher born in a
Latin country.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to get into an argument about this,'' the
Dominican-born Marichal said. ``But a writer from Venezuela asked
me a question about something (Martinez) said in some article in
Nicaragua. He said he was the best Latin pitcher. I responded by
saying that if he thinks he's the best, I respect his beliefs. But
if you want to see the best, compare the numbers. If you compare
the numbers and if you know baseball, you can judge for yourself.
That's all I said.''
</P>
<P>
   Marichal is correct, of course. During his 16-year career,
Marichal was 243-142 with a 2.89 ERA. He won 20 games six times.
Martinez, born in Nicaragua, is 243-190 with a 3.68 ERA in his 22nd
season. He never has won 20 games in a season but did become the
second over-40 pitcher to record a save for the Braves last week,
joining Hoyt Wilhelm. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Includes information from other media sources. Pedro Gomez can be
reached at
</P>
<P>
   pedro.gomez(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
