</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOXDEVILRAYS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RAYS BEAT RED SOX
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients) 
By Gordon Edes 
c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. PETERSBURG, Fla. _ Life was anything but a beach Saturday
night for the fun-in-the-sun Red Sox, who finally fell off the wave
they've been riding, 8-5, to the expansion Tampa Bay Devil Rays,
who treated Bret Saberhagen's changeup like they were hitting off a
tee.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox lost not only the game, ending a four-game winning
streak before a crowd of 41,169 in Tropicana Field, but also the
argument, as manager Jimy Williams was ejected despite having what
appeared to be a legitimate (sounds like beach).
</P>
<P>
   Williams was tossed for the second time in 17 days, giving him
one more ejection than he had all of last season, after plate
umpire Rich Garcia reversed his call in the fifth inning and ruled
that Quinton McCracken had been hit by a Saberhagen pitch with two
Devil Rays already on base.
</P>
<P>
   All three baserunners scored after Dave Martinez scorched a
two-run double off Saberhagen, who has lost his last two starts
after winning three in a row, and Wade Boggs followed with a
sacrifice fly off rookie Brian Barkley.
</P>
<P>
   Garcia changed his mind after consulting third-base umpire John
Hirschbeck at the request of Greg Riddoch, the Devil Rays'
third-base coach, who told Garcia that he heard the pitch hit
McCracken.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody in the ballpark knew it hit the guy except me,''
Garcia said. ``So I got help from one of my partners.
</P>
<P>
   ``The third-base coach very politely asked me if I'd heard it
because he had. I thought, `My God, if it was that obvious, I'd
better ask one of my guys.' Obviously if he heard it, John must
have heard it, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Out of the Red Sox dugout popped Williams, who sandwiched
himself between Garcia and Hirschbeck while posing, in language
that became increasingly pungent the longer the argument went on,
this question: How could Hirschbeck, standing 120 feet away, be in
a better position than plate umpire Garcia to hear a ball striking
a batsman?
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never seen a third-base umpire make that call because he
heard it,'' said Williams, who added that he has never even seen a
plate umpire ask for help from a base umpire in that situation,
though Garcia claims he has done it before.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were 41,000 people, under a roof in a dome where the
sound isn't going anyplace,'' Williams said. ``This is not the US
Open, where a guy is putting on the 18th green. This isn't
Wimbledon, where somebody holds up a sign saying, `Quiet, please.'
The bottom line is it's disappointing that he would make a call
like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever explanation Garcia offered did not satisfy Williams,
who followed the umpire back down the third-base line, barking all
the way. Even after Garcia tossed him, Williams kept up what had
become a one-sided debate. ``That's bad umpiring,'' Williams could
be seen saying at one point, pointing to his ear.
</P>
<P>
   Garcia said he tried to add some levity to the argument in hopes
of making Williams go away. ``I told him the reason I didn't hear
it is I'm 56 years old and my hearing is gone,'' said Garcia, chief
of this crew. ``Jimy said, `I'm 54 and I didn't hear it.' I said,
`Perfect. You're over 53, and you don't hear, either.'''
</P>
<P>
   Williams was not amused, either at the time or afterward.
``(Hirschbeck) was down behind third base, at least 120 feet
away,'' he said. ``Even if you did hear something, how would you
know what it was? You can't call it from there.''
</P>
<P>
   And Williams grew even more furious when Garcia, in the
manager's presence, turned to Sox catcher Scott Hatteberg and asked
him what he thought. ``He shouldn't be talking to my catcher,''
said Williams.
</P>
<P>
   To the ultimate question _ did the pitch hit McCracken? _ Mo
Vaughn offered an unbiased opinion. ``The correction was the right
call,'' he said. ``Quinton McCracken is not going to lie. He's a
young dude, trying to swing and drive runs in.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think Jimy was arguing the call. I think he was
arguing the change of call. He put some spark in our dugout.''
</P>
<P>
   Down, 6-1, to the Devil Rays, the Red Sox drew to within a run
on Vaughn's 21st home run and Lou Merloni's RBI single in the
sixth, and two hits and a two-run error committed by Tampa Bay
second baseman Miguel Cairo on Vaughn's hard shot in the seventh.
</P>
<P>
   But the Devil Rays, losers of their first four meetings against
the Red Sox, rallied for two runs in the bottom of the inning
against Barkley and Jim Corsi, who gave up a two-run ground single
to catcher John Flaherty, fresh off the disabled list.
</P>
<P>
   The loss, which dropped Saberhagen's record to 8-5, was only the
third in the Sox' last dozen games. Saberhagen bolted from the
clubhouse afterward, not wishing to discuss damage wreaked by
Cairo's triple and Kevin Stocker's sacrifice fly in the second,
Paul Sorrento's two-run homer in the fourth, and Martinez's two-run
dagger in the fifth.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was not the situation where the game was won or lost,''
Vaughn said, referring to the McCracken Affair. ``We clawed our way
back in there, but then some things happened that we can't let
happen tomorrow.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
