<SLUG> BC-RYANCOLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPECIAL PERSPECTIVE ON GAMES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients) 
By Bob Ryan 
c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   We have all been made aware that one of our rich local athletes
is in a classic ``play-me-or-trade-me'' mode. He should be made
aware that there are people in the world with real problems, and
that it would be better were he simply to shut up and play when
asked.
</P>
<P>
   Better yet, he should be sent home immediately. He should then
be dispatched to Cambridge, where he can take a look at a different
type of athlete. He might come away better equipped to deal with
his own life issues.
</P>
<P>
   This is not to imply that the Special Olympics are any kind of
somber experience. Au contraire. The Massachusetts Special
Olympics, which are being held this weekend at MIT, happens to be
one of the great uplifting experiences anyone can have. I mean, if
it's smiling faces you want to see, the Special Olympics is the
place to see them.
</P>
<P>
   It's a variation of the famed Grantland Rice idea that the
important thing is how you played the game. In this case, the
important thing is that you played the game. For many of the
athletes, participation truly is enough to make them happy.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, some of the participants do care more about winning
than others. There are some very spirited competitions. But that is
never the point. As the PA announcer said during the morning track
competition, ``It is OK to cheer for every athlete out there _ just
a reminder.''
</P>
<P>
   You can meet some extraordinary people. Take Michael McAdams,
for example. He has been participating in Special Olympic
competitions since 1987. He was there to run in both the 100 meters
and 400 meters Saturday, but during his time he has earned medals
in basketball, soccer, volleyball, the long jump, and shot put.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got 185 medals,'' he beamed. ``They're all home, in
boxes.''
</P>
<P>
   When most of us think of the Special Olympics, we tend to
conjure up a picture of people running, jumping, or throwing an
object. Track and field is the glamour sport of the event, no
doubt. But there is a lot more going on right now than track and
field.
</P>
<P>
   There is tenpin bowling going on in Dorchester. There is sailing
competition in Charlestown. And there is tennis at MIT.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're one of the smaller competitions,'' explains Sylvia
Swartz, who has brought 14 athletes from Handi-Racket, which plays
out of the Longfellow Club in Weymouth. ``We're almost like a
little subculture over here.''
</P>
<P>
   I got to see most of a doubles match. Dan Widrich and Rich
Miller prevailed over David Broden and Meg Schilling in a match
that included some nice rallies and some particularly agile
retrieves by Miller, a Special Olympics veteran who admitted to
being a somewhat reluctant participant since he considers himself
more of a coach than an athlete these days.
</P>
<P>
   ``Soccer is actually my favorite sport,'' he says. ``It's fun to
watch them kick that ball and then jump up and down when they
score.''
</P>
<P>
   The tennis players are particularly excited because four of them
will be nominated to participate in the 1999 World Games, which
will be held next summer in North Carolina. But most of the
participants don't need that carrot in order to enjoy themselves
here.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been in Handi-Racket for eight years,'' says Rayna
Segelman, who may not have full use of her right hand, but who has
complete command of the English language. ``It's one of the best
things I've ever done in my whole life. You always try the best you
can, but the fact is that every person who participates is a
winner.''
</P>
<P>
   With that, the skies opened up a bit and it seemed to make sense
to get in out of the rain. That took me inside the hockey rink, and
into the roller skating competition.
</P>
<P>
   Now here were some people who were justly proud of their
accomplishments. A young lady named Patty Pitts did something of a
header, but that was OK. Remember the Bing Crosby line in ``Well,
Did You Evah?'' She's a game girl, you know. Got up and finished
fourth. Patty did better than that. She's a game girl who got up
and finished second. You'd have liked the smile on her face when
she received her silver medal.
</P>
<P>
   And speaking of smiles, Peter Richards had a grin as wide as a
football field every time he passed in front of his family when he
skated around the floor. He was pretty psyched when he got his
silver medal, too.
</P>
<P>
   Vicki Movsessian was on hand to give out medals, and if the name
sounds familiar, it's because she was a member of the gold
medal-winning women's hockey team in Nagano.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's great to come here to see the excitement and the
sportsmanship,'' Movsessian said. ``We can all learn so much from
them. I think it's important to recognize all athletes, regardless
of the abilities or disabilities.''
</P>
<P>
   She brought along her gold medal.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's the sense of keeping it hidden?'' she said. ``It's
something that represents the team, family, and the United States
of America. Why not share it?''
</P>
<P>
   The Special Olympics are a huge undertaking, but everything was
humming along nicely Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are very pleased,'' said Tony Carnevale of the public
relations staff. ``We had close to 750 volunteers sign up, and we
must have had another 750 show up on top of that. And we can always
use them.''
</P>
<P>
   The Special Olympics can really get in someone's blood.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the volunteers was telling me that on Sunday he is
bringing his wife and two small children here as a Father's Day
activity,'' Carnevale explained. ``He said that he wanted his
children to see, while they are young, that there are some people
in the world who are different. He thought that would be a great
way to spend Father's Day.''
</P>
<P>
   I know this much: There is no way you can put a price tag on one
of those smiles.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-21-98 0030EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
