<HEADLINE>
LONG RIDE FOR BAHRES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients) 
By Michael Vega 
c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUDON, N.H. _ Sunday, Bob Bahre and his only son, Gary, will
spend Father's Day much the way they spend the other 364 days of
the year. They will be at their track at New Hampshire
International Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully my dad already knows this, but everything I've got
is a result of what he's done for me,'' said Gary, 35, who is
part-owner and president of NHIS. ``I can tell you that even if I
didn't have anything, I've got the best dad in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Bob, the 71-year-old patriarch of NHIS, says none of it would
have been possible without his son. But he doesn't figure on
retiring any time soon.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't retire,'' he said with a cackle. ``I retire every
night, but I have to get up every morning to go to work.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Gary is constantly reminding his father to take it easy.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the time,'' said Gary. ``I'm always telling him that I'd
like to do different things with him. You should come up to Maine
sometime to see his collection of cars. He's got Packards,
Dusenbergs. They're beautiful and he loves them. But one of the
best times he and I ever had together was on a whirlwind trip we
took together.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It was about 15 years ago,'' Bob recalled. ``We got on a plane
and went to Milwaukee and we went to Oklahoma and we went to
Kansas, looking at cars. We finally ended up buying a Packard from
this guy in Oklahoma.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a father-son bonding experience, and they are partners
now in another joint venture, NHIS. Sometimes they agree. Sometimes
they don't. But they always talk.
</P>
<P>
   ``At least twice a day,'' Bob said. ``I talk with Gary in the
morning, then we'll talk again at night.''
</P>
<P>
   As for Sunday?
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll spend it at the track, just like we've always spent
Father's Day,'' Bob said.
</P>
<P>
   ``And we always will,'' chimed in Gary.
</P>
<P>
   Focal point
</P>
<P>
   Evidently, it was dissent between Dale Earnhardt and crew chief
Larry McReynolds that led Winston Cup car owner Richard Childress
to shake up his underachieving teams two weeks ago. Childress made
a swap in crew chiefs, switching McReynolds from Earnhardt's No. 3
Goodwrench Chevrolet to Mike Skinner's No. 31 Lowe's Chevy. Kevin
Hamlin is now Earnhardt's crew chief, bringing an end to the
18-month relationship between Earnhardt and McReynolds, who charged
last week that the seven-time Winston Cup champ has suffered from a
lack of focus. ``Talentwise Dale's still there, but the competition
has certainly caught up,'' McReynolds told Sports Illustrated.
``The days of showing up at a track on Friday, then hightailing it
out of there after the race on Sunday _ without even talking about
what the car was doing, and then maybe driver and crew chief
talking to each other once during the week _ and showing up at the
next racetrack the next Friday, those days are gone.'' Earnhardt
has had his share of distractions. He and his wife have started a
Winston Cup team. He has fielded a Busch Grand National car driven
by his son, Dale Earnhardt Jr. And he has many appearance and
sponsor obligations ... In last week's Miller Lite 400 at Michigan
Speedway, NASCAR officials had to contend with controversy. Leader
Jeff Gordon contended that someone threw a piece of debris onto the
track, prompting a caution period that interrupted his unbridled
gallop. Mark Martin wound up winning, his fourth victory of the
season, to move into third place in the Winston Cup point
standings. The debris was a piece of roll bar padding that NASCAR
officials were unable to match up with a car, leaving them baffled
as to how it wound up on the track. ``We have evaluated all of the
videotapes, and the evidence is inconclusive as far as how the
debris got on the racetrack,'' said Gary Nelson, NASCAR Winston Cup
director. ``While we consider the situation suspicious, there is no
conclusive evidence as to how it occurred. NASCAR's view of a
caution flag is to warn drivers of potential hazards. Obviously,
roll bar padding is not a hazard, but we don't know that until we
go and pick it up.'' ... Jeremy Mayfield, despite being winless
this season, &UR;  &LR; remained atop the Winston Cup standings with a
26-point lead over Gordon (2,023 to 1,997) after finishing fifth at
Michigan. ``We're not pushing the `winning thing,' at least not
mentally,'' said Mayfield. ``Don't get me wrong. We want to win. We
want to win bad, but we're willing to be patient, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Tracy fires back
</P>
<P>
   FedEx CART driver  &UR; Paul Tracy  &LR; will be on probation when he
starts  &UR; today &LR; 's Budweiser/G.I. Joe's 200 at Portland, Ore. CART
officials cited Tracy for a run-in with  &UR; Christian Fittipaldi  &LR; at
the ITT Automotive Detroit Grand Prix. Tracy responded with an
angry missive, citing other incidents that went unpunished. ``If I
am to be placed on probation for attempting to pass a car at 35
miles per hour in Detroit,'' Tracy wrote, ``why was no action taken
when Christian more or less forced me into the wall while trying to
overtake me at Long Beach (repeating the equally unsuccessful
maneuver he tried with  &UR; Greg Moore  &LR; in 1996)? Or when  &UR; Gil de
Ferran  &LR; hit my rear wheel with his front wheel at Rio? Or, for that
matter, when  &UR; Max Papis  &LR; hit  &UR; Arnd Meier  &LR; at Gateway? Or when
 &UR; Patrick Carpentier  &LR; pinched down on  &UR; Michael Andretti  &LR; at
Milwaukee? I cite these incidents not because I believe that two,
three, or four wrongs make a right, but because I think CART should
treat every wrong equally.'' ... Rain wreaked havoc at area tracks
last week. New Thompson (Conn.) Speedway rescheduled the Shaw's 300
for Labor Day weekend, and Saturday night's program at Oxford
Plains (Maine) Speedway was postponed and not immediately
rescheduled.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
