<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NOTES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DRAFT PREVIEW
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients) 
By Peter May 
c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   He is rapidly becoming the ``must have'' of the 1998 NBA draft.
Considering that many hoop fans never even heard of him a year ago,
well, it says that Michael Olowokandi has come a very long way in a
very short time.
</P>
<P>
   He's testament to two NBA articles of faith: (1) You can't coach
height and (2) centers are hard to find. NBA scouts are ignoring
Olowokandi's limited college career (77 games) and lack of tough
competition (he went to Pacific) and are spinning things to the
upside: He didn't start playing seriously until college, and the
unvarnished prospect (he played recreationally in Europe) has not
gotten spoiled by hangers-on and anti-fundamentalists. He has
excellent footwork and agility, thanks in part to years of playing
soccer.
</P>
<P>
   Olowokandi was born in Nigeria and attended high school in
England, at Newlands Manor, which we don't think is the St.
Anthony's of the British Isles. His one year in college in England
was spent at an institution _ Brunel University in Uxbridge,
Middlesex _ that did not have an athletic program.
</P>
<P>
   He decided on the University of the Pacific by choosing it out
of a phone directory. He wanted a school by the ocean. Pacific is
about as close as UNLV is to the Pacific Ocean. It's like Humphrey
Bogart's great line from ``Casablanca'' after he tells Claude Rains
that he came to Casablanca for the water. Told that Casablanca is
in the desert, Bogart says, ``I was misinformed.''
</P>
<P>
   In three years at Pacific, Olowokandi has gone from rudimentary
to stiff to certified 20-10 guy in the NBA. He won't go lower than
second and it's another testament to his size, ability, and
potential that Vancouver, picking second, doesn't feel it can let
him pass even though the Grizzlies have $65 million committed to
Bryant ``Big Country'' Reeves. They would have to move Olowokandi
(or Reeves), but they realize his inherent value and can't let him
go by.
</P>
<P>
   Olowokandi has size (7 feet 1 inch), strength (265 pounds),
speed (4.5 in the 40), and is still young to the game. That means
he still finds it fun, still has room to grow, and doesn't think a
cell phone is as important as a jump shot. He averaged 22.2 points,
11.2 rebounds, and 2.9 blocks for Pacific last season and has
thoroughly impressed everyone with his workouts and interviews.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a heck of a prospect,'' said Grizzlies coach Brian Hill.
``He may not do it right away, but in two or three years, he may be
pretty good.''
</P>
<P>
   Added Golden State general manager Garry St. Jean, whose team
has no shot at Olowokandi unless it trades up, ``We didn't really
work him out. We played H-O-R-S-E with him and talked to him. He's
also a great kid.''
</P>
<P>
   The only unknown is whether the Clippers, picking first, will
pass on Olowokandi, which would be true to their history. The
Grizzlies won't. As Hill put it, ``If we're sitting at 2 and
Olowokandi is available, I think a lot of people are going to be
knocking at our door. If it's Mike Bibby, I don't think we'll get
as many people knocking.''
</P>
<P>
   Olowokandi and Bibby (whom David Falk apparently is not allowing
to work out anywhere but Los Angeles) are 1-2 or 2-1 or 1-1A on
everyone's list. After that is where the fun starts. The next six
players are almost certain to be Paul Pierce, Vince Carter, Robert
Traylor, Larry Hughes, Raef LaFrentz, and Antawn Jamison. They
could go anywhere. After that, it's a guessing game. The Bucks, who
draft ninth and 19th, had 38 players in for workouts. There are two
high school kids, Rashard Lewis and Al Harrington, who could go in
the first round. There are no UCLA kids who could go in the first
round.
</P>
<P>
   Here is a list of the teams drafting and their needs. New
Jersey, Miami, New York, Washington, Phoenix, Portland, and
Cleveland have no first-round picks, while two teams, Orlando and
Houston, each have three.
</P>
<P>
   LA CLIPPERS (1, 22): They need everything but a small forward
and will need that if they move Maurice Taylor, arguably their best
player. The latest rumor has the Clippers trying to get both the
first and second picks, using their roster as an alleged
enticement. Bear in mind that this team has never re-signed any of
its own quality free agents (Loy Vaught was extended), and Ike
Austin may be the latest to bolt.
</P>
<P>
   VANCOUVER (2): Hill says, ``We can use anything other than a
small forward or a center.'' The Grizzlies are getting bombarded
with offers and can afford to select like an epicurean at a
four-star restaurant. They did bring in LaFrentz for a second
workout (always a clue) and may work out a deal with Toronto that
brings them the fourth pick and a body (Doug Christie?). We also
hear Steve Nash's name here, although it would seem that the
Grizzlies would demand more than that for the pick.
</P>
<P>
   DENVER (3, 23): You win 11 games, you need the best of
everything. They'd love Olowokandi, but whom do they have that
anyone wants? Oh yes, and they don't have a coach, either. (Neither
do the Clips.) Any of the available select six would help here.
</P>
<P>
   TORONTO (4): They had three firsts. Now they have one. Prior to
acquiring Kevin Willis (and what was that all about, by the way?)
they had to be looking big. But with Willis and Marcus Camby still
there, they may think smaller.
</P>
<P>
   GOLDEN STATE (5): What an awful roster. And most of the best
players are free agents. They're getting lots of calls about Mr.
Warmth, Latrell Sprewell. They'll go with one of the perimeter
players to help their vaunted front line anchored by Erick Dampier
and backed up by Bill Walton clone Todd Fuller.
</P>
<P>
   DALLAS (6): Their starting backcourt is Hubert Davis and Khalid
Reeves. Need you know more? Cedric Ceballos is also a free agent.
</P>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO (7): Would they dare deal Chris Webber? GM Geoff
Petrie is trying to fight the good fight for the marginal
franchise, but he may have no other option. This team needs
backcourt help. Mitch Richmond is gone, as is Mahmoud Abdul-Rauf
(Turkey).
</P>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA (8): Theo Ratliff and Joe Smith are free agents and
Derrick Coleman could be bought out. All signs point to big,
although a guard who could coexist with Allen Iverson wouldn't
hurt, either.
</P>
<P>
   MILWAUKEE (9, 19): The Bucks have no free agents of note and a
pretty sizable hole in the middle. It's hard to think they will
fill it here, although Ute Mike Doleac would be a natural.
Supposedly, they're also discreetly shopping Terrell Brandon, which
may or may not affect one of their picks.
</P>
<P>
   BOSTON (10): Rick Pitino says he wants scoring, size, maturity,
and a starter. That means someone better than Andrew DeClercq (a
frightening thought) or Walter McCarty. He's looking to move up;
he'd love a crack at LaFrentz.
</P>
<P>
   DETROIT (11): The Pistons should be looking big, given their
unhappiness with Brian Williams. One has to assume they'll re-sign
Jerry Stackhouse. Who else wants a slasher who can't finish and a
scorer who can't shoot?
</P>
<P>
   ORLANDO (12, 13, 15): The Magic can fill positions; will they
fill their needs? They can get a point guard (Jason Williams), a
power forward with at least one major flaw, and maybe take a flyer
on a foreigner at center. Penny will then evaluate the picks.
</P>
<P>
   HOUSTON (14, 16, 18): Three picks in the teens is like getting
Herbert Hoover, Rutherford B. Hayes, and William Henry Harrison in
a ``Best of the Presidents'' contest. The Rockets actually sound
excited at having them, however. Maybe Rudy T can find them on
whatever team he takes to Athens. Again, a chance to fill
positions, one of them possibly being the first high schooler,
local favorite Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   MINNESOTA (17): The Wolves said goodbye to Stanley Roberts,
which, given their precarious center position, tells you a lot
about Stanley Roberts. If they want to go big here, their only
possibility is a foreigner with a contract hangup. And, as Stan
Kasten once noted prophetically (see Celtics v. Jugoplastika,
Celtics v. Il Messaggero), ``International is synonymous with
trouble.'' They still could use help up front, especially with Tom
Gugliotta's status uncertain.
</P>
<P>
   ATLANTA (20): They need a new set of alibis for Lenny Wilkens.
He may need them. The small forward hole is still there, and two
key frontliners, Alan Henderson and Christian Laettner, are free
agents. Henderson will get a lot of interest.
</P>
<P>
   CHARLOTTE (21): Both centers are free agents. How did that
happen? Again, no hope in that department unless they re-sign one.
George Shinn is fast turning into the Donald Sterling of the East.
</P>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO (24): Calling all shooters! With Tim Duncan and
David Robinson (apparently) set for the next couple years, the
Spurs desperately need someone to balance the books on offense. If
Bryce Drew is available, they'll probably go for him. It doesn't
help, we think, that two of the three players in their
spectacularly humdrum backcourt (Vinny Del Negro and Jaren Jackson)
are free agents.
</P>
<P>
   INDIANA (25): Boy, they sure got a lot out of Austin Croshere,
didn't they? The Bulls capitalized on Indiana's one demonstrable
weakness _ athleticism _ and the Pacers need to get someone who can
cover the floor. Someone like Corey Benjamin would be ideal, but
he's likely to be gone by then.
</P>
<P>
   LA LAKERS (26): Jerry West will drive Nick Van Exel to the
airport if need be. West also likes to take point guards, and this
may yet be another time, though maybe not the one we think he'll
take. The Lakers have had luck with late picks and West knows
talent. But talent isn't what this team needs. It has plenty of
that.
</P>
<P>
   SEATTLE (27): We're throwing darts now. There might not be
anyone left who can even make the team, let alone be of any help.
The same holds true for Utah and, possibly, Chicago, depending on
what happens. This might be the place to draft a foreigner, a raw
kid with some potential, and wait, or simply pass and refuse to
guarantee three years to what the late, great John Killilea used to
call a ``K.P.'' (Kan't Play).
</P>
<P>
   CHICAGO (28): You can be sure Jerry Krause has some obscure guy
in mind who will be a terrific player. He always does. The
difference this time around is that the guy may not have to be
wearing a suit come playoff time because there's either not going
to be a postseason in Chicago (NBC's worst nightmare) or the Bulls
will be so mediocre they'll need the guy.
</P>
<P>
   UTAH (29): The Jazz face the daunting task of preparing for life
without Chris Morris. How do they handle that? Scotty Layden has
made some terrific second-round picks (Shandon Anderson, Bryon
Russell), and this might as well be the second round. He also may
go international given that there are no real holes in his team.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
