<HEADLINE>
BONILLA HOSPITALIZED, PUT ON DL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ Bobby Bonilla, already sidelined by a tender left wrist
and left Achilles tendon, was placed on the 15-day disabled list,
retroactive to Wednesday, after being hospitalized Friday night
with an intestinal infection.
</P>
<P>
   Bonilla, expected to remain in a Denver-area hospital until
Monday, also is suffering from dehydration. He first came down with
flu-like symptoms two weekends ago, during the series in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   He returned after two games but remained weak, batting just four
times without a hit in the Dodgers' series in San Diego.
</P>
<P>
   Manager Bill Russell has been concerned by Bonilla's lack of pop
since joining the club. Bonilla is batting .175 in 27 games since
he was acquired May 15 from the Florida Marlins. He hit a home run
in his first game as a Dodger but none since. He had 97 RBI last
year for the Marlins.
</P>
<P>
   ``He just hasn't been the same guy we know he can be,'' Russell
said. ``With all that is going on with him, this was the only move
to make.''
</P>
<P>
   Taking Bonilla's place on the roster is Triple-A left-hander
Will Brunson, 28, who was 4-4 with a 4.75 ERA with Albuquerque.
</P>
<P>
   Luke returns: Matt Luke received a warm reception from teammates
when he rejoined the Dodgers before Saturday's game. Luke, who
played two months with the Dodgers before being designated for
assignment May 29, spent two weeks with Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
   When the Indians designated Luke for assignment June 15, the
Dodgers purchased his contract. He pinch hit for Jim Bruske in the
seventh inning, singled and scored on Eric Karros' bases-loaded
double. In 33 games with the Dodgers, Luke batted .286 with seven
doubles, three homers and 11 RBI. He was 0 for 2 with the Indians.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has been a pretty strange few weeks, to say the least,''
Luke said. ``I went home (Laguna Beach) for a day before getting
here. The Indians let me take batting practice with them for a
couple of days, so I have been working out. But I need to get those
at-bats.''
</P>
<P>
   Friendly fire: Rockies third baseman Vinny Castilla and Dodgers
reliever Antonio Osuna are friends during the offseason in Mexico.
But Castilla was only half-kidding when he said Saturday he thought
Osuna showed him up Friday night after striking him out to end the
game. Osuna threw a fist in the air and gestured Castilla back to
the Rockies' dugout.
</P>
<P>
   ``He went too far,'' Castilla said. ``Maybe next time if I get
him, I will go too far.''
</P>
<P>
   People's choice: Colorado's Larry Walker, on the DL with a sore
right elbow, isn't sure he should be a starting outfielder in the
July 7 All-Star Game at Coors Field. He leads Moises Alou by about
240,000 votes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always said people get voted into the All-Star Game who
probably don't deserve to be there, and other guys get snubbed
out,'' said Walker, who can be activated July 3. ``It looks like
that's going to happen to me this year.''
</P>
<P>
   Walker is batting .336, but the elbow has robbed him of his
power. He has only nine homers and 33 RBI. Alou is hitting .340
with 58 RBI, and Sammy Sosa is hitting .333 with 29 home runs and
72 RBI. ``Some guys are going to get screwed,'' Walker said. ``I
might be the cause of that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
