</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-GONZALEZ-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GONZALEZ SETTING A HEALTHY PACE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ERIC NOLAND  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM _ In the posh new visitors' clubhouse at Edison Field, a
side door leads to a well-appointed gym. In there, among other
fitness equipment, is a bench-press rack with 45-pound disks, a
curling bar, some enormous dumbbells and the requisite mirror
covering an entire wall.
</P>
<P>
   (For some strange reason, all of this lies just beyond one table
laden with doughnuts and another heaped with a decadent array of
candy.)
</P>
<P>
   When the Texas Rangers hit town this weekend, several players
puffed and sweated in the room in the mid-afternoon, but Juan
Gonzalez, breaking from one-time routine, wouldn't step near it. He
remained at his locker, lifting nothing more than the corners of
his mouth.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was working so hard before with heavy weights,'' the
Rangers' slugging right fielder said of his recent past. ``I had a
lot of injuries, a lot of problems.''
</P>
<P>
   That smile broadened. ``But now I feel great. I feel more
flexibility in my body. I feel more strong. More velocity _ speed.
I feel more comfortable.''
</P>
<P>
   For Gonzalez, one of the most powerful hitters in baseball, the
word ``projection'' used to be akin to ``cruel joke.'' He would
take off on a pace that would project to record numbers in RBI or
home runs, but then his muscles and connecting tissue would begin
to rip apart, so overbuilt was his body.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, he hired as a personal, 12-month trainer a
fitness guru from the Dominican Republic, Angel Precinal, who has
studied elite-athlete training techniques in Cuba and in Europe.
``I am exercising,'' said Gonzalez, ``like track and field.''
</P>
<P>
   And not breaking down. The projections, as a direct result,
are... well, not Ruthian, perhaps, but at least Wilsonian.
</P>
<P>
   Texas has played 73 games this season and Gonzalez has appeared
in each and every one of them, along the way rifling bullets to all
fields and driving in 88 runs, a major-league lead that even Mark
McGwire can't touch. If Gonzalez can maintain that pace for 158
games this year, he would break a major-league RBI record that has
stood for 68 years _ since Hack Wilson of the Chicago Cubs drove in
190 in 1930.
</P>
<P>
   (ITAL)If.(END ITAL)
</P>
<P>
   In the past, any such bid was always foiled by a lengthy absence
to injury. Gonzalez has not reached the 135-game mark in any of his
last four seasons. Why, even when he won the American League Most
Valuable Player award in 1996 he missed 28 games because of injury
_ which is an indication of just how thoroughly he can savage
pitching when he is sound.
</P>
<P>
   The maladies were the type that screamed out for increased
flexibility _ torn quadriceps, herniated disk in his back, strained
groin, torn cartilage in his knee, torn ligament in his thumb.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was always hurt because he was too bulky,'' said teammate
Luis Alicea, the former Angels infielder.
</P>
<P>
   ``Six or seven years ago, there was a tendency in baseball for a
lot of players to do body-building,'' added Luis Mayoral, a
Spanish-language broadcaster for the Rangers. ``(Jose) Canseco did
it. Ruben Sierra did it. That was the tendency, at least among the
Hispanics _ to be Adonis, to have the great body. But having the
great body doesn't necessarily mean you're going to perform as a
baseball player.''
</P>
<P>
   Don't assume, however, that Gonzalez now spends his spare time
visiting one of those snack tables in the clubhouse.
</P>
<P>
   ``People see Juan playing every night, putting up the big
numbers,'' said Texas' Roberto Kelly, the former Dodgers
outfielder. ``They don't realize that he gets up in the morning
after putting in a long night and goes to the gym and works out. I
know it because I work out with him.''
</P>
<P>
   Just as much work as before, but with a vastly different
emphasis: stretching and light weights.
</P>
<P>
   The regimen neatly complements Gonzalez's style as a hitter.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire attracts hordes when he takes batting practice, because
his hitting stroke is the type that takes the breath away _ dead
pull, uppercut, launching balls to the deepest reaches of the
left-field seats.
</P>
<P>
   When Gonzalez stepped into the cage before a game with the
Angels on Friday afternoon, it generated barely a ripple of
excitement. Here's why: His first 17 cuts produced hits up the
middle or to right field, with only one ball carrying the wall. Low
liners jumped off his bat and threatened to leave dents in the
right-center wall.
</P>
<P>
   Hardly sideshow stuff _ but something that would cause any
baseball purist to marvel.
</P>
<P>
   A couple of hours later, on a low-and-away fastball that the
Angels' Chuck Finley had appeared to spot perfectly, Gonzalez
lashed a double into the right-center gap that cleared the bases.
</P>
<P>
   Rangers hitting coach Rudy Jaramillo, who managed a 16-year-old
Gonzalez in rookie ball 12 years ago, said, ``The thing I see about
Juan, (compared to) Ken Griffey or McGwire or Albert Belle or Frank
Thomas, Juan is the most prolific line-drive hitter I've ever seen.
Those guys sky theirs, and Juan drives his like a golf ball. That's
the difference. He hits line drives with power.''
</P>
<P>
   Now Gonzalez wants to hit with durability. And play and live
with ease.
</P>
<P>
   By all accounts, the maturity is clearly evident in this former
mercurial and reckless young man. Being divorced three times by age
28 is sure to weather anyone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel relaxed when I play this game,'' he said. ``Before, I
had personal problems, a lot of injuries. But right now I don't
have injuries, I don't have personal problems. I'm a positive man,
ready to play every day. That's it.''
</P>
<P>
   As with McGwire and Roger Maris, Gonzalez has been made keenly
aware of the accomplishment of Wilson. It doesn't produce the
slightest flinch. ``The record is not easy, you know _ 191 is not
easy,'' Gonzalez said. ``But it's not impossible, too. The key is,
when I see men on base, having a lot of concentration to drive the
runs in.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of games remaining, a lot of baseball
remaining, and I'll see a lot of runners on base.''
</P>
<P>
   The words reflect the brimming optimism of a guy who has gone
nearly three months in a rigorous sport without missing a day's
work.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-21-98 0040EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
