<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-NOTES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIG DAY FOR KUCHAR
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients) 
By Joe Concannon 
c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ This is Father's Day, and it is also Matt
Kuchar's 20th birthday. He's having fun out here in the 98th US
Open at the Olympic Club, and so is his father/caddie, Peter. The
Georgia Tech junior upstaged his playing partners _ defending
champion Ernie Els and British Open champion Justin Leonard _ in
the first two rounds, but what else is new? He stole the spotlight
from Tiger Woods at the Masters in April.
</P>
<P>
   This amateur can hit it out there with Woods, he can sink putts
with Ben Crenshaw, and he has the personality of an Arnold Palmer.
Kuchar, who was at 1 under through two rounds, may be a future star
in the sport, but right now he is simply a college kid charming the
galleries in the game's majors.
</P>
<P>
   Kuchar, whose grandfather was an offensive lineman for the
University of New Hampshire in the '40s, lit up the press room at
Olympic the same way he did at Augusta. Asked if he were surprised
or excited after his first two rounds, Kuchar replied, ``Both.
Surprised and excited.''
</P>
<P>
   This is as much a fantasy for his father and grandfather as it
is for him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if you ever get used to it,'' said Kuchar. ``The
feeling you get playing golf is different than anything else. The
nervousness. That feeling of being in contention. I guess it's a
feeling that I don't know if you will ever get used to. It's
exciting when you get that twinge in your stomach. That's really
what golf is all about.''
</P>
<P>
   When Kuchar was at Augusta, he talked about his studies, his
friends, and his college team. There will be a temptation to turn
pro, though, and he'd be a welcome addition to the PGA Tour.
</P>
<P>
   ``I doubt myself turning professional before school ends,'' said
Kuchar, the reigning US Amateur champion. ``But I really don't
know. I really haven't thought about it. Dad and I haven't even
talked about it. It's all up in the air. I'm just rolling with
everything right now.''
</P>
<P>
   No amateur has won the US Open since Johnny Goodman in 1933. The
odds of a collegian doing it are extremely long, but who knows what
Kuchar is capable of?
</P>
<P>
   ``If you start thinking about winning, it's not good,'' said
Kuchar. ``I remember in the junior tournaments I was thinking,
`What am I going to say in my acceptance speech?' I would be
playing in the last group and think, `What am I going say when I
get the trophy?' I never won a single junior event.''
</P>
<P>
   Take it away, Tom
</P>
<P>
   Tom Watson, who returned to the winner's circle at the age of 48
last month at the Colonial, recounted that triumph before the Open,
where he missed the cut after 73-75_148: ``I still believe that I
can swing the golf club and hit the ball straight. I made a slight
change in the takeaway. I did the same thing with the putter. I
shot 66 in the pro-am and I said, `Well, it's working now. Let's
play. See if it works during the regular tournament.' It did.
Emotionally, I was honestly thinking, `Well, is this maybe my last
tournament I am ever going to win on the tour?' That's the reason a
tear or two came out. I am enjoying the twilight of my career.''
... Jaime Ortiz-Patino, the owner, president, and superintendent at
Valderrama GC in Sotogrande, Spain, which was venue for the Ryder
Cup last September, has been selected to receive the Old Tom Morris
Award from the Golf Course Superintendents Association of America.
Ortiz-Patino is also on the board of directors at the Lahey Clinic
and plays golf at Weston GC and Brae Burn CC on his visits to the
Greater Boston area ... Lee Westwood is Great Britain's rising star
and may be a regular on the US PGA Tour next year. ``I haven't made
my mind up yet,'' he said. ``I really enjoy playing here. I enjoy
playing in Europe as well. But there a lot of incentives to join
this tour next year, and it is going to be a difficult decision.''
... Els, whose back spasms forced him to withdraw from Westchester
the week before the Open, may reduce a global schedule that has him
playing in his homeland of South Africa, Europe, Australia, and on
the PGA Tour. ``We will see how it goes,'' he said. ``Obviously I
have got to take that into consideration now, not to travel too
much. But I really enjoy playing around the world, so I have really
got to just reconsider and see how the back reacts in the next
couple of weeks. I've never had any back problems. I've been quite
healthy. It's serious, but it's not the kind of injury which is
going to affect my schedule in years to come, hopefully. We will
take it as it comes the next couple of weeks.'' ... Jack Nicklaus,
playing in his 42d consecutive US Open, is still competitive at the
age of 58. ``I think I've been fortunate from a health standpoint
that I have never been injured to the point where I couldn't
play,'' said Nicklaus. ``I always point and prepared myself for
these events and was always ready to play when I got there. If I
were playing tournament golf every day, I probably would have been
injured more. I've been very lucky.'' ... Tom Lehman, who has led
the last three US Opens entering the final round, followed an
opening 68 with a 75 Friday. He talked about his hopes entering the
competition: ``I try not to think about it. It's a very, very, very
hard golf course.'' ... Olin Browne, who has roots in the Greater
Boston area and played a lot of golf at The Country Club, qualified
for this year's US Open by finishing joint fifth last year at
Congressional. ``If you hit fairways, you have a chance to score,''
said Browne after making the cut on 73-70_143. ``If you don't,
you're DOA. The problem in the Open is that every shot requires
precision. The pin positions require delicate approaches and you
have to be cautious all day.''
</P>
<P>
   A view atop Olympus
</P>
<P>
   Paul Kennedy grew up in Natick, Mass., and attended Xaverian
High School and Nichols College, beginning a journey that today
finds him general manager of the Olympic Club. He worked at the
Lighthouse Inn in West Dennis when he was in college, landed a
position at the Wigwam Resort in Phoenix for seven years, and now
is in his 10th year presiding over the West Coast's most noted
athletic/golf complex. The US Open, of course, is its major event.
``The set-up began a year ago,'' said Kennedy. ``Now, it's just
finally, `Get out of its way and let it happen.' There are
financial benefits to the club, but the club's a strong believer in
giving back to the game.'' The affiliated athletic club downtown is
sponsoring four athletes for the US Olympic team _ a decathlete, a
cyclist, a javelin thrower, and a water polo player. ``That's what
the club's about,'' said Kennedy. ``Taking care of the amateur
athlete.'' ... Ryder Cup fever continues to heat up. The PGA of
America reports that more than 30,000 ticket applications from 12
countries and all 50 states have been received in the first week.
Entries will be accepted through Aug. 31, and a random drawing will
be conducted in September. The public can apply via the Internet at
www.pga.com or by calling 1-888-RYDER CUP between 10 a.m. and 9
p.m. There is a nonrefundable $5 application fee and a maximum
number of two tickets per person available ... Geoff Sisk will
defend his title in the 89th Massachusetts Open, which begins its
three-day run Monday at Oak Hill CC. He's one of 10 former winners
in the field of 153 competing for the $12,000 first prize out of a
total purse of $60,000 ... The field for the Willowbend Children's
Pro-Am on June 29 includes 1998 PGA Tour winners Stuart Appleby
(Kemper), Watson (Colonial), and Mark Calcavecchia (Honda), plus
Billy Andrade, Craig Stadler, Tom Kite, Scott Hoch, Frank Nobilo,
and Brad Faxon.
</P>
<P>
   Up a tree
</P>
<P>
   Paul Simson, who is vice president of an insurance company in
Raleigh, N.C., and became a reinstated amateur in 1978, had a bit
of an adventure in his opening round of 76. He lost a ball in a
tree on the 10th hole and went with son/caddie Phil to look for it.
``We were climbing up in the tree and found seven or eight balls
that were lodged up there,'' said Simson, who had to return to the
tee with a one-stroke penalty, and ended up with a triple bogey on
the par-4 hole. Two spectators said they saw somebody pick up his
ball when it bounced out of the tree and into heavy rough. But once
Simson played the provisional ball, no adjustments could be made
... The consensus after the USGA's press conference Wednesday
regarding the ``material and construction of a club face'' was that
it was much ado about very little. The USGA backed off on declaring
some clubs illegal and thus avoided possible litigation from
equipment manufacturers. ``All clubs have some springlike effect,
because all clubs deform at impact,'' said USGA executive director
David Fay. ``Two questions need to be answered. No. 1, can the
concept of springlike effect be clearly defined? No. 2, assuming it
can, should there be a limit of springlike effect in a golf club?
The intent of the rule is clear, but the current language in the
rule book requires clarification. We recently developed a test that
can measure in terms of velocity the springlike effect in club
heads. We expect to release the particulars of this proposed test
protocol to manufacturers within the next few weeks. The test
itself will be based on the rebound velocity of a golf ball off a
club face. Golf constantly evolves. We have a responsibility to all
who are involved to set clearly defined, clearly understood
standards that anticipate emerging technology and maintain the
fundamental challenge of the game.'' Play away, please.
</P>
</TEXT>
