<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-NOTES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW PLAY FOR KASPER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients) 
By Kevin Paul Dupont 
c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Steve Kasper will be at the NHL entry draft Saturday in Buffalo,
but with a different perspective this time. He's been there both as
a player (drafted 81st overall by the Bruins in 1980) and a coach
(most recently in 1996, when he was about to enter his second year
behind the Boston bench).
</P>
<P>
   This time he'll be there as Kasper Sports Management
International. Once one of the most dogged checkers in the game,
the 35-year-old Kasper is now an agent, certified last month with
the NHL Players' Association and already with his first player
signed to an NHL contract.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe part of it relates to my coaching experience,'' said
Kasper, asked what he likes about his new career, which he launched
one year after being dismissed as the Bruins' bench boss. ``I like
the idea of controlling what I'm doing and answering to myself.
That's a very good feeling.''
</P>
<P>
   Michigan Tech forward Andre Savage, recently signed by the
Bruins as a free agent, became Kasper's first client. Savage was
referred to Kasper by Tech coach Tim Watters, who spent a season
with Kasper in Boston before departing for the college ranks.
</P>
<P>
   Kasper fired out a Savage highlight film to all 27 NHL
franchises, followed up, and found that Boston had the most
interest. When the deal got done, it was Kasper sitting across the
desk from Harry Sinden, the man who drafted him as an 18-year-old,
then hired him as Boston's head coach 15 years later, then sent him
packing last spring.
</P>
<P>
   ``Getting dismissed is part of the game,'' said Kasper, asked if
it felt awkward to deal with Sinden only a year after being
cashiered. ``I've said all along, I'm content with what I did in my
time coaching the Bruins. As far as dealing with Harry goes, well,
he's always dealt with me with respect, and it's not as if I've
been a total stranger around (the FleetCenter). I saw a lot of
games there last year. I've been around.''
</P>
<P>
   Upon being dismissed, Kasper could have joined the Bruins' front
office but elected to look elsewhere. Last summer, he interviewed
for broadcast openings here in Boston and also talked with the
Ducks about their head coaching vacancy, a job that opened again
last week when Pierre Page was fired.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, I could have stayed part of it,'' said Kasper. ``But you
know, I really don't want to get into that. It was an opportunity
that I could have stayed involved ... but I just thought at this
time it's better for Steve Kasper to go on his own.
</P>
<P>
   ``And I'm happy to do what I'm doing. It's hard work. It's very
competitive, but everything is in today's world. It wasn't as if
coaching was a lifelong dream of mine. But an opportunity was
presented to me, I took advantage of it, and I did enjoy it. I
still love the game, and I want to be a part of it, and this is one
way I might be able to help someone along the way.''
</P>
<P>
   The winning formula
</P>
<P>
   No one's asking, but if I were looking to get a franchise off
the ground, I'd find the right paperwork-and-detail guy to go with
Scotty Bowman, then just hand the whole thing over to them. Then
check back in no less than three years and see if that team hasn't
made it to at least the conference finals. In the meantime, Bowman
is under contract to work the Detroit bench for one more season,
but as of late last week he hadn't made up his mind for '98-99. He
was hinting heavily after the Game 4 clincher vs. the Capitals that
it could be time to retire ... The Bruins are contemplating a
change in starting times for weeknight games, from 7:30 to 7 p.m.
Season ticket-holders, recently mailed their renewal forms, were
asked their opinion. Initial returns show nearly a 2-to-1 vote in
favor of dropping the puck earlier. If it remains that positive,
the change will be made. The Canadiens are moving up a half-hour
next season. The Penguins, after switching to 7 p.m. last year, are
going back to 7:30 ... Business has been brisk in the Bruins'
season-ticket office, where orders have been written for more than
800 new sales (42 home dates). Among the hottest summer sellers:
the back four rows of Sections 307-310, the end where the Bruins
shoot twice per game. One seat to all 42 games sells for $630,
about the economic equivalent of a five-cent cigar by today's
standards ... Brian Burke remains on the job as NHL vice president
in charge of almost everything, especially the dirty work of fines
and suspensions, but he is expected to leave this offseason for a
GM's job, possibly as early as Monday, when, according to one
rumor, he will get the Vancouver job ... A New York Post report
during the Stanley Cup finals had Burke being replaced by former
Ranger coach Colin Campbell, who is still being paid by New York
... Nice break Steve Shields got Friday, being traded to San Jose.
The former Michigan netminder spent the last two seasons as Dominik
Hasek's understudy, rarely seeing the ice other than from the
bench, and now he'll have a chance to be a bona fide No. 1 with the
Sharks. He's big (6 feet 3 inches, 210 pounds), and he showed in
last year's playoffs, when Hasek got hurt in the opening round vs.
the Senators, that he can do the job ... NHL GMs recognized a real
need to improve the game last week when they recommended a variety
of rule changes, including phasing in two referees, moving the nets
another 2 feet off the rear boards, and shaving the sides off the
shaded crease area that has triggered infractions and nullified
goals (hello, Tim Taylor). The Board of Governors is expected to
rubber-stamp the recommendations in Toronto Thursday morning, prior
to the annual awards ceremonies that night.
</P>
<P>
   Brotherly shove
</P>
<P>
   If the Mighty Ducks have even the slightest clue that they know
what they're doing, they're keeping it one of the Original
Twentysomething's best-kept secrets. They drummed Page out of town
on Monday, less than a year after naming him as Ron Wilson's
replacement. Not to be melodramatic, said Ferreira, but he looks at
Page as a brother. Now there's family for you. No replacement yet,
but round up the usual suspects: Ted Nolan, Marc Crawford, Jacques
Lemaire, et al (one day the league will construct a giant recycling
bin for these guys on the sidewalk outside league HQs in
Manhattan). Meanwhile, Ferreira will scale back on his duties
considerably, with much of the detail work to be handled by David
McNab (brother of former Bruin Peter McNab), who had a shot to
become Atlanta's GM until the Ducks withdrew permission for him to
negotiate with the slow-to-decide Thrashers ... The Blackhawks
haven't named a coach to replace Craig Hartsburg yet, but GM Bob
Murray recently said he has completed interviews, and Crawford was
not on the talk-to list. ESPN's Barry Melrose remains a contender,
but not as much as he would make it sound ... Rumor had the Devils
trading ex-US Olympian Mike Dunham, Martin Brodeur's backup at Exit
16W, to the Oilers on Thursday, but the deal didn't get done. The
Devils could lose him for nothing in Friday's expansion draft at
Buffalo that will stock Nashville. The Oilers, with Curtis Joseph
about to depart, could use Dunham ... Rather than lose ex-Bruin
netminder Andy Moog to Nashville, the Canadiens might send some
minor league bodies to the Predators as compensation for passing on
Moog. Moog is on record as saying he would retire rather than go to
an expansion club, but he is under contract with the Habs, at a
price of $2 million, for next season. There aren't many who would
walk from that kind of cash ... Five goals in 35 games for the
Devils and offseason surgery to repair nerve damage in his right
wrist. Jason Arnott may be a young, talented Group 2 free agent,
but bad numbers and a bad wrist are going to make it difficult to
reach into GM Lou Lamoriello's pocket. Arnott worked for $1.8
million last year and would expect a bump to at least $2.5 million,
perhaps more on a long-term deal. This is one that has ``holdout''
written all over it, unless the Devils move him this summer ...
Ex-Bruin Eddie Westfall won't be a regular in the Islanders'
broadcast booth next season, supplanted after 19 years by a
broadcaster to be named later. No. 18 will contribute pregame
features and reports, but a new partner will be found for
play-by-play man Howie Rose ... Crawford is free to sign on
anywhere as coach next season, following mediation last week
between the coach and his former employer, the Avalanche. Depending
on how Crawford's new club does next season _ presuming he gets
hired _ Colorado will end up with either a first- or second-round
pick in the '99 draft.
</P>
<P>
   The next Mario?
</P>
<P>
   The Lightning will take Rimouski (Quebec League) center Vincent
Lecavalier in Saturday's entry draft. He's 6-4, French-Canadian,
and rated No. 1 in North America by Central Scouting _ ergo the
comparisons to Mario Lemieux, who was all of that and more entering
the 18-year-old draft in '84. Colorado owns four first-round picks,
including Boston's, and likely will try to swap all of them for the
right to take Lecavalier, who just so happens to be represented by
Bob Sauve, former partner in the agent business with Pierre
Lacroix, now the Avalanche GM (sometimes it seems like the same
10-12 guys run the entire hockey business). Colorado has the Nos.
12, 17, 19, and 20 picks to offer; if someone had given the
Penguins that for Lemieux in '84, here's what it would have netted:
Gary Roberts (12, Calgary), Kevin Hatcher (17, Washington), Dave
Pasin (19, Boston) and Duncan MacPherson (20, NY Islanders). Forget
it ... July 1 marks NHL free agency. You may be surprised to learn
that former Bruin Geoff Courtnall, who earned $2.5 million in St.
Louis last year, will enter the pool as the group's biggest goal
scorer from 1997-98 (31). Since departing Boston in the swap for
Moog, the now 35-year-old left winger has broken 40 goals once and
30 goals four times. Courtnall joined the Blues as a free agent in
the summer of '95, signing a three-year deal valued at $6.8 million
... Hmm. The Chelioses of Chicago invited the Hulls of St. Louis to
the NBA Finals. They were USA teammates at Nagano. More and more it
appears they'll be teammates in Chicago. Hull remains adamant about
a three-year, $15 million, no-trade contract from the Blues, and
they're not ponying up the third-year guarantee ... Kings coach
Larry Robinson was unimpressed by former Bruin Jozef Stumpel down
the stretch drive, with Stumpel scoring only 2 goals in the final
21 regular-season games and going 1-2_3 in the four-game playoff
flop vs. the Blues. Robinson to the Long Beach Press-Telegram: ``I
don't think he played like a No. 1 center in the playoffs. He did
all year, but when it came to crunch time, when they were putting
two or three guys on him, I don't think he did it consistently.''
Stumpel will make $1.65 million next season ... Hard-shooting
defenseman Vladimir Malakhov, his neck too sore for him to suit up
against Buffalo in what proved the Habs' elimination game, recently
saw Montreal take a three-year, $7.5 million offer off the table.
The offer was made during the regular season, well before Malakhov
pulled the 'chute vs. the Sabres. It all adds up to Malakhov
getting moved ... Now that John Muckler has hired Keith Acton as an
assistant coach with the Rangers, don't be surprised to see
ex-Oiler Charlie Huddy join the staff. Huddy most recently has been
head coach in Huntington, W.Va., in the ECHL ... The Lightning
picked up Bill Ranford from Washington, thinking they'll expose the
oft-injured Daren Puppa in the expansion draft. One problem: If no
one takes Puppa, the Bolts will have to write checks for both
Ranford and Puppa next season, a total of $5.3 million. And no one
knows for sure whether Ranford or Puppa can be a No. 1 netminder. A
shaky start for the Bolts' new ownership.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
