<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-NOTES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEL VALLE A DREAMER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients) 
By Ron Borges 
c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Lou Del Valle believes he knows what's coming next month when he
fights perhaps the best boxer in the world.
</P>
<P>
   So does everyone else.
</P>
<P>
   Lou Del Valle believes what's coming is a beating.
</P>
<P>
   So does everyone else.
</P>
<P>
   So we're all in agreement then about the future of the World
Boxing Association light heavywight champion, who will try to unify
the title July 18 against World Boxing Council titleholder Roy
Jones Jr?
</P>
<P>
   Well, not exacatly.
</P>
<P>
   Lou Del Valle thinks he's going to be on the upside of that
beating.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone else thinks he's going to play a role similar to that
of the snare drum in The Ringo Starr Story.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Jones's previous 36 victims, Del Valle believes he has an
edge because once he was paid to be punched around by Jones. But
Jones's former sparring partner argued that this will not be a
sparring session like the 38 rounds they once shared in 1995. This
will be a fight, not a farce.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always knew it was going to happen,'' Del Valle said last
week at a press conference in New York called by HBO to announce
that the fight had finally been made after much political
maneuvering between Del Valle's promoter, Cedric Kushner, and the
WBA, which threatened to block Del Valle's biggest payday by
forcing him to make a mandatory defense against an unknown
challenger of its own choosing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm the type of person that goes to bed and dreams. I always
dream about certain fights and they always happen. I have that
power.''
</P>
<P>
   Most people in boxing will argue that this is no dream.
</P>
<P>
   But Del Valle is not most people. He's a guy who has grown used
to the underdog's role, having played it in all of his biggest
fights. When he first won the title, Del Valle had to journey to
Aachen, Germany, to face undefeated European champion Eddy
Smulders. Knowing he had no chance of winning a decision in such a
place, Del Valle (27-1, 19 KOs) stopped Smulders in the eighth
round, something few experts thought likely.
</P>
<P>
   Del Valle had learned about winning the hard way when he first
fought for the WBA title a year earlier when, despite bloodying and
dropping champion Virgil Hill in Hill's hometown of Bismarck, N.D.,
he lost a close, controversial decision. Or so the judges said.
</P>
<P>
   With those experiences behind him, Del Valle seemed to feel no
trepidation coming to New York to fight Jones. He sees it as an
opportunity for the former pupil to show his teacher what he's
learned since they last studied together.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I figured him out more than he figured me out,'' Del
Valle contended. ``I really believe I gave him problems the whole
camp.''
</P>
<P>
   If so, Jones (36-1, 31 KOs) didn't notice. He believes Del Valle
has yet to understand the meaning of the word ``problems.'
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like (A) he wasn't winning the sparring and (B) I'm
different when I'm mad,'' Jones insisted. ``I'm totally different
when there's a crowd around. I'm not near as fast when I spar. I'm
not near as dangerous. When I spar, I don't have that killer
instinct. So this will be totally different.''
</P>
<P>
   The implication is it will also be painful for Del Valle, who
Jones pointed out never mentioned to him that he'd want to fight
Jones one day. Jones seemed miffed at that, giving the very strong
impression he'd have more to say about it July 18.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he told me from Day 1 that one day he wanted to fight me, I
would have still sparred with him,'' Jones said. ``I would have
still tried to help him. But at least I would have known where he
was coming from. Instead, he played it cool. He laid low until the
time came to say, `I want Roy Jones.' I can't respect that.
</P>
<P>
   ``He doesn't know enough to beat me.''
</P>
<P>
   As the teacher was saying those words, the pupil was in the
corner.
</P>
<P>
   Smiling.
</P>
<P>
   If Lou Del Valle is still able to do that come July 19, no one
will be more surprised about it than Roy Jones Jr.
</P>
<P>
   Short jabs
</P>
<P>
   Jones's friend and stablemate Derrick ``Smoke'' Gainer (23-4)
will highlight the undercard in a rematch with former champion
Kevin Kelley (48-2-2). Kelley stopped Gainer in 1995 in a thrilling
contest in which Kelley went down once and Gainer twice until
Gainer was finally counted out in the eighth round. Gainer would
have talked about that fight at the press conference but he missed
the private flight Jones booked from Pensacola. The Champ waits for
no one ... This is the second time Jones has bailed out HBO on
short notice. When the Ike Quartey-Pernell Whitaker fight fell out,
he stepped in and fought Hill on short notice and destroyed him.
This time it was a bout between Naseem Hamed and Kennedy McKinney
that went away when Hamed decided he didn't want to fight until
October. Jones has been playing basketball with a semi-pro team in
Jacksonville and filming a small role in a movie called ``New
Jersey Turnpike,'' about the days of the American Basketball
Association, but he agreed to go back into training to fight Del
Valle ... Jones's apparent change in attitude toward his chosen
profession became clear to HBO when he asked HBO Sports CEO Seth
Abraham if he could fight again in December if he defeats Del Valle
... Oscar De La Hoya says his Sept. 18 rematch with Julio Cesar
Chavez in Las Vegas came about at his insistence. Although no one
gives Chavez a chance to defeat De La Hoya, the young champion has
grown tired of hearing his former idol make lame excuses for why De
La Hoya left him beaten and bloody in their first meeting. ``Chavez
is personal,'' De La Hoya explained. ``That is my fight. He never
gave me the respect I deserved, so now I want to be the first to
knock him out. I'm very disappointed in the way he acted, making
excuses. A lot of people are finding out the real Chavez. It's
terrible to find out my childhood idol is the way he is. I want to
punish him, actually. There'll be no more excuses for him.'' ... De
La Hoya claims his most dangerous opponent at 147 pounds is Jose
Luis Lopez, who so dominated De La Hoya's scheduled Nov. 11
opponent, Yory Boy Campas, that Campas moved up to 154 pounds to
get away from him. ``Lopez has fast hands and a good chin and he's
very powerful,'' De La Hoya said. ``He can really take a punch and
he's got the conditioning, too. I think he's the most dangerous
opponent for me in the welterweight division.'' After much trying,
Lou Duva and Shelley Finkel have convinced Lopez (41-3-2, 32 KOs)
to sign a partnership deal. He now wll be co-managed by Finkel,
Duva, and Rene Martinez. Wonder how that came about ...
Negotiations are being explored once again to try to make an
Evander Holyfield-Lennox Lewis heavyweight title unification fight
in the wake of the cancellation of Holyfield's bout with Henry
Akinwande. The most immediate consequence of that cancellation was
that HBO withdrew it's six-fight, $30 million contract extension
offer to Lewis when he didn't sign it by the June 6 deadline.
Abraham now says he's ``revisiting the landscape. We didn't want to
leave that deal on the table while we're figuring out what to do
next. We wanted to think about whether Holyfield-Lewis can be made
and then decide how to proceed. My father-in-law, Meyer Rubenstein,
is 76. He's a used-machinery dealer. He always told me, `Time heals
all wounds but time wounds all deals.''' Those words had an ominous
ring for Lewis, who may have blown easy money by not signing the
extension.
</P>
<P>
   Around and around
</P>
<P>
   Hot young prospect Fernando Vargas (12-0, 12 KOs) faces
world-rated veteran Anthony Stephens (29-9-2, 17 KOs) Tuesday night
at the legendary Blue Horizon in Philadelphia in his first main
event. Underneath him on the USA Network card is old Olympic
teammate and rival Antonio Tarver. Word is Tarver (9-0, 7 KOs) was
irate to learn that his promoter, Philly's J. Russell Peltz, put
Vargas in as the main event ahead of him. Tarver will face a tough
test from Jose Luis Rivera (15-1, 12 KOs) ... Arturo Gatti (29-2,
20 KOs) returns to the ring Aug. 22 on HBO's ``Boxing After Dark''
against Ivan Robinson, who had been set to fight International
Boxing Federation lightweight champion Shane Mosley later this
month until a cut postponed the bout ... Last Saturday was a bad
night not only for WBC light-weight champion Stevie Johnston but
also for Mosley. The two had hoped to set up a lucrative (for
lightweights, at least) unification match on HBO but Johnston was
upset by Cesar Bazan ... The WBA has given the Acaries brothers 30
days to reschedule a postponed May 16 title fight between Quartey
and Andrei Pastriev. The brothers claim Quartey refused to sign the
contract for the fight in an attempt to get out of his own deal
with them. Quartey's allies claim the Acarieses won a purse bid for
the bout with no intention of putting it on or paying Quartey the
75 percent of the bid required by WBA regulations.
</P>
<P>
   Local bleatings
</P>
<P>
   Don King filed a $100 million lawsuit against Bob Arum last week
trying to block Chavez's bout with Ken Sigurani at Foxwoods
Thursday. King claims he has a valid contract with Chavez and that
Arum paid Chavez to breach it. This is King's second attempt at
blocking the bout. Meanwhile, Arum has promised Chavez a $250,000
bonus if he can knock out Sigurani in that bout, which is
underneath Buster Douglas-Lou Savarese. The aging Chavez (100-2-2,
83 KOs) is facing a kid who is 22-1 but with no punch, as evidenced
by his eight KOs ... Malden mid-dleweight Dana Rosenblatt was a big
hit at the Carnegie Deli in New York last week. Arum took him there
to promote Rosenblatt's appearance vs. Arthur Allen underneath
Douglas-Savarese. Word is, however, that Rosenblatt ate little of
his pastrami on rye and matzo soup, weight being of bigger concern
to him than a meal ... Friday night, the Boxing Scholarship
Foundation will present the first ``Friday Fight Night at the
Woburn Elks Club'' to help raise funds. The night of amateur boxing
will feature three bouts with senior competitors (over 40) in
addition to a full amateur card. For ticket information, call
Boston Sport Boxing Club at 781-938-8785 or 617-354-3434 ... The
July 12 card at Cape Cod Melody Tent in Hyannis is still on, but
the headliners will be changed. Both Joey DeGrandis and Vernon
Forrest had to withdraw, DeGrandis because of a persistent elbow
problem and Forrest because of sore ribs. Zab Judah, a recent
victor over Lowell's Mickey Ward for the US Boxing Association
junior welterweight title, replaces Forrest in the main event ...
Promoter Jimmy Burchfield has a showdown planned Friday night at
Rhodes-on-the-Pawtuxet in Cranston, R.I., when he pits New England
cruiserweight champion Arthur Saribekian (18-4-1) vs. John
Rainwarter (8-1) in a rematch. Sarbekian Saribekian won a decision
in their first meeting last Oct. 23. For ticket info, call
401-724-2253 ... Worcester's Jose Rivera will fight Vargas Aug. 22
in Atlantic City underneath Gatti and his as-yet-unnamed opponent
... Old friend of boxing Danny Wambolt of Halifax will be inducted
into the World Boxing Hall of Fame in Los Angeles Oct. 18.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
