<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CASSCOL21-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DIPLOMACY NEEDS TO BE BIG WINNER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID CASSTEVENS  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LYON, France _ In simpler times, a demonstration was what a
door-to-door vacuum cleaner salesman offered to give the lady of
the house.
</P>
<P>
   Demonstrations are something else in politics, and soccer. Like
a French braid, the two are entwined.
</P>
<P>
   Iran plays the United States today in the ``Coupe du Monde,'' as
the hosts like to say. If the Americans win, they will breathe a
sigh of relief. If Iran wins, it's party time.
</P>
<P>
   In Tehran, there would be dancing, singing, weeping. The
explosion of national pride might rival the scene that erupted in
November after Iran, playing in Melbourne, Australia, qualified for
the World Cup for the first time in 20 years. In a passionate
outpouring, 2 million citizens _ including 5,000 women who ignored
police instructions to stay home _ filled the streets. Women ripped
off their government-mandated veils. When the team returned home,
Iranians welcomed them, packing 120,000-seat Azadi stadium.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. team, of course, hopes to prevent a day (or days) of
rapturous glee.
</P>
<P>
   In this regard, Coach Steve Sampson might confer with the famous
American diplomat and motivationalist, Charles Barkley. Before Game
5 of the 1993 NBA Finals, the Phoenix Suns faced elimination.
Chicago police braced for a rowdy celebration. The Bulls won the
title, but lost Game 5, at home, the night Barkley wrote the
playful pre-game message _ ``SAVE THE CITY!'' on the Suns
chalkboard.
</P>
<P>
   Iran vs. the USA is bigger, of course.
</P>
<P>
   This is more than a game of kickball. After two decades of
hostilities between Iran and the West, President Clinton expressed
his hope for a ``genuine reconciliation'' with Tehran. So did
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright. Perhaps one step toward that
goal can be achieved through sportsmanship and soccer diplomacy.
</P>
<P>
   Few Iranian players appear to regard the American team as an
emissary of the Great Satan. Their coach, Jalal Talebi, spent 17
years in the United States. A kind, soft-spoken man, Talebi
sometimes answers even Persian questions in fluent English. He
would make an excellent ambassador.
</P>
<P>
   Most American players are too young to remember the hostage
crisis in Iran almost 20 years ago. To a man, they repeat the
it's-just-another-big-game quote, and downplay the political
overtones.
</P>
<P>
   Last week a French television channel screened ``Not Without My
Daughter,'' a true-story film about an American woman's attempt to
reclaim her daughter from her cruel Iranian husband. Iran's
ambassador to French became overheated and threatened to take the
team home. One Iranian player, Ali Reza Mansourian, claimed the
film had ``weakened the morale of the Iranian soccer players.''
</P>
<P>
   Team USA's reaction? Alexei Lalas, whose nanny-goat chin
whiskers give him the appearance of a young red-haired Uncle Sam,
said, ``It's just a ``movie,'' man.''
</P>
<P>
   But this is isn't just the next game. The world's most popular
sporting event has given Iran a major place on an international
stage for the first time since the revolution led by Ayatollah
Khomenei overthrew the Shah in 1979.
</P>
<P>
   Iranians have the opportunity to show themselves as sportsmen
and fans, not as terrorists and religious fanatics, which is how
they are perceived in the West.
</P>
<P>
   How the teams conduct themselves on the field will be worth
watching, and millions will. With both countries facing certain
elimination in the first round if they lose, the contest will not
be a ``friendly,'' the soccer term for exhibition matches.
</P>
<P>
   Sampson has demanded his team play more aggressively than it did
in a 2-0 loss to Germany. ``We have to attack and defend, and
attack with vigor,'' he said, sounding like a military man. The
match, he predicted, will be fierce, physical.
</P>
<P>
   To insure impartiality, the game will be officiated by a Swiss
referee.
</P>
<P>
   Iran was the last team to qualify for the World Cup. The
Iranians don't have the size or speed or skills of the German team.
The U.S. expects to win. ``We ``have'' to win,'' Lalas said,
referring not to the politics but the three points awarded for a
victory.
</P>
<P>
   Win, lose or honorable tie, U.S. players plan to shake hands
with the Iranians afterward. Several said they hope to exchange
gifts.
</P>
<P>
   Better T-shirts than arms and hostages. &QL; 
David Casstevens can be reached at david.casstevens(at)pni.com via
e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
