<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-21 12:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9190 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NOTEWORTHY-PAPERBACKS     06-21 0894
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NOTEWORTHY-PAPERBACKS-$ADV28-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW &AMP; NOTEWORTHY PAPERBACKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release on Sunday, June 28.)  
 (HLW)  
 By SCOTT VEALE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; THE ANGEL OF DARKNESS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Caleb Carr. Ballantine, $7.99.
</P>
<P>
   The intrepid child psychologist Laszlo Kreizler and his unusual
coterie of fellow crime fighters are put through their paces again
by the author of `` &UR; THE ALIENIST &LR; ,'' this time to track down a
serial murderer of young children in turn-of-the-century Manhattan.
Last year our reviewer, Ben Macintyre, called this ``a ripping yarn
told with verve, intensity, and a feel for historical detail.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A HISTORY OF THE BREAST &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Marilyn Yalom. Ballantine, $14.95.
</P>
<P>
   This provocative analysis of cultural and artistic attitudes
toward womankind's most symbolically freighted body part explores
the rich array of sacred, maternal, erotic, and political
perceptions of the breast through the centuries. There is a
surprising amount to discuss, from Stone Age artifacts to the
evolution of women's underwear to modern performance art. ``Yalom's
stately romp through history is variously enlightening, amusing,
and enraging,'' Natalie Angier wrote in the Book Review in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; READ THIS AND TELL ME WHAT IT SAYS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   A. Manette Ansay. Bard/Avon, $11.
</P>
<P>
   Set in the rural Midwest, these 15 tales focus on ordinary
people and the modest epiphanies that make give meaning to life.
The stories ``map the distances between ourselves and other
worlds,'' Jonis Agee said here in 1995. ``They remind us of how
necessary our dreams and desires are to the fragile lives we piece
together.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE UNIVERSE BELOW: DISCOVERING THE SECRETS OF THE DEEP SEA &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By William J. Broad. Touchstone/Simon &AMP; Schuster, $15.
</P>
<P>
   The author, a science reporter for The New York Times, combines
personal experience with scientific and historical research to
provide ``a readable and reliable guide'' to deep-sea exploration
and exploitation, John Durant wrote in these pages last year.  &UR; IN
DARWIN'S DREAMPOND: DRAMA IN LAKE VICTORIA &LR; , by Tijs Goldschmidt
(translated by Sherry Marx-Macdonald, MIT, $15), a Dutch fish
taxonomist describes how the introduction of the predatory Nile
perch doomed most of the African lake's dazzling native population.
This literate account ``stands head and shoulders above the
predictable genre of eco-gloomies,'' Mark Ridley said here in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TERMINAL VELOCITY &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Blanche McCrary Boyd. Vintage Contemporaries, $12.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1970s, a prim book editor dumps her heterosexual life in
Boston to take up with a band of radical lesbians in a California
commune called Red Moon Rising. The author of this dizzying novel
about the search for the self has ``a voice that never wavers in
its authority or its fierce sexual politics,'' our reviewer, Andrea
Barnet, wrote in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; JOHN WAYNE'S AMERICA &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Garry Wills. Touchstone/Simon &AMP; Schuster, $14.
</P>
<P>
   A polymath extraordinaire, in deconstructing the symbol of
manhood for generations of Americans in an often unsettling feat of
revisionism, seeks to rescue Wayne from both his idolaters and his
detractors. ``I hope this new book will find its way into the hands
of those who are ready to think seriously about a pivotal figure in
our culture, a figure who was a great star and a flawed man,''
Molly Haskell said last year in these pages.  &UR; LIGHTING OUT FOR THE
TERRITORY: REFLECTIONS ON MARK TWAIN AND AMERICAN CULTURE &LR; , by
Shelley Fisher Fishkin (Oxford, $13.95), maps the literary and
moral legacy of another iconic figure, focusing in particular on
the writer's true feelings about race and slavery. This ``is an
illuminating companion to any consideration of Twain's work,''
David Walton wrote here in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE WHITE CASTLE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Orhan Pamuk. Translated by Victoria Holbrook. Vintage
International, $12.
</P>
<P>
   In a canny metaphysical novel that explores the limits of
identity, an Italian scholar becomes a slave to a scientist in
17th-century Istanbul who appears to be his double. The Turkish
author ``is a storyteller with as much gumption and narrative zip
as Scheherazade,'' Jay Parini said here in 1991. The same publisher
has issued Pamuk's most recent novel,  &UR; THE NEW LIFE &LR;  (translated by
Guneli Gun, $13), in which a young student embarks on a surreal bus
journey with a mysterious woman after being magically transformed
by a book. Last year our reviewer, D.M. Thomas, found the story to
be too disconnected from reality, but called it ``a skillful play
of illusions.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; HOW PROUST CAN CHANGE YOUR LIFE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Alain de Botton. Vintage International, $12.
</P>
<P>
   A clever nine-step program drawing lessons from the life and
literature of Marcel Proust shows how `` &UR; REMEMBRANCE OF THINGS
PAST &LR; '' can make you a better person. The result is an ``enormously
entertaining ... self-help manual for the intelligent person,''
Frank Gannon wrote in the Book Review in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; DANGEROUS ANGELS: THE WEETZIE BAT BOOKS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Francesca Lia Block. Harpercollins, $12.
</P>
<P>
   These five dreamlike fables, which share an offbeat cast of
characters and a freewheeling narrative sprawl, have found a
natural following among young adults. In reviewing the first book,
``Weetzie Bat,'' in 1989, Betsy Hearne said ``the language is
inventive Californian hip, but ... the theme is transcendent.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-21-98 1224EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980621.0035 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
