<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980621.0040 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-21 15:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9265 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BANKRUPTCY-COX &UR;      06-21 1279
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BANKRUPTCY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     BANKRUPTCY REFORM WILL LIKELY FOCUS ON CONSUMER RESPONSIBILITY
</HEADLINE>
     &HT;     DUPLICATION ALERT: Moving in (w) Washington and (f) Financial
categories 
 &HT;     By CHRISTI HARLAN 
 &HT;     c. 1998 Cox News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ By setting aside tobacco legislation that would
have increased costs for smokers, the Senate cleared the way last
week to consider a bill that will raise the ante for people whose
debts are driving them into bankruptcy.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the tobacco debate, which barely touched on smokers'
responsibility for their habits, the debate over tightening
bankruptcy rules is likely to focus on consumers' responsibility
for paying their bills.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time a deadbeat does not pay his bills, that means
working people have to pay more'' for consumer goods, mortgages and
other credit, said Sen. Phil Gramm, R-Texas, who passionately
supports making bankruptcy proceedings more difficult for people
who can pay part of their debts.
</P>
<P>
   Gramm and other reform-minded lawmakers are reacting to
bankruptcy filings that have hit highs not seen since the collapse
of the real estate market and savings &AMP; loans in the last half of
the 1980s. With no similar economic crisis to explain the current
spike in bankruptcy filings, some lawmakers are pointing their
fingers at the debtors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Something is wrong when we have record prosperity and record
numbers of bankruptcy,'' Gramm said.
</P>
<P>
   Consumer advocates, in turn, are pointing fingers at banks and
retailers that are marketing credit cards at unprecedented rates.
University of Texas law professor Jay Westbrook, a bankruptcy law
specialist, prepared for a recent speech in Austin by collecting
eight days' worth of credit offers that he and his wife received in
the mail. The total hit $600,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was stunned,'' said Westbrook, who joined 60 other
bankruptcy law professors in a letter urging Congress to slow its
reform efforts. The professors _ including two from Emory
University; one from Georgia State University; one from Ohio State
University, and one from Florida State University _ don't oppose
bankruptcy reform, but they said ``the study of its consequences
(was) superficial.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Aside from the tax code and the Social Security laws, no other
federal law affects more Americans,'' the letter said. ``We believe
that the current debate is ill-considered, rushed and unbalanced.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the professors' concern, Congress has moved at
uncharacteristic speed to change the rules governing the levels of
relief available to people with crushing debts. The House approved
its package of changes June 10 in a 306-118 vote.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate is expected to take up its version of bankruptcy
reform in mid-July, after a 2 1/2 week recess for the July 4
holiday.
</P>
<P>
   The main goal of both the House and Senate bills is to restrict
debtors' use of a section of the U.S. bankruptcy code known as
Chapter 7, under which individuals and married couples declare an
inability to pay debts and effectively have most of them canceled,
or discharged.
</P>
<P>
   Some personal debts _ such as income taxes, child support,
alimony, student loans and court judgments for fraud or injury to
another person _ are considered priority debts and must be paid in
full under both Chapter 7 and its alternative, Chapter 13.
</P>
<P>
   Under Chapter 13, individuals and couples reorganize their debts
and repay part of them under a plan approved by the bankruptcy
court. Chapter 13 is the personal version of Chapter 11, which is
used by corporations to reorganize debt.
</P>
<P>
   Both forms of personal bankruptcy contain allowances for debtors
to retain some personal property, such as items necessary for
income and, to varying degrees, a home. States traditionally have
set the rules for the value of the personal property and homes.
</P>
<P>
   Some states, such as Texas and Florida, set no limit on the
value of the homestead, which led to headline-grabbing bankruptcy
cases in the late 1980s and early 1990s. One Texas S&AMP;L operator,
for instance, paid $1.17 million cash for a Dallas mansion on the
same day he was indicted for fraud by a federal grand jury. Weeks
later, he filed for bankruptcy, and his home could not be touched
by his creditors.
</P>
<P>
   To counter such abuses, the Senate's bankruptcy reform would set
a national cap of $100,000 for the value of homesteads. A similar
provision in the House bill was removed in a 222-204 vote and
replaced with a rule that prohibits the fraudulent purchase of a
home within one year of filing bankruptcy.
</P>
<P>
   Gramm sees the merit of limiting the value of homesteads _
``when people declare bankruptcy and walk away millionaires,
something needs to be done about it,'' he said _ but he hasn't
decided whether he will support a compromise that his fellow Texas
Republican, Sen. Kay Bailey Hutchison, plans to introduce.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the outcome of the effort to reign in the homestead
provision, other pieces of bankruptcy reform mean big changes for
individual debtors, particularly those whose debts are largely due
to credit-card companies and retailers.
</P>
<P>
   The credit industry has lobbied hard for the legislation, which
would discourage debtors from using Chapter 7 and force more people
into Chapter 13, where at least some debt would be paid down.
</P>
<P>
   ``The current bankruptcy system is flawed,'' said William P.
Binzel, vice president of government relations for MasterCard
International. ``It allows debtors to walk away from their debts
even when they have an ability to repay them.
</P>
<P>
   ``And when debts are discharged in bankruptcy, they just don't
go away,'' he said. ``They get passed on to other consumers in the
form of higher prices and interest rates.''
</P>
<P>
   To push more debtors into Chapter 13, the House and Senate
legislation would set a maximum income level for debtors seeking
Chapter 7 relief: no more than national median income, now about
$51,000 for a family of four. Debtors with higher income would be
required to file under Chapter 13.
</P>
<P>
   The punishment for debtors wrongly filing under Chapter 7 would
fall on their lawyers, who would risk losing their fees if their
clients' assets or income disqualified them from Chapter 7 relief.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's real scary for us attorneys who represent people,'' said
James McMillen, a Corpus Christi lawyer who is secretary of the
National Association of Consumer Bankruptcy Attorneys. ``We're
going to have to send (investigators) to their homes, and we're
still going to miss things that they didn't tell us about.''
</P>
<P>
   The bankruptcy attorneys and consumer advocates are also
disturbed by part of the legislation that would give credit-card
debt a new priority for repayment. Creditors insisted on that
provision, although no more than 1 percent of all credit accounts
end up in bankruptcy, according to lobbyists for both the
credit-card industry and retailers.
</P>
<P>
   ``While it is one percent, what we're seeing increasingly is
double-digit increases in the rate of bankruptcy filings,'' said
MasterCard's Binzel. ``The amount of debts will continue to grow
substantially as well. I have yet to hear a credible argument
promoting a public policy that people should be allowed to walk
away from their debts.''
</P>
<P>
   Westbrook, the bankruptcy-law professor, said Congress and the
credit industry are missing the bigger picture of debt.
</P>
<P>
   ``The same debates have gone on for the hundred years that we've
had a workable bankruptcy system,'' he said. ``There's always a
sense that, well, somehow these people should pay.
</P>
<P>
   ``A free-market system involves casualties,'' he said. ``We just
have to accept that. That's part of the system.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; For use by clients of The New York Times News Service &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
