<DOCNO> NYT19980621.0043 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-21 16:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9317 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-REPORTER-CRAIG-MEDIA-     06-21 0967
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REPORTER-CRAIG-MEDIA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPORTER'S EFFORTS FREE WOMAN IMPRISONED 25 YEARS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By JANE GROSS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROCHESTER, N.Y. _ Robert Redford is not clamoring to star in the
movie. Students are not lining up at journalism schools with hopes
of duplicating his reportorial feats. His name will not appear in
history books for toppling an American president.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Gary Craig's accomplishment at The Rochester Democrat and
Chronicle, helping to free a woman wrongly imprisoned for 25 years
for murder, is comparable in its way to the reporting of Woodward
and Bernstein. Like the onetime Washington Post pair, Craig's labor
ended with a dramatic flourish: Betty Tyson's release. But it began
with tedium: months of dogged, thankless work.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Tyson was a prostitute and a heroin addict, picked up in a
street sweep after the 1973 murder of an out-of-town businessman in
the red-light district. But Craig, 39, knew little about her
background. The fire that burned in him was not an obsession with
Ms. Tyson's freedom. Rather, he wanted to know if a rogue detective
had run amok, beating confessions out of Ms. Tyson and two teen-age
witnesses who said they saw her with the victim. ``I wasn't writing
about Betty Tyson, the person, or Betty Tyson, the inmate,'' Craig
said. ``I was writing about evidence, about the cops, the case.''
</P>
<P>
   The detective in question, since deceased, had been convicted
for fabricating evidence in a case involving six organized-crime
figures. He was also a defendant in civil suits accusing him of
police abuse. Ms. Tyson and her co-defendant, who is still
imprisoned, said during the trial that their confessions were
coerced. But what of the witnesses? There were rumors here that one
of them, Wayne Wright, confided to family members that he lied on
the stand. With no physical evidence against her, Ms. Tyson was
convicted on the strength of that testimony, and similar assertions
by another teen-ager.
</P>
<P>
   Craig had just completed a project about conditions in state
prisons. At the urging of local advocates for Ms. Tyson, he began
this investigation late in 1996 with a thorough reading of police
files and court transcripts, where he found plenty of red flags.
But the most promising avenue was Wright's rumored recantation.
Craig tracked down Wright's relatives, who confirmed he had told
them he lied. But Wright ignored telephone messages and notes left
at his home.
</P>
<P>
   Undaunted, Craig continued to ``nibble away'' at other aspects
of the case. He researched the history of the detective and found
much to support claims of abusive conduct. He tracked down two
counselors who had been at the jail where Ms. Tyson was held after
her 1973 arrest and said she had bruises on her arms and legs. He
also went to the Bedford Hills Correctional Facility in Westchester
County to talk to Ms. Tyson, the only time they met until her
release.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Tyson asked him to take a letter to Wright, begging for the
truth. Only after Craig delivered it did Wright agree to a meeting.
At that lunch, an off-the-record session, Wright said he was trying
to find a way to help her, without jeopardizing himself. From that
day forward, the two men met frequently. Wright had many questions
about the legal implications if he publicly recanted and Craig did
his best to inform him. The reporter also kept Wright abreast of
his other findings, thus reassuring him that the article he had in
mind would be a comprehensive revisiting of the case.
</P>
<P>
   By now, it was the summer of 1997. One day, Craig would tell his
editors, ``I'm close.'' The next day, he would have to beg for more
time. But Craig was confident. ``I felt comfortable waiting for him
to feel comfortable,'' Craig said of Wright. ``And all the waiting
gave us time to build a case on all the other fronts.''
</P>
<P>
   In November, Wright agreed to tell Craig, on the record, that he
had lied on the stand. But he had one lingering reservation. Ms.
Tyson had no lawyer. What good would his recantation do if there
was nobody to file a motion on her behalf? Craig found a local
lawyer to take her case and Wright produced a 15-page affidavit.
</P>
<P>
   Craig's article spanned two full pages of the paper and included
Wright's affidavit, the new evidence from the jail counselors and a
profile of the deceased detective who is believed to have beaten
both the suspects and the witnesses into making false statements.
It took months for Ms. Tyson's new lawyer, Jon Getz, to file a
motion for dismissal, but it was in the hands of the judge in
February of this year.
</P>
<P>
   In anticipation of the discovery process, the Monroe County
district attorney began digging through old files. Among them was a
single sheet of paper that in the end persuaded the judge to
reverse the conviction: a police report, never introduced into
evidence, in which the other witness, Jon Jackson, said he had not
seen the suspect and the victim together.
</P>
<P>
   That report alone, Judge John Connell ruled in May, could have
produced a different verdict. The case could be tried again,
Connell said, but the district attorney decided not to because of
Ms. Tyson's long incarceration and the death of key witnesses. On
May 27, 25 years to the day from her arrest, Betty Tyson was free.
</P>
<P>
   Craig was invited to celebrate with the Tyson family that night.
But in the weeks since, he has spent considerably more time with
Wright, whom he had come to know well during their long
negotiations. And he is back at work in the trenches of Rochester's
courts and police stations, examining several other cases handled,
or mishandled, by the same detective, William Mahoney. ``This has
solidified in my mind the sort of work we should be doing,'' Craig
said. ``But I worry we're doing less of it than we used to.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
