<SLUG> BC-MEDIA-TALK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HAWKING VIDEOCASSETTES  
 PUBLISHER BACK IN THE CLUB  
 BUZZ OVER BELL BOOK  
 NEW LOOK FOR CJR 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Will Barry Diller start making infomercials for NBC? Now that
NBC has begun _or at least tiptoed _ into the business of selling
videocassettes directly to consumers, it might want an outside
company to produce them.
</P>
<P>
   And with Diller at the helm of USA Networks, the parent of the
Home Shopping Network, USA would be a logical choice.
</P>
<P>
   The two companies have had some ``very preliminary''
discussions, as one person close to the talks put it. And though
Diller has declined to comment, he has made no secret of his desire
to use his shopping network's direct-response capabilities for
outside clients.
</P>
<P>
   He is already mapping his plans for USA. The company owns a
Miami television station and plans to experiment with selling
sports clothing in connection with broadcasts of Miami Heat
basketball games.
</P>
<P>
   Then why not produce commercials for NBC if it wants to sell
more home videos? NBC took its first steps in direct marketing on
the network in April when it sold videocassettes of its miniseries
``Merlin'' directly to audiences, using two 30-second spots. In
just one minute it sold 100,000 videocassettes for $29.95 each.
</P>
<P>
   Hawking cassettes may not be as classy as having Nike promote
sneakers. But it is lucrative, and at a time when the networks are
scrambling for more revenue, selling merchandise can be appealing.
</P>
<P>
   With NBC being owned by General Electric, maybe some day the
network could even start selling light bulbs and dishwashers.
</P>
<P>
   Renegade Rejoins Establishment
</P>
<P>
   So the wild cowboy has finally joined the club. After five years
of spurning the Magazine Publishers of America, David Pecker, the
president and chief executive of Hachette Filipacchi Magazines _
which publishes Elle, George and Mirabella _ has rejoined the
industry association.
</P>
<P>
   When Pecker was first starting out in 1990, he was viewed as
something of an outsider because he did things differently _
acquiring magazines like crazy, taking out a full-page ad in large
newspapers to criticize a competitor's ad strategy, unabashedly
going after big advertising contracts and turning his back on the
association in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   But as Pecker has built Hachette, a unit of Lagardere Groupe,
into a successful company over the last eight years and as the
industry has increasingly moved toward Pecker's way of doing
business, Hachette has gradually won its way back into the good
graces of the industry.
</P>
<P>
   The move represents a triumph for the association, which has
been courting Pecker ever since he pulled out. The trade group will
get the benefit of Hachette's annual dues _ magazine companies pay
according to their gross revenues _ as well as the influence of a
company like Hachette, which has gone from 14 titles to 30 and
become the No. 3 magazine company in ad pages, behind Time Inc. and
Conde Nast and ahead of Hearst Magazines.
</P>
<P>
   Pecker said he initially resigned because he did not like the
direction the association was going and thought the dues were not
worth the money. Under Hachette's new arrangement with the
association, the magazine company will pay a total of $400,000 in
dues over the first four years and $400,000 a year after that,
according to a Hachette executive who insisted on anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   Among the few publishing companies that remain outside the
association are Forbes magazine and Wenner Media, which publishes
Rolling Stone.
</P>
<P>
   Pulitzer-Winning Writer Cries Foul
</P>
<P>
   If the Scottish writer James Mackay had been content to publish
his new biography of Alexander Graham Bell in Britain, perhaps
Robert Bruce, a Pulitzer Prize-winning historian, would not have
stirred.
</P>
<P>
   But, as the 74-year-old Bruce put it, Mackay strayed too far
into his ``historical precinct,'' igniting a dispute about
plagiarism that probably will result in the shredding of several
thousand copies of ``Alexander Graham Bell: A Life,'' which was
published this spring by John Wiley &AMP; Sons in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been studying and writing history for 50 years, and I've
never heard of anything like this before,'' said Bruce, the author
of a 1973 biography of Alexander Graham Bell. ``He seems to have
written with a typewriter and a thesaurus.''
</P>
<P>
   Lingua Franca, the academic magazine, and Slate, the online
magazine, have detailed the dispute, which centers on Bruce's
contention that Mackay borrowed his research, structure and
concepts.
</P>
<P>
   The biography was first published in Britain by Mainstream
Publishing, and Wiley bought the rights to publish it in the United
States. Several people close to the situation said an agreement was
circulating among the writers and publishers that would stave off a
lawsuit in exchange for Wiley's agreement to declare the book out
of print and to shred the remaining copies.
</P>
<P>
   Reached in his native Scotland, Mackay said he was
``flabbergasted'' by the contretemps with Bruce, whom he
acknowledges on page 12 of his book. He said he had tried to write
a more general biography of Bell, which was aimed at a much less
academic readership. Mackay sent Bruce a note of apology,
explaining, ``I had absolutely no idea that anything I had done
could be construed as plagiarism.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite their obvious dedication to Alexander Graham Bell's
legacy, neither author has resorted to what seems like an obvious
step to resolve the dispute _ share a phone conversation.
</P>
<P>
   Journalism Review Polishes Its Look
</P>
<P>
   Call it coincidence. On second thought, don't even bother. Even
its editor says The Columbia Journalism Review's decision to jazz
up its look with the July/August issue has something to do with the
fact that Brill's Content came out earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Brill's Content is the first magazine to give The
Columbia Journalism Review _ otherwise known as CJR _ some real
competition. But Marshall Loeb, the Review's editor, said he
welcomed the challenge. ``I think there is enough going on in the
world of media and journalism that there is room for a number of
us,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The changes at the Review are subtle, however. Loeb said the
magazine had been gradually phasing them in for some time. Perhaps
the most drastic shift is the cover design; the magazine will use
the full name Columbia Journalism Review instead of CJR. Loeb said
this was to emphasize that the magazine was about journalism.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Loeb said he had been trying to make the magazine
more reader friendly, with more pictures and graphics, subheads and
entry points and a slightly decreased type size to allow for more
articles.
</P>
<P>
   The Review, which was founded in 1961 and has a circulation of
about 30,000, covers the same terrain as Brill's Content, which is
aiming for a circulation of 500,000. For example, Loeb said the
Review featured a similar article _ albeit, minus a few revelations
_ four months ago about how the press handled coverage of Monica
Lewinsky. What the Review doesn't have is the same sort of buzz.
</P>
</TEXT>
