<SLUG> BC-DANCE-GRAHAM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GRAHAM DANCE COMPANY TO SELL HEADQUARTERS BUILDING
</HEADLINE>
   (ja) 
 By JENNIFER DUNNING   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The board of the Martha Graham Dance Company voted
last week to sell the financially hard-pressed company's
headquarters and school on East 63rd Street in Manhattan. The vote,
on June 16, was unanimous.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will move on to smaller quarters and regroup in a new home,
I know,'' the artistic director of the Graham company, Ron Protas,
said on Friday. ``But to lose this historic building is a
tragedy.'' Graham created dances like ``Acts of Light,'' ``The Rite
of Spring'' and ``Temptations of the Moon'' in the three decades
she worked in the back studio of the odd-shaped little brick
building, which may be demolished. Many of today's dancers and
choreographers, in the United States and abroad, trained at the
school.
</P>
<P>
   Among those who studied and rehearsed in the studios were Rudolf
Nureyev, Mikhail Barsyhnikov, Natalia Makarova, Twyla Tharp, Robert
Wilson, Madonna, and Woody Allen. The studio in which Graham worked
opened out to a small garden next to the building; it provided a
quiet spot for meditation and a place for parties attended by
artists, musicians, film and theater performers and fashion
designers of the day. For many years, a tree grew through the wire
fence around the garden, symbolic, Graham often said, of the
persistence of art.
</P>
<P>
   Proceeds from the sale will be used in part, over a 12-month
period, to resolve outstanding debt and help the company work
toward a negotiated settlement of the building's mortgage. Todd
Dellinger, managing director of the troupe, said that those would
be the first steps in a three-to-four-year plan for the
stabilization and revitalization of the company, which would invest
proceeds from the sale in an endowment and begin a capital campaign
to raise money for a new permanent home.
</P>
<P>
   Dellinger said that the Graham troupe would have to operate for
two years out of minimal rented office and studio space, with a
reduced school enrollment though a full complement of technique
courses. With the company on layoff during this time, emphasis
would also be placed on training future Graham dancers who perform
in the junior company, the Martha Graham Dance Ensemble. The
ensemble will perform June 24-27 at the Marymount Manhattan Theater
in a program that includes several rarely seen dances by Graham.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have worked here to maintain one of the true American art
forms of the 20th century, created by the person Time magazine
deemed `Dancer of the Century' just a few weeks back,'' Dellinger
said. ``This is the home of such a glorious artistic tradition for
this country. You'd think that someone would have wanted to make
sure it stayed that way.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
