<HEADER>
A9327 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TAX-REFORM-ART-2TAKES     06-21 1059
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TAX-REFORM-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR THE FUTURE OF TAX COLLECTION, LOOK TO KANSAS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: La., Va., Maine, Mont.)  (ART ADV: A graphic is being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204.) 
(mk) 
 By DAVID CAY JOHNSTON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOPEKA, Kan. _ The new way that taxes are collected in this
Midwest state capital may offer taxpayers everywhere a glimpse of
what the future may be like in dealing with the IRS.
</P>
<P>
   Consider the taxpayer from Great Bend who recently called the
Kansas Department of Revenue to inquire about his state income tax
refund, which was weeks overdue. John Waldo, whose title is
customer representative, asked for the caller's Social Security
number and typed it into his computer. Instantly his screen filled
with both an image of the caller's tax return and a summary report
showing that the Post Office had returned the refund check because
the taxpayer had moved.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's your new address?'' asked Waldo, who then typed it in
and promised the caller that his check would go out the next
morning. Solving the taxpayer's problem took less than a minute
because Kansas has applied modern information technology and a
customer-service attitude to the time-dishonored task of processing
income tax returns, creating an operation that resembles the
billing system of a credit card company.
</P>
<P>
   Paper tax returns are now fed into Kodak scanners that create an
image from which custom character-recognition software extracts
information identifying the taxpayer and the numbers on the return
and feeds it into a central database. The system allows quick
access to each taxpayer's records. It also creates a storehouse of
data on all taxpayers that will help flag returns for possible
audit and uncover patterns, especially in sales tax remittances,
that suggest cheating.
</P>
<P>
   So remarkable is the Kansas system _ even to other tax
collectors _ that in New Orleans on June 16 the Federation of Tax
Administrators, the organization for state tax agencies, will give
Kansas two awards at its annual meeting.
</P>
<P>
   And the changes adopted by Kansas may become relevant for all
the nation's taxpayers _ oops, customers _ because the techniques
are strikingly similar to ones outlined by Charles Rossotti, the
businessman whom President Clinton made IRS commissioner last year
with orders to modernize the service.
</P>
<P>
   The similarities are no coincidence: The prime contractor
building the Kansas tax system is American Management Systems of
Fairfax, Va., where Rossotti was chief executive until last fall.
(As the largest individual shareholder in American Management
Systems, Rossotti will be required by federal ethics rules to hand
over all decision-making authority on the contracts if the company
ends up bidding to build a new computer operation for the IRS).
</P>
<P>
   In contrast to Kansas' new integrated system, which started to
be phased in last year and will be completely operational by the
fall of 1999, the current federal IRS operation is scattered across
some 50 disparate computer systems _ most of which cannot
communicate with one another and some of which date to the era when
Elvis Presley was not only alive but thin. No wonder that a federal
taxpayer with even a minor problem with the IRS can get lost in the
cybervoid among these computer systems, one of which may be
acknowledging receipt of taxes at the same time another is issuing
demands for payment.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas, like most states, used to operate pretty much a
miniature version of the federal tax collection system. Like the
IRS, its tax agency was ruled by policies conceived in what some
critics say was an official attitude that all taxpayers are out to
cheat the government and must never be trusted.
</P>
<P>
   But that is not the policy in Kansas anymore _ especially not
since John LaFaver, who had been tax commissioner in Maine and
Montana, became the Kansas tax commissioner three years ago.
LaFaver set to work shifting the tax department's culture from one
that hunted for every last dime of revenue, especially from
corporations, to a culture built around service and making
compliance with the tax laws easier. (As part of the new service
philosophy, every law, regulation and policy that the Kansas
Department of Revenue uses _ some 7,400 documents _ is posted at
www.ink.org/public/kdor on the World Wide Web.)
</P>
<P>
   LaFaver said the new policy was based on ``an assumption that
most people are honest and trying to pay their taxes and our job is
to help them.'' And there is pragmatism behind the politesse. ``If
we succeed, we will bring in more revenue,'' LaFaver said,
``because compliance will improve.''
</P>
<P>
   To distinguish between taxpayers who comply and those who need
to be closely watched, the system employs an extensive database. If
a business is due to remit its quarterly taxes on a Monday, for
example, but does not meet the deadline, the new system
automatically interrogates the database.
</P>
<P>
   If the business has a history of paying on time, the computer
sends the taxpayer a notice and then schedules itself for an
automatic review, assigning taxpayers with good payment histories
to an escalating schedule of notices, telephone calls and
ultimately collection efforts that span eight months, if required.
For the most chronically delinquent taxpayers, that schedule is
accelerated to four months.
</P>
<P>
   To a large degree, the changes in Kansas involve a shift in risk
from the taxpayer to the government. Consider the hypothetical case
of a taxpayer who earned $14,000 last year and properly reported it
on his tax return, but then received an audit notice that a hefty
sum in taxes, penalties and interest was due on income of $114,000.
That kind of mistake can easily occur at the IRS, where thousands
of clerks manually punch into computers the numbers listed on tax
returns.
</P>
<P>
   And it used to occur in Kansas. Nadine Cloud, a customer
representative, said that under the old system a taxpayer who
called with such a problem faced long delays _ while demands for
payment continued to go out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now you get the taxpayer's Social Security number and, boom,
you get the image of their return and see the mistake,'' she said.
``You can fix it immediately.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The new system has not always worked so smoothly. Last year,
when it was new, the scanners misread so many names and numbers
that tax returns were delayed up to three weeks. But the problem
was solved, and this year's refunds were issued faster than in
1996, the last year under the manual system. Refunds now go into
the mail seven to 10 days after returns are received, said Karla
Pierce, the official supervising the transition to the new system.
</P>
<P>
   To the state, the greatest benefit is the ability to perform
intense statistical analysis of income and sales tax returns to
hunt for those who chisel and cheat, and to reduce the number of
audits of people who do not (and whose audits produce little or no
additional revenue).
</P>
<P>
   The state is also pushing to get more people to file
electronically. One in five did so last year, and LaFaver expects
two-thirds to do so three years from now.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas lawmakers approved the makeover plan after being
convinced that the costs _ a modest $75 million or so _ could be
paid for from new revenues generated as a more efficient
tax-processing system inexpensively identified people and companies
who were not paying, or not fully paying, their taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Fixing the IRS, of course, will be a much more daunting task
than the five-year project here. Kansas collects $4.6 billion in
taxes annually, or roughly what the IRS takes in as a daily
average.
</P>
<P>
   The IRS will also have to deal with a variety of taxpaying
cultures compared with Kansas, where taxpayers are generally so
compliant that even their federal returns are audited by the IRS at
only about two-thirds the average rate for the nation as a whole.
</P>
<P>
   But while the IRS has policy walls intended to make sure no one
gets a dollar back that is not deserved, Kansas officials have
decided that it is smarter to assume that most people are honest.
</P>
<P>
   So what happens if, say, the caller from Great Bend was a crook
who gave a phony address to intercept someone else's refund check?
</P>
<P>
   ``That will happen,'' conceded Waldo, the customer
representative. And when it is discovered, he said, the state will
promptly send the real taxpayer the refund and then try to recover
the money sent to the crook.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-21-98 1644EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
