</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-REVIEW-SLAYER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SLAYER CONCERT IS LIKE WATCHING A FURNACE ROAR
</HEADLINE>
   (EDS.: the phrase ``oh yea'' is cq.) 
(ja) 
 By BEN RATLIFF   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It's hard not to resort to metaphor in describing a
Slayer concert, because what you're confronted with is both
kinetically massive and uniform, blank, detailless.
</P>
<P>
   In 1986 the band recorded ``Reign in Blood,'' an album that's
still the primary sacrament of death-metal; the short, powerful
record mixed the rhythms of hardcore punk with a single-minded
focus on ritual violence. As a lot of defunct death-metal bands
have since found out, carnage and devilry are a tricky songwriting
trope: unless you make a living as a torturer, you can only imagine
it in so many ways before you get tangled up in cliches and the
clunky Victorianisms that go so well with decadent themes.
</P>
<P>
   But metal, for some reason, continues to need words, and where
they were prolific in the '80s, now the band's songwriters squeeze
out a batch of malevolent scenarios every three years or so.
``Imagine humanity's decline,'' sings Tom Araya in one of the
band's songs on its new album, ``Diabolus in Musica'' (Columbia).
``Step inside my stain of mind/infesting superiority/infectious
immorality, oh yea.''
</P>
<P>
   Let the metaphors begin, oh yea: Watching Slayer's show at
Irving Plaza on Wednesday night was no more or less interesting
than watching an enormous furnace for 90 minutes. It was also like
being crushed by an archetype. The members of Slayer constructed
the language of death-metal, and in concert they set about
deploying it purely, with as little variation as possible. This
enforces the in-crowd aspect of the music. If you have to ask at
this point, you'll never know.
</P>
<P>
   The drummer Paul Bostaph began the show with a few triplet
rhythms that gave way to single slablike beats, spaced apart; it
was a teasing ritual. Then the speed-metal of ``Hell Awaits''
began. Typically, the songs flickered between thrashing two-beat
rhythms and a starchily funky four, with a flowing, histrionic
high-note guitar solo nailed somewhere in the middle. Slayer's
pleasures are purely physical; some of the show's best moments were
the pockets of winded silence after the band had ended a 400
beats-per-minute song and before the fans could physically raise a
cheer.
</P>
<P>
   Eight of the 11 songs on ``Diabolus in Musica,'' a few of which
were played at the show, are in the same gray key, and the band's
rhythmic ideas have a wearying sameness too. Other major metal
bands _ Pantera, Metallica, Megadeth _ at this point, more than a
decade into their careers, are diverse by comparison. In a
career-retrospective show like the one at Irving Plaza, you can
feel it's all one barreling song.
</P>
<P>
   Slayer's impact is bigger than even a large club like Irving
Plaza ought to withstand; the band's massive sound board, to the
rear of the room, displaced about 100 people. But previous shows at
larger halls have proven that Slayer fans and furniture of any kind
_ even chairs bolted to the floor _ do not mix. At Irving Plaza, a
whole new crop of young fans filled the floor, becoming an eruption
of arms, legs and hair. They knew the coordinates, yelling every
refrain; for ``Angel of Death,'' the final song, the air in front
of the stage rained with stage divers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
