<HEADER>
A9338 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FLA-WILDFIRES-COX     06-21 0682
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLA-WILDFIRES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Florida wildfires burn as dry weather continues
 &HT;    By Scott McCabe and Scott Cech
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Wildfires burned in more than half of
Florida's rain-starved counties Saturday, as weary fire fighters
from North Florida to Palm Beach County battled scattered hot spots
in 90 degree-plus heat.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would take a tropical system to dump a lot of water on the
state to make a difference,'' said Barbara Doran of the Florida
Emergency Operations Center in Tallahassee, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   In all, she said, fires burned in 38 of Florida's 67 counties,
though fire threats to Jacksonville and the Alachua County town of
Waldo _ the only populous areas affected _ diminished.
</P>
<P>
   Palm Beach County firefighters battled 14 brush fires Saturday.
None threatened homes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The dry conditions of course make it easier for brush fires to
start,'' said Nigel Baker, spokesman for county Fire Rescue.
</P>
<P>
   On the Treasure Coast, a wave of afternoon lighting flashes
ignited at least half a dozen fires in the deccicated brush.
</P>
<P>
   In St. Lucie County, strong winds downed tree limbs and tore
power lines loose and pea-sized hail pounded Fort Pierce.
</P>
<P>
   A fire that started about 2 p.m. in St. Lucie County threatened
local businesses, so sheriff's deputies briefly closed down a
section of U.S. 1 as a precaution. The fire came within 100 yards
of the highway at one point, fire officials said, but Forest
Service firefighting equipment was in such high demand throughout
the area that no bulldozers were available to dig fire trenches.
</P>
<P>
   And instead of the rain that might have dampened the blazes,
some areas of the Treasure Coast got high winds that fed the fires.
Other significant brush fires were started in Fort Pierce and
western St. Lucie County.
</P>
<P>
   Blazes have ravaged drought-striken Florida since Memorial Day,
singeing more than 67,000 acres and damaging 114 homes and
businesses. One person died in Seminole County.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, President Clinton declared all of Florida a fire
disaster area, giving emergency relief to exhausted fire fighters.
</P>
<P>
   That federal emergency declaration expanded a previous one from
seven counties to every one of Florida's 67 counties. The latest
move would bring in federal forestry workers and equipment to help
fight the Florida blazes.
</P>
<P>
   A swamp fire at San Pardo Bay enveloped the region in choking
smoke.
</P>
<P>
   Since Thursday, fire has burned more than 7,500 acres of private
forest at the northeast corner of Taylor County. And although it's
blown dense, smog-like smoke 100 miles east to Jacksonvillle, it's
hard to see. But it's out there, crackling just beyond the green
thicket of pond cypress, slash pine, swampcyrilla, and razor-sharp
greenbriar vines.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is going to be a tremendously big fire, I'm afraid,''
said Bill Crane, a member of the North Carolina forest firefighting
team that has sparred with the wildfire since it began.
</P>
<P>
   More than 25 forest-fire fighters, including South Carolina
crews, are expected to join the army of 97 people already on hand.
</P>
<P>
   Crews remained on the defensive Saturday. Bulldozers ploughed
the dense brush along existing dirt roads, carving out a 25-mile
perimeter in which to keep the fire contained.
</P>
<P>
   Tractor crews bunkered down along a 50-yard-wide strip where an
underground gas line had been built. The pipe was too far below the
earth to be a danger, but Incident Commander John Pearson worried
heavy smoke might ground out nearby power lines.
</P>
<P>
   As smoke thickened several hundred yards off, crews remained
skittish.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been kind of waiting, creeping around, burning real
slow,'' said Travis McCoy, a crew member of Foley Timber and Land
Co. ``That's good for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Foley and Gilman Paper Co. own most of this timber land that
stretches on for more than 100,000 acres, Pearson said.
</P>
<P>
   Staff writers Jennifer Peltz, Monika Gonzalez and William
Cooper, Jr. and the Associated Press contributed to this story.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
