<HEADER>
A9344 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LILITH-CONCERT-REVIEW     06-21 0985
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LILITH-CONCERT-REVIEW-600&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LILITH FAIR REVIEW: EXTOLLING FEMININITY, GENTLY 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By ANN POWERS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORTLAND, Ore. _ Sarah McLachlan does not want the Lilith Fair,
the summerlong ``celebration of women in music'' that began its
second year Friday at the Civic Auditorium here, to be judged as a
political intervention.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. McLachlan, the Canadian singer-songwriter and Lilith
founder, has said she wanted concertgoers to appreciate the
artistry of this touring bill of female artists, and to leave
questions of its social impact for the history books.
</P>
<P>
   Judging Lilith Fair on esthetic terms, however, demands
exploring what unites its participants beyond gender. Such
collective interests turn the best summer festivals into events
rather than just painfully long concerts. Consider Lilith as if it
were a bluegrass fest, then, or a day of Dixieland jazz: a
gathering devoted to an esoteric musical style. At Lilith, feminine
folk-pop is the chosen arcana.
</P>
<P>
   Viewing Lilith this way derails the questions that critics have
raised about its lack of diversity. (The tour goes out on its
farthest limb later in its schedule, when hip-hop stylist Missy
Elliott joins in for some dates.) It finds strengths in the
resemblances among the five acts that shared the concert's main
stage on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   These artists _ Ms. McLachlan, Natalie Merchant, the Indigo
Girls, Erykah Badu and Sinead O'Connor _ are masters of the brand
of tuneful, literary pop that explores woman-centered myths and
realities. Appearing with their own bands here, each claimed a
stake within this rich, if sometimes overly sweetened, style.
</P>
<P>
   Feminine folk-pop offers specific emotional and musical
pleasures. It blends confessional singer-songwriting with vague
social idealism, finding common ground in women's personal
experiences. Emphasizing the voice and the gentle give-and-take of
ensemble playing, it ignores instrumental virtuosity and generally
avoids the catharsis of rock. Sympathy is its ultimate value, as
fans apply its messages about love and understanding to their own
lives.
</P>
<P>
   Many artists working within this traditionally feminine mode are
content to honor its ethos; the most interesting also reconfigure
it. Each of Lilith's main-stage performers attempted this, with
varying degrees of success. Inventiveness, though, is not
necessarily the quality that endears them to most fans swaying and
crooning to their favorite meaning-filled ballads. Thus, they
lightly tread the territory connecting their individualism with the
genre's equalizing demands.
</P>
<P>
   Sets on two smaller stages by up-and-coming artists, including
the flamboyant Billie Myers and the moody Spanish group Lhasa, set
the mood, but this year's emphasis is on the main stage. Ms.
O'Connor appeared there first, offering a condensed version of her
appearance at the Guinness Fleadh festival in New York City the
week before. In good voice and a chipper mood, she made the most of
a short set.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Badu also abbreviated her usual show without abandoning her
favorite themes. She broke the festival's most significant cultural
barrier by preaching her Afrocentric philosophy via a smooth blend
of hip-hop, jazz and soul, just as she does to her largely black
audiences on her own tours.
</P>
<P>
   As she extolled motherhood and thanked the Creator for her
talent, it was easy to comprehend the themes she shares with Ms.
O'Connor. Both view femininity as a spiritually rich calling that
has been tainted through abuse and seek to restore its luster
within their soothing but powerful songs. Both also sing and write
in ways that make their music as singular as their messages can be
sweeping; and although neither did anything unusual Friday, their
presence gave depth to the festival.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The Indigo Girls are impressive singers, too, but despite their
conscious efforts to refresh folk-rock with new ingredients (a
sampled trip-hop beat here, a heavy-metal riff there), they remain
strongest within its most familiar parameters.
</P>
<P>
   The duo prompted many sing-alongs, balancing Amy Ray's
deep-voiced, passionate declarations against Emily Saliers' more
lightly phrased musings.
</P>
<P>
   Inviting Ms. McLachlan and K's Choice, one of the groups that
performed on a smaller stage, to join them for the traditional folk
song ``The Water Is Wide'' and Neil Young's ``Rockin' in the Free
World,'' the Indigo Girls invoked the bonding ritual of feminist
women's music festivals, spicing it up with a dash of mainstream
rock-and-roll.
</P>
<P>
   Diametrically opposed to the Indigo Girls' extroverted presence,
Ms. Merchant tapped the enduring charm of the eccentric woman
artist. In a multicolored outfit reminiscent of a Pottery Barn
catalog, spinning and curling herself into a ball, she guided her
band through her sometimes cryptic songs in a performance that was
all about her own joy in the music.
</P>
<P>
   She sang a campy version of ``If I Only Had a Brain,'' from
``The Wizard of Oz,'' and material from her older albums and the
new ``Ophelia.'' But the individual selections mattered less than
the buoyant mood she created by so gracefully dancing with her own
muse.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the very lack of such a peculiar inner sprite is what
has made Ms. McLachlan so popular; her gift is for playing an
idealized emotional Everywoman, and she took that stance once again
during her surprisingly short closing set. Revisiting hits and
presenting a few new songs, she made the sophisticated pop that is
her specialty intimate by mining the lustrous quality of her voice.
</P>
<P>
   Once in a while, she roughened up that instrument ever so
slightly, abandoning her patented comforting tone. For now, though,
she remained the quintessential feminine folk-popster, reigning at
the easily reached center of a perilously softhearted art.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
