</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-COLUMN-OWEN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEARTY ITALIAN FARE FOR TERRIFIED TRAVELERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN OWEN  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the Italian Dolomites, a bus driver weaved his way along a
narrow road skirting precipices, occasionally swerving to pass a
truck on a blind curve. The tape deck was playing and with one hand
the driver waved an imaginary baton, directing Pavarotti through a
difficult aria. The other hand was begrudgingly assigned to the
steering wheel.
</P>
<P>
   Yet another bus on the high cliffs of the Amalfi coast executed
so many hairpin turns, horn blasting, that a passenger was swept
with motion sickness and three times hollered for the driver to let
him out. He finally left the bus permanently, saying he'd walk into
Amalfi.
</P>
<P>
   In Padua, confessionals in St. Anthony Cathedral were full at 10
a.m. on a Friday morning. At the saint's tomb, a wall is devoted to
photos of teenagers, grinning in front of wrecked autos. On behalf
of these lucky survivors, the same message to St. Anthony has
repeatedly been scrawled:
</P>
<P>
   ``Grazie!''
</P>
<P>
   In the streets of Rovigo, grandmothers on bicycles with infants
perched on handle-bar seats, weaved through a stream of snorting
Fiats, trucks and darting motorbikes. The grandmothers look neither
left nor right, their unhelmeted heads protected only by 40-mph
hair spray.
</P>
<P>
   Virtually none of the bicycle or scooter owners in Italy wears a
crash helmet, yet they seem completely unconcerned, despite the
fact that nobody in the country _ dating back to the invention of
the combustion engine _ has ever been detected yielding the right
of way or swerving to avoid any object other than the occasional
dead burro.
</P>
<P>
   For some reason scooter drivers turn off their headlights on
rainy nights in Rome. They are no longer scooters. They are
transformed into Stealth fighters. Even more of a threat are the
young lovers, sharing a scooter in Sorrento _ hugging, clutching,
kissing at 30 mph.
</P>
<P>
   I once asked my daughter, Kathy, how she survived the traffic
during the time she lived in Boston. She said she imagined that her
car was enclosed in a crash-proof bubble and she motored through
the roundabouts with immunity.
</P>
<P>
   Every Fiat Panda Jolly and Vespa sold in Italy is apparently
equipped with an invisible plastic bubble.
</P>
<P>
   Italy is the Land of Living Dangerously. Those who survive the
traffic threats challenge themselves by chain-smoking, eating food
afloat in olive oil and washing each bite down with healthy gulps
from $3 bottles of the local wine.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, we too survived a month of living dangerously. Once
dismounted, the Italians proved to be extremely friendly. The
scenery was breathtaking. Typical of our meals-for-two was an order
for one salad, two pastas, one veal dish, one tiramisu dessert and
a bottle of wine for $27, service included, at Osteria Gatto Nero
in Sorrento. And we avoided all careening Vespas by a safety margin
of at least six inches.
</P>
<P>
   ``Grazie!'' St. Anthony.
</P>
<P>
   Here are a couple of dishes similar to those we encountered.
</P>
<P>
   Tuscan Tortellini Salad
</P>
<P>
   1 pound frozen tortellini
</P>
<P>
   1 cup frozen peas
</P>
<P>
   One-half red pepper, diced
</P>
<P>
   One-half cup green onions, chopped
</P>
<P>
   1 6-ounce can albacore tuna
</P>
<P>
   1 14-ounce can artichoke hearts
</P>
<P>
   One-half cup chopped fresh parsley
</P>
<P>
   12 black olives, sliced
</P>
<P>
   One-quarter cup fresh basil leaves, chopped, or 2 teaspoons
dried basil
</P>
<P>
   For the dressing
</P>
<P>
   1 clove garlic, minced
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon Dijon mustard
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   One-third cup orange juice
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons olive oil
</P>
<P>
   One-third cup low-fat sour cream
</P>
<P>
   One-quarter cup minced fresh basil leaves or 2 teaspoons dried
</P>
<P>
   Cook the tortellini in boiling water according to package
instructions. Drain and cool under running water. Thaw the peas
under running water.
</P>
<P>
   Dump the pasta into a bowl and top with the peas, red pepper and
onions. Drain the tuna and add to the bowl. Quarter the drained
artichoke hearts and add them to the bowl, too, along with the
parsley, olives and basil.
</P>
<P>
   To make the dressing, dump the garlic, mustard, lemon juice and
orange juice in a blender bowl. Hit the button and hold it down 30
seconds. (Hey, that sounds just like a Vespa starting up on a cold
morning.) With the blender still running, slowly pour in the olive
oil. Stop the motor, add the sour cream and basil, then blend
briefly and pour over the tortellini salad.
</P>
<P>
   Top the salad with dressing and toss a couple of times. Add salt
to taste, toss again, and refrigerate. Serve cold or at room
temperature.
</P>
<P>
   Vitello Venice
</P>
<P>
   6 veal scallops (6 ounces each)
</P>
<P>
   Two-and-one-half cups dry bread crumbs
</P>
<P>
   One-and-one-half cups sliced almonds
</P>
<P>
   One-third cup minced parsley
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons grated lemon rind
</P>
<P>
   3 egg whites, lightly beaten
</P>
<P>
   One-third cup olive oil
</P>
<P>
   Pound the veal (vitello in Italian) between sheets of waxed
paper until \ inch thick. Salt and pepper the meat. Lightly toast
the almonds.
</P>
<P>
   Combine the crumbs, parsley and lemon rind on a large plate. Dip
the scallops into the egg white, then into the crumb mixture,
pressing in to coat on both sides. Chill the veal on a baking sheet
for 30 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Heat the oil or butter in a medium-hot skillet and saute the
scallops just a minute or two on each side. Remove to a warm
platter. Sprinkle with the warm almonds and serve with lemon
wedges. Serves two bus drivers and four passengers.
</P>
<P>
   Don't worry about the empty place setting. That particular
``guest'' is walking into town and will probably miss dinner.
</P>
<P>
   John Owen writes ``The Intermediate Eater'' weekly for the P-I.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
