<DOCNO> NYT19980621.0063 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-21 17:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9347 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYC-OPERA-KELLOGG-ART     06-21 1094
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYC-OPERA-KELLOGG-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PAUL KELLOGG: OPERA INNOVATOR TAKES RISKS IN SEARCH OF UNTAPPED
AUDIENCES 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or 1927.) 
 (bl)  
 By ANTHONY TOMMASINI   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In the continuing debate over the reasons for the
dwindling of classical music audiences, the managers of opera
companies and orchestras get a bad rap. Or so says Paul Kellogg,
the general and artistic director of the New York City Opera.
</P>
<P>
   For sure, many managers are fairly perceived as willing
kowtowers to the bottom line, eager to placate their worried boards
and wealthy patrons by presenting tried-and-true repertory that the
most loyal segments of their audiences supposedly want.
</P>
<P>
   But others, Kellogg says, are adventurous souls at heart, closet
radicals who would love to try new works, take chances and
challenge their audiences, but are understandably afraid to take a
risk.
</P>
<P>
   In his own career, Kellogg, 60, has taken more risks than most,
emboldened by his belief in untapped audiences. He sees opera-goers
who are younger, hipper types who, because arts education in the
schools is so lacking, have no vested interest in the classics and
might be willing to try something new, or even something old and
unfamiliar but presented in a daring new form. If only they could
be reached.
</P>
<P>
   Reflecting recently on his two completed seasons at the helm of
the New York City Opera, Kellogg talked with messianic fervor about
that untapped audience.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are out there who don't know Puccini's `Boheme' from
Britten's `Paul Bunyan,''' he said. ``And they're just as likely to
come to the Britten, if they think that it be fresh and
intriguing.'' These are the people who, in other areas, Kellogg
added, first gravitate to new movies, new pop groups, new plays,
before looking to the past. ``And I think I'm reaching them.''
</P>
<P>
   Evidence to support his hunch is hard to come by. How do you
survey hipness? And the hard numbers, though encouraging, are not
conclusive. For example, by advertising in campus publications, the
company alerted college students to a discount allowing them to buy
advance tickets at rush-seat prices: $10.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1996-97 season, the company sold 2,460 student discount
tickets; this season the number jumped to 11,685. Impressive, yes.
But with a total of 115 performances in the 2,700-seat New York
State Theater, that means potentially more than 310,000 seats are
available.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm willing to lose money on student discounts in 1998,''
Kellogg said, ``in order to build an audience for 2008.'' In a way,
his anecdotal evidence is almost more convincing. ``I see far more
younger, more casually dressed people, and college-age couples on
big dates all dressed up the way they think you should for opera,''
he said. ``It's very noticeable, and you would not have seen that
10 years ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Kellogg may be right. But he is no lone idealist. The conviction
that new audiences are waiting to be tapped and that new repertory
is one way to tap them also drives Michael Tilson Thomas, the
charismatic conductor of the San Francisco Symphony. Thomas'
programs, while fully attentive to the classics, are notable for
their high quotient of recent works, American music and neglected
20th-century repertory. Audiences there are getting younger, said
Peter Pastreich, the orchestra's executive director.
</P>
<P>
   Pastreich was not surprised by the results of a survey this
season that compared single-ticket buyers, who tend to be
last-minute purchasers, with subscription holders, for whom
symphony-going is a habit. Some 35 percent of single-ticket holders
were in the 25-35 age bracket (compared with 5 percent of regular
subscribers), and 25 percent of single-ticket holders were in the
36-44 age bracket (compared with 14 percent of subscribers).
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not scientific proof,'' Pastreich said. ``But younger
people are buying single tickets and showing up. Of course, part of
this has to do with Michael Tilson Thomas himself. Younger people
identify with his dynamism and sex appeal. They trust his
programming and have figured out that something hip is going on
here.''
</P>
<P>
   Thomas' counterpart at the Los Angeles Philharmonic, the
conductor Esa-Pekka Salonen, is also challenging his audiences with
bracing contemporary fare and drawing in new listeners. And Gerard
Mortier, the artistic director of the famously snoozy Salzburg
Festival in Austria, is shaking up the place with newly
commissioned operas and a contemporary music series, making enemies
and winning converts in the process.
</P>
<P>
   Kellogg points out that opera companies have an advantage over
orchestras in attracting new audiences: at its best, opera can be
an exciting form of theater. And the use of supertitles, which
audiences everywhere have embraced, has opened up the opera house
to people interested in a good show.
</P>
<P>
   ``To us,'' Kellogg said over lunch recently in his Lincoln
Center office, ``this means we can look for people who are
interested in theater and may have been put off by Broadway, with
its dumb spectacle.'' They just might find opera a strangely
involving type of theater, he thinks.
</P>
<P>
   Emblematic of what he wants to accomplish was the recent ``Paul
Bunyan.'' This production, imaginatively directed by Mark Lamos,
originated in 1995 at the Glimmerglass Opera, the summer festival
in Cooperstown, N.Y., that Kellogg founded in 1975.
</P>
<P>
   He still serves as artistic director at Glimmerglass, which
built its following ``not with opera's top 10 favorites,'' he said,
but by including American and contemporary works and unfamiliar
Baroque operas. ``Paul Bunyan,'' Britten's first opera and his only
collaboration with W.H. Auden, was a surprise success. ``It's a
wonderful American fable, a haunting and touching piece,'' Kellogg
said.
</P>
<P>
   So how did it fare with City Opera audiences this spring?
</P>
<P>
   For its five performances, the opera played to 70 percent
capacity. This compares with, say, the ever-popular ``Carmen,''
which had nine performance at 88 percent capacity. But, Kellogg
emphasized, before he arrived, contemporary works attracted houses
of 45 percent to at most 65 percent (the figure for the 1994
production of Hindemith's ``Mathis der Maler'').
</P>
<P>
   This spring, for the annual broadcast on the PBS ``Live From
Lincoln Center'' series, Kellogg pushed hard for ``Paul Bunyan''
and won. He intends to bring it back to the stage in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Kellogg also has strong ideas about the standard repertory.
Given that the Metropolitan Opera House is across the plaza, a City
Opera ``Boheme'' or ``Nozze di Figaro'' should offer something
distinctive; for example, instead of stars, young and eager signers
who look like the characters they portray.
</P>
<P>
   Here, as Kellogg concedes, the company has had mixed results.
There is a fine line between giving a fledgling singers a chance
and prematurely pushing them into vocally unsuitable roles.
</P>
<P>
   This season's ``Macbeth,'' a familiar but hardly standard opera,
represented Kellogg's ideal of what his company should uniquely do
with seminal 19th-century works. Critics generally praised the
performance, especially the impassioned Lady Macbeth of Lauren
Flanigan. Reaction was divided about the production, specifically
John Conklin's sets, which used shining steel platforms and
scaffolding to evoke the inner lives of these medieval Scottish
characters.
</P>
<P>
   ``People who came to see a Macbeth in kilts were disappointed,''
Kellogg said. ``But the audience hoping for a vivid theatrical
experience liked it immensely. Nobody familiar with the way
Shakespeare is presented in the theater these days would have been
bothered a bit.''
</P>
<P>
   It played to 77 percent capacity, which makes its fifth best for
the season.
</P>
<P>
   The attendance figures require some interpretation. Looked at
simply in terms of the number of seats sold, the great hits of
opera's past won out, topped by ``La Boheme'' at 31,600 seats,
with, in descending order, ``Carmen,'' ``La Traviata,'' ``Macbeth''
and, at 18,000, ``Madama Butterfly.''
</P>
<P>
   But some operas had more than twice the number of performances
as others, and when the percentage of the house sold (including all
performances of a particular opera) is looked at, the list is
strikingly different: Handel's ``Xerxes'' took first place (93
percent), followed by ``Carmen'' (88 percent), then the United
States premiere of the Chinese-born composer Tan Dun's 1996 opera
``Marco Polo'' (85 percent), ``La Boheme'' (83 percent) and
``Macbeth'' (77 percent).
</P>
<P>
   Of course, there were just five performances of ``Xerxes,'' only
four of ``Marco Polo'' and 13 of ``La Boheme.'' But that's to be
expected, Kellogg said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many people want to see the bread-and-butter operas like
`Carmen,''' he said. ``They sometimes don't even care so much how
they're sung, and that's true for Met audiences as well. These are
great works, and many people are hearing them for the first time.''
</P>
<P>
   All the contemporary works this season did fairly well in terms
of percentages, Kellogg reports, including Tobias Picker's brooding
``Emmeline'' (four performances, at a little under 70 percent). One
reason has to do with a trend that transcends opera, Kellogg
believes. ``New music is more accessible these days,'' he said.
``Musical styles are wildly more eclectic and less rigidly bound to
what is intellectually fashionable.''
</P>
<P>
   Presenting fresh repertory in stimulating productions is
central, he says. Of course, one person's stimulation is another's
gimmickry. The production of Gluck's remarkable ``Iphigenie en
Tauride,'' directed by Francesca Zambello, emphasized the
homoerotic aspect of the bonded male friendship that is at the core
of the story, drawn from the Greek drama.
</P>
<P>
   And casting two handsome young singers who spent much of the
performance in loincloths drove home that awareness. Some critics
found it stunning, and the audience on opening night responded with
a frenzied ovation, especially for Christine Goerke, a superb young
soprano, in the title role. Other critics found it sensationalized.
</P>
<P>
   Next season, Gluck's ``Orfeo ed Euridice'' will come to City
Opera in a co-production with the English National Opera, directed
and choreographed by Martha Clarke. It includes an Elysian Fields
scene for six male and six female dancers who will be completely
naked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those dancers are incredibly beautiful,'' said Kellogg, who
insists that the nudity is humane and sensitive.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the case, count on seats in the front rows going fast.
</P>
<P>
   Other unusual works include two American operas: Jack Beeson's
``Lizzie Borden,'' which was given its premiere by the New York
City Opera in 1965, and Carlisle Floyd's ``Of Mice and Men.'' There
will also be new productions of Handel's little-known ``Partenope''
and Strauss' seldom heard ``Intermezzo.''
</P>
<P>
   City Opera board president Mark Newhouse, who supports Kellogg's
programming ideas, said that trying to attract new audiences was
like playing the stock market. ``The day after it goes up or down,
it's easy to get 10 experts telling you what happened,'' he said.
``It's hard to figure.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Kellogg must attend to the nuts and bolts of running
a company. In a gamble, he increased this year's operating budget
by $3.5 million, to $30 million, with yearly increases expected to
follow.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the money has gone and will go to increasing rehearsal
time and boosting fees for artists,'' he said. ``The New York City
Opera can have the most innovative season imaginable, but, first
and foremost, we have to be good.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
