<HEADER>
A9350 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BRAVES-NOTEBOOK22-COX     06-21 0881
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRAVES-NOTEBOOK22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Galarraga quietly helps other Braves bats
 &HT;    By Jack Wilkinson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONTREAL _ His improved home run pace is not as dramatic as,
say, Mark McGwire's or even Sammy Sosa's. Yet when Javy Lopez hit
his 16th homer here Saturday night, it put the catcher five weeks
ahead of last year's pace. Lopez never hit No. 16 last season until
July 26. Now, he's just seven behind his career high. The reason?
</P>
<P>
   The new first baseman. Andres Galarraga.
</P>
<P>
   ''For me, Galarraga's a big positive,'' said Lopez. ''He really
makes us believe the ballpark doesn't have anything to do with your
ability. Once you hit the ball, it's going to go.
</P>
<P>
   ''He really proved the ballpark doesn't matter. To me, that's a
big motivation.''
</P>
<P>
   So forget all that early-season talk last year that Turner Field
wasn't home run-friendly. ''I just tried to tell him, 'Hey, it
doesn't matter where we play, who's pitching. You just need to make
good contact,''' said Galarraga. ''He's so strong, knows how to
hit. I've said to him a couple of times, 'A catcher's got to be a
good hitter. You have an idea how they pitch.' Just little things,
make more concentration.
</P>
<P>
   ''I've said lots of times, 'I think this place (Turner Field) is
easier to hit it out than Coors Field.' I was just joking. But
maybe it helps.''
</P>
<P>
   This does, too: Galarraga's right-handed presence in the cleanup
spot, instead of the left-handed Fred McGriff. ''I see what they're
throwing him,'' said the right-handed Lopez, who hits two spots
behind Galarraga, ''and I'm hitting the pitches they throw him. I'm
also trying to take Vinny Castilla's job.''
</P>
<P>
   In Denver, the right-handed, ex-Brave Castilla also hit sixth
and fed off Galarraga for consecutive 40-homer seasons the past two
years. Galarraga's influence in Atlanta has already far surpassed
McGriff's last year.
</P>
<P>
   ''We loved Freddie but this guy has already hit as many homers
as Freddie had all last season,'' Bobby Cox said recently.
Actually, Galarraga already has 25 homers, three more than
McGriff's total last year. ''The impact has been awesome.''
</P>
<P>
   ''He's made our lineup a lot tougher to defend if you're an
opposing manager,'' said Chipper Jones.
</P>
<P>
   WEISS HOME: Walt Weiss did not play Sunday. He flew home to
Atlanta Sunday morning to be with his seriously-ill son, Brody, 3.
Cox doesn't know when Weiss will rejoin the team. Ozzie Guillen
took Weiss' place in the lineup, leading off and playing shortstop.
</P>
<P>
   WELCOME BACK: The applause started slowly but when Dennis
Martinez came on to pitch the ninth inning Saturday night, the
ex-Expo got a standing ovation that gave Olympic Stadium something
it sorely lacks nowadays: Noise.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was great. I had a great relationship here with the fans,
the people of Montreal because we had a few good years when I
played here,'' said Martinez, who pitched here from 1986-93, won
100 of his 243 career victories, was an NL All-Star in 1990-92 and
threw a perfect game in 1991 in Los Angeles against the Dodgers.
''Plus, I guess they appreciated what I did for them on the playing
field and off.
</P>
<P>
   ''This place appreciated me more than any other place I played.
It will always be No. 1. I think it has something to do with
they're another country, like I'm from another country. They might
understand me more because we have a different culture and they
appreciate the effort on the field, win or lose. If you give them
100 per cent, they really appreciate that.''
</P>
<P>
   Martinez brought his wife and two youngest children with him on
this trip. ''We really wanted to show people, 'Thank you for taking
us under your wing,''' he said. ''This is the place where I started
my second (NL) career in baseball. Everything here is great
memories. They closed that chapter (Saturday) night. Unfortunately,
I didn't have a chance to tip my hat to them. I know deep in my
heart, I was touched by the ovation. After the game, I said, 'I
hope they're not offended I didn't tip my hat.'''
</P>
<P>
   Why didn't he? Martinez was too intent on pitching.
</P>
<P>
   ETC. Sunday's crowd of 12,265 was the largest of the weekend but
brought the three-game total to just 33,768. The Braves average
home crowd in 42 dates: 38,177...Like 13 other NL teams, the Expos
have a 7:05 p.m. start for night games. Only the Braves and Mets
start at 7:40. Why don't the Braves start earlier? TV. TBS dreads
losing both the early-evening revenue from ''The Andy Griffith
Show'' at 7:05 and the later prime-time game revenue should the
Braves start earlier.
</P>
<P>
   ''Television always has an impact on our scheduling decisions,''
said assistant general manager Dean Taylor. ''There are some
revenue issues surrounding starting times. They're pretty
complicated.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Braves fan surveys a few years ago indicated a
preference for earlier starting times for night games, midweek
games still start at 7:40 p.m. with Saturday night games at 7:10.
''Every year, when we discuss scheduling issues with TBS, one issue
we always discuss is starting times,'' said Taylor, ''in order to
give them the opportunity to make the schedule as attractive as
possible from a television standpoint. That's very important.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
