<SLUG> BC-BRAVES-ONDECK22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Braves On Deck: New York Yankees
 &HT;    By Jack Wilkinson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   _ When: Tonight and Tuesday, 7:35 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   _ Where: Yankee Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   _ TV/radio: TBS will broadcast both games.
</P>
<P>
   _ Probable starting pitchers: Tonight _ RHP Greg Maddux (10-2,
1.62 ERA; 1-0, 1.00 lifetime vs. Yankees) vs. LHP Andy Pettitte
(8-5, 4.13; 0-0, 0.00 lifetime vs. Braves). Tuesday _ LHP Tom
Glavine (9-3, 2.75; 0-0, 0.00 lifetime vs. Yankees) vs. RHP Orlando
Hernandez (2-0, 1.52; first appearance vs. Braves).
</P>
<P>
   _ Series history: Atlanta leads all-time 2-1, taking two of
three interleague games last year in the Bronx.
</P>
<P>
   _ Past meetings: In their first encounter since the Yankees
rallied from an 0-2 deficit to win the 1996 World Series in six
games, the clubs played nine scoreless innings last June 30 in
Yankee Stadium. Andy Pettitte worked the first five for New York
and Tom Glavine all nine for Atlanta before Mike Bielecki gave up
four straight one-out singles in the 10th. The last, by Luis Sojo,
gave the Yanks a 1-0 win. The next night, Atlanta got 7-2/3 strong
innings from Denny Neagle, superb relief from Mark Wohlers and a
two-run homer from Ryan Klesko in a 3-1 victory. Klesko homered the
next afternoon, when Greg Maddux absolutely baffled the Yankees
with a three-hit, eight-strikeout, 2-0 shutout that lasted just 2
hours, 9 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   _ Yankees leaders: Avg. _ Bernie Williams (.353). HR _ Williams,
Tino Martinez and Darryl Strawberry (10). RBI _ Martinez (51).
Steals _ Chuck Knoblauch (19). W _ David Wells and David Cone (9).
ERA _ Orlando Hernandez (1.52). Strikeouts _ Cone (81). Saves _
Mariano Rivera (16).
</P>
<P>
   _ Quickly: Baseball's best team continues to roll, even without
Williams. The center fielder is on the disabled list with a
strained right knee, but shortstop Derek Jeter returned from the DL
Friday...The Yankees have the best winning percentage in the majors
(.746), as well as the best home (26-5) and road (24-12) records.
When the Orioles took two of three from the Yanks in Baltimore this
week, it ended New York's big-league record-tying streak of 24
straight series without a loss. After losing two games to open the
season in Anaheim, the Yankees went 20-0-4 in their next 24 series
before Baltimore...The Yanks are 49-13 since starting the season
1-4...Hernandez is 2-0 since being called up from Class AAA
Columbus June 2, and El Duque gives manager Joe Torre a rotation
that rivals Atlanta's. He hasn't pitched enough to qualify, so his
1.52 ERA isn't the AL's best. Irabu's 1.68 is tops, along with his
.191 opponents' batting average...David Wells, who beat Cleveland
Saturday for his ninth win, threw a perfect game May 17 versus
Minnesota, the 14th in big-league history...The Yankees are second
in the AL in batting (.291) and pitching (3.94 ERA), third in
fielding (.984). They average 6.2 runs per game.
</P>
<P>
   _ Who's hot: Before losing his last start, Cone (9-2) had won
nine straight decisions, the majors' longest winning streak this
year. Rivera had three saves on the road trip, 16 in 19
opportunities this year. Catcher Joe Girardi has hit in a
season-high five straight games, going 7-for-15.
</P>
<P>
   _ Who's not: Tino Martinez is 5-for-his-last-33, 11-for-56.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
