<HEADER>
A9352 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BRAVES-YANKS-COX     06-21 0460
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRAVES-YANKS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Braves, Yankees get first look at each other Monday
 &HT;    By Jack Wilkinson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONTREAL _ Bobby Cox dismisses it as a prelude to nowhere,
merely four enjoyable games. Tom Glavine urges June caution. Yet
Keith Lockhart foresees a mid-season measuring stick and there's a
sense of anticipation in the Braves clubhouse. Indeed, Andres
Galarraga can't wait to see Yankee Stadium well in advance of the
World Series.
</P>
<P>
   So folks, let the Yankees games begin.
</P>
<P>
   ''If we've heard it once, we've heard it 1,000 times: This is a
preview of the World Series,'' Glavine said of a four-game set with
the Yankees that begins tonight with two games in the Bronx, then
shifts to Atlanta Wednesday for two more. ''It's way too early to
be talking about that. There's still some teams out there who are
going to have something to say about who plays in the World Series,
whatever happens with us and the Yankees.''
</P>
<P>
   ''It's four games we'll enjoy because playing the Yankees is
always great, like the Red Sox and Baltimore,'' said Cox. ''Makes
the season go faster. But I haven't put one iota of energy into it.
It's certainly not a prelude to anything. That's what everybody's
thinking.''
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees have clearly established themselves as the AL's _ if
not baseball's _ best. The Braves are again the big cheese of the
NL. Even Glavine admits it has late-October implications as a
''potential match-up.''
</P>
<P>
   ''There's a lot of pride on the line right now,'' said Glavine,
who starts Tuesday against Orlando Hernandez. ''A lot of people are
talking about them as the best team in baseball. We want to go in
and show them we're better.''
</P>
<P>
   The Braves were last year, taking two of three taut, terrific
games in the Bronx. The finale was an afternoon delight for Cox: A
2-hour, 9-minute, 2-0 three-hit shutout by Greg Maddux, who opposes
Andy Pettitte tonight. There's also the lingering distaste of the
1996 World Series, when the Yankees overcame an 0-2 deficit to
celebrate at home.
</P>
<P>
   ''They've got a pretty unbelievable team,'' Lockhart said. ''You
hope it's going to be a good series. We can see what kind of team
we have. It should be exciting.''
</P>
<P>
   Especially for Galarraga, who has never played in Yankee Stadium
and approaches this as advanced surveillance. ''I want to see it
before the World Series,'' he said, grinning. ''It's kind of
important. We saw them in spring training but it's not the same.
Now, we have to do some scouting: How they pitch, how they run,
what they do in (certain) situations.
</P>
<P>
   ''It works both ways. They're probably thinking the same thing.
They want to see what we have.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
