<SLUG> BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Sunday, June 22, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 212-556-4204.) 
(bl) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Hazy, very warm and humid conditions will cover most of the
Eastern states. A broken band of heavy showers and a few
thunderstorms will form near a weak frontal system as it moves
through the interior Northeast. Locally, heavy rain will occur in a
few locations near the central Appalachians and Middle Atlantic
states where high level winds direct a series of thunderstorms over
the same spot. Otherwise, light onshore breezes will keep the
coastal Northeast much cooler with less chance for showers than the
interior. Patches of dense coastal fog will be common from Maine to
northern Jersey, especially in the morning.
</P>
<P>
   Very hot weather will persist from the southern Plains through
the Southeastern states. Sunshine will be plentiful in most of the
region; however, some strong thunderstorms will develop in the heat
of the afternoon in the Tennessee Valley. A few heavy
thundershowers will also help alleviate the unusual heat and
dryness in parts of the Florida. There will be little chance for
rain in most of Texas and Oklahoma, however, isolated late
afternoon thunderstorms will erupt in western sections.
</P>
<P>
   High pressure will promote dry and very warm conditions from the
eastern Dakotas to the southern Great Lakes. A wavering front from
the central Rockies to the Ohio Valley will be the focus for
clusters showers and thunderstorms, particularly in the afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   The West Coast states will have plenty of sunshine, despite
patchy morning coastal clouds. A few afternoon thundershowers will
form over the high ground from the Cascades to the Bitterroots.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Hot Nights
</P>
<P>
   It was the warmest night on record in Midland, Texas, on
Saturday when the mercury fell no lower than 82 degrees.
Measurements have been taken at the western Texas town since 1930.
During the weekend, several other cities in the southern Plains and
Southeast set daily records for overnight lows. In general, warm
nights are more common than they were earlier this century.
Official readings in the modern era are typically taken in
increasingly urban environments. The concrete roads and buildings
retain the day's heat longer than the open terrain in rural areas. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
