<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUFFETT MAY FACE SCRUTINY FROM INSTITUTIONAL HOLDERS
</P>
<P>
   The acquisition of General Re by Berkshire Hathaway, which was
announced late Friday, means Wall Street professionals will become
holders of 15 percent of the shares of Berkshire Hathaway, Warren
Buffett's far-flung corporate empire.
</P>
<P>
   For years, Buffett has enjoyed a luxury unknown to most other
corporate chiefs _ he has answered almost exclusively to individual
investors. But now the professionals who manage portfolios for
mutual funds, college endowments and big corporations will be
asking questions.
</P>
<P>
   A REPORTER'S WORK FREES A WOMAN
</P>
<P>
   Betty Tyson was released from prison on May 27 because of the
reporting of Gary Craig of The Rochester Democrat and Chronicle. He
became obsessed with a rogue detective who was accused of beating
confessions out of Ms. Tyson and two witnesses in her murder case.
After many years, one witness admitted that he had lied, and it was
later learned that the other witness had never seen the victim with
Ms. Tyson.
</P>
<P>
   OPPOSITION TO INTERNET RESTRICTIONS
</P>
<P>
   Many law experts are dismayed at the restrictive legislation
being drafted and enacted by state and federal governments for use
of the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   DIET COKE BRINGS BACK CLASSIC ADS
</P>
<P>
   Coca-Cola has brought back spots for Diet Coke that initially
began appearing in early 1996.
</P>
<P>
   GROUP TO USE PHONE LINES FOR DATA
</P>
<P>
   Eleven high-technology companies, including IBM and Lucent, are
working jointly to develop standards for sending data at high
speeds over the copper telephone wiring in most houses and
apartments.
</P>
<P>
   EDITORS RE-EXAMINE FACT CHECKING
</P>
<P>
   Newspapers around the country are re-examining the accuracy of
what they print in the wake of the Boston Globe's dismissal of
Patricia Smith, a metropolitan region columnist.
</P>
<P>
   EVERYTHING'S UP TO DATE IN KANSAS
</P>
<P>
   Kansas is teaching the IRS how to deal with taxpayers. The state
has applied modern information technology and a customer-service
attitude to the task of processing income tax returns, creating an
operation that resembles the billing system of a credit card
company.
</P>
<P>
   PATENT FOR PAIN RELIEF TECHNIQUE
</P>
<P>
   The Journal of the American Medical Association reported last
week that many elderly people and cancer patients do not receive
enough medicine for pain relief. Aradigm Corp. has now patented a
technology that it says will make pain medication much easier to
administer.
</P>
<P>
   NBC TALKING WITH USA NETWORKS
</P>
<P>
   Will Barry Diller start making infomercials for NBC? NBC, which
began selling videocassettes directly to consumers in April, has
held talks about it with the head of USA Networks, the parent of
the Home Shopping Network.
</P>
</TEXT>
