<HEADER>
A9359 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CARAMOOR-MUSIC-FESTIV     06-21 0587
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CARAMOOR-MUSIC-FESTIVAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MUSIC REVIEW: CARAMOOR CONDUCTORS PUT BEL CANTO FIRST 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By JAMES R. OESTREICH   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   KATONAH, N.Y. _ In a profession in which ego plays a significant
and undoubtedly essential role, the conductors at the Caramoor
International Music Festival here seem a surprisingly selfless lot.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Oundjian, a violinist turned conductor, in this, the first
season he programmed as artistic director of the festival, ceded
its opening night Saturday night to Will Crutchfield and the bel
canto program he started last season.
</P>
<P>
   And Crutchfield, after an opening romp through the Overture to
Cimarosa's ``Matrimonio Segreto'' with the resident Orchestra of
St. Luke's, was content to play a backup role to operatic singers,
led by June Anderson, and to Soovin Kim, a violinist.
</P>
<P>
   As the main offering, the second half of the program consisted
of goodly chunks of Bellini's ``Norma,'' with Ms. Anderson in the
title role. A thunderstorm at the start merely heightened the
drama, and the heavy patter of rain on the tent of the Venetian
Theater gave the sense of a classic voice heard through the surface
noise of an old 78-rpm record.
</P>
<P>
   This sense was heightened by a certain fragile quality that has
entered Ms. Anderson's voice with wear. It remains a beautiful
instrument, however, and proved fully in its element here.
</P>
<P>
   With no stage trappings to help, Ms. Anderson pulled a listener
into the heart of the drama of the tormented Druid heroine through
sheer force of voice and personality. She drew from a rich palette
of colorations and achieved a consistent beauty of tone in haunting
quiet passages as well as in forceful outpourings. She was well
supported by a handful of other singers, led by Marguerite Krull, a
soprano who, as Adalgisa, sang elegantly and complemented Ms.
Anderson ideally as they traced the sinuous interflow in the duets
of the opening scene of Act II.
</P>
<P>
   Crutchfield gave the singers plenty of room to work, leading the
orchestra and a well-prepared Festival Chorus with flexible pace
and firm control of dynamics.
</P>
<P>
   He also did his work well in the first half of the program,
where matters were not always so happy. Ms. Anderson sang two
Mozart numbers, rising decently to Donna Anna's ``Non mi dir'' from
``Don Giovanni'' despite some sharpness of pitch and unevenness in
coloratura. Her vocalism sat heavily on ``L'amero, saro costante,''
from ``Il Re Pastore,'' though she introduced imaginative
ornamentation into the repeat of the opening.
</P>
<P>
   Kim, who rendered the obbligato violin part in that aria
stiffly, took center stage in Paganini's Violin Concerto No. 2 and
played it well: no small accomplishment in view of the work's
fiendish difficulties. But more is needed to make the tricks seem
more than calisthenics, to engage rather than merely entertain the
listener. It is a matter of temperament, which the young Kim may
acquire with experience.
</P>
<P>
   The Cimarosa overture was delightful. Here and everywhere else,
Crutchfield showed a fine rapport with the Orchestra of St. Luke's,
which never fails to impress with its versatility. Apart from an
occasional insecure attack or release and, in the Paganini, some
harshness in string ascents, there was little fault to find.
</P>
<P>
   Crutchfield, this time as pianist, is to present a Rossini
evening with Vivica Genaux, a soprano, on Friday, and Oundjian is
to conduct a varied orchestral program Saturday. The season runs to
Aug. 9.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
