</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CUPKEEPER: News of the odd &AMP; off-beat
 &HT;    By Wendy Parker
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WRONG TRANSLATION
</P>
<P>
   This is Croatia's first World Cup, one in which the Balkan
nation, freed from the yoke of hated Yugoslavia in 1991, proudly
has been showing off its independent checkerboard stripes.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine the indignation of Croatia coach Miroslav Blazevic and
his players when they arrived at a press conference following
Saturday's 1-0 win over Japan and were greeted by a Serbian
translator.
</P>
<P>
   When a Croatian diplomat offered to translate instead of a young
FIFA-assigned female volunteer from Belgrade, he was immediately
reproached.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a FIFA press conference,'' FIFA's Markus Siegler said.
``Even if the lady speaks with a Serb accent, I'm not going to
allow any politics in here.''
</P>
<P>
   But Croatian team spokesman Darko Tironi insisted that had
already happened.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are two different languages,'' he said. ``We will make a
complaint to FIFA.''
</P>
<P>
   FIFA assigned the translator.
</P>
<P>
   ONE MORE GOOOOOOOAL
</P>
<P>
   The famous cry of Univision announcer Andres Cantor following a
score is a standard three shrieks of GOOOOOOOOOOAL! _ even in Major
League Soccer. But when Mexico's Cuauhtemoc Blanco scored a
riveting goal Saturday to tie Belgium, Cantor was so awash in
excitement that he threw in a fourth rendition. Elapsed time: 11
seconds.
</P>
<P>
   PARREIRA BOOTED
</P>
<P>
   Coaching Saudi Arabia is like managing for George Steinbrenner.
After he lost his first two World Cup matches, coach Carlos Alberto
Parreira has been told not to bother showing up for his third, a
meaningless finale Wednesday against South Africa.
</P>
<P>
   Parreira, who led Brazil to the 1994 title, was fired on
Saturday and will be replaced with Mohammed al-Khuraishi for the
South Africa match. Saudi Arabia, the first team to be eliminated,
has gone through eight coaches in four years.
</P>
<P>
   Parreira was hired away from the New York/New Jersey MetroStars
of MLS.
</P>
<P>
   SCOTS GO HOME
</P>
<P>
   Scottish fans started off the World Cup enjoying some hearty
digs at England and its infamous hooligans. Now, Team Braveheart
followers have been stained.
</P>
<P>
   Several dozen troublemakers arrived in Glasgow Saturday after
being kicked out of both France and Spain for various incidents
that usually involved beer, nightclubs, arrests and property
damage.
</P>
<P>
   ``The atmosphere in the airport was, frankly, ugly,'' said a
27-year-old male Glaswegian about waiting with them to board a
flight from Salou, Spain.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
