<HEADLINE>
ACCOUNTS AND PEOPLE IN THE ADVERTISING WORLD 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Two Big Clients Consolidate Accounts
</P>
<P>
   Two advertisers have consolidated accounts.
</P>
<P>
   First Brand Corp. in Danbury, Conn., named McCann-Erickson New
York to handle consolidated duties for Glad plastic products, STP
automotive products and four cat litter brands. Combined billings
were estimated at $35 million.
</P>
<P>
   The decision came after a three-month review that had been
narrowed to four finalists, all of New York: McCann-Erickson, part
of the McCann-Erickson World Group unit of Interpublic Group of
Cos., which handles Scoop Away, Ever Clean, Jonny Cat and Ever
Fresh cat litters; Young &AMP; Rubicam Advertising, which handles STP;
Bozell Worldwide, part of True North Communications, and J. Walter
Thompson, a unit of WPP Group PLC.
</P>
<P>
   Glad had been handled by the Leo Burnett USA unit of Leo Burnett
Co. in Chicago, which resigned on June 12 because a conflict
prevented the agency from taking part in the review for the
consolidated account.
</P>
<P>
   And Kaiser Permanente in Oakland, Calif., named Rapp Collins
Worldwide in New York to handle its consolidated national direct
response account, with billings estimated at $24 million. The
account had been split among nine agencies.
</P>
<P>
   The decision came after a three-month review that had been
narrowed to Rapp Collins, part of Omnicom Group, and one other
finalist: Grey Direct in New York, part of Grey Advertising, which
continues as agency of record for Kaiser Permanente brand
advertising.
</P>
<P>
   Top Awards for Cliff Freeman
</P>
<P>
   For the first time in at least 20 years, one agency won Best of
Show in the broadcast and print categories at the American
Advertising Awards, sponsored by the American Advertising
Federation in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   At the presentation on Saturday night of the 30th annual Addy
Awards, which came during the federation's national conference in
Minneapolis, Cliff Freeman &AMP; Partners in New York, part of Saatchi
&AMP; Saatchi PLC, won the broadcast award for work for Fox Sports
Network, part of News Corp., and the print award for an ad for
Sauza Conmemorativo tequila, marketed by the Domecq Importers unit
of Allied Domecq PLC. Freeman also won seven other Addys for work
for accounts including Staples Inc. and Little Caesar Enterprises.
</P>
<P>
   Fallon McElligott in Minneapolis won seven Addys for clients
including BMW of North America and the Time magazine unit of Time
Warner Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Shuffling Done by 2 Advertisers
</P>
<P>
   Two advertisers have changed agencies.
</P>
<P>
   Hershey Foods Corp. in Hershey, Pa., expanded its relationship
with the New York office of DDB Needham Worldwide by naming the
agency to handle advertising for its retail pasta brands, which had
been handled by Pedone &AMP; Partners in New York. Billings were
estimated at $5 million to $10 million.
</P>
<P>
   DDB Needham New York, a unit of Omnicom Group that has worked
for Hershey since 1978, was awarded the pasta assignment _ brands
like Ronzoni, San Giorgio, American Beauty and Skinner _ without a
formal review. The agency has handled other Hershey accounts like
Kit Kat and York Peppermint Pattie candy and Hershey's Syrup.
</P>
<P>
   And Star Markets in Cambridge, Mass., named Heater Advertising
in Boston to handle its account, with billings estimated at $5
million to $8 million. The account had been handled by the Boston
office of North Castle Partners, which closed. The decision came
after a monthlong review in which the other participants were not
disclosed.
</P>
</TEXT>
