<HEADER>
A9363 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-ANIMATED-REVIEW-52     06-21 0739
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-ANIMATED-REVIEW-525&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`BOB AND MARGARET': ABSOLUTELY UNFABULOUS BUT MUDDLING THROUGH 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Production notes are at end of review. Time, channel are for
New York area. Check local listings.) 
(lb) 
 By CARYN JAMES   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the past year, viewers have been identifying with people made
of construction paper, colored ink or computer keystrokes. Fox's
hit ``King of the Hill,'' about a suburban family in Texas, and
Comedy Central's ``South Park,'' the M-rated phenomenon about
grammar school boys, have made animated comedies a major prime-time
trend and have shown how easy it is to see ourselves in cartoons.
</P>
<P>
   With so little realism on the surface, animated characters can
sneak up and irreverently hit plenty of nerves. The dunderheaded
fathers of ``The Simpsons'' or ``King of the Hill,'' much less the
boys of ``South Park,'' would never get on the air if they were
breathing actors.
</P>
<P>
   Now Comedy Central has come along with a wry animated series
that qualifies as the anti-``South Park.'' ``Bob and Margaret,''
about a middle-aged English couple, is as gently humorous and
grown-up as ``South Park'' is boisterous and adolescent, and the
new series may go further than any other in turning commonplace
behavior into humor.
</P>
<P>
   How unglamorous are Bob and Margaret? He is a dentist, she is a
podiatrist, and a typical plot might center on going to a gym
(which they desperately need and barely survive) or being robbed.
(Their favorite flowered teapot is stolen, but, on the bright side,
a bit of insurance fraud lets them trade up to a big-screen
television with Surroundsound.)
</P>
<P>
   With its bold visual look and understated humor, ``Bob and
Margaret'' brings to mind Nick Park's hilarious, inventive films
about Wallace and Gromit, a soft-spoken Englishman and his much
smarter dog. Drawn in broad strokes, the characters in ``Bob and
Margaret'' have large jaws, lumpy bodies, crazy hair.
</P>
<P>
   Margaret looks as if she has two croissants sticking out from
the side of her head, while Bob has a corkscrew on top of his.
Based on ``Bob's Birthday,'' which won the 1995 Academy Award for
best animated short, the series lacks the inspired lunatic touches
of ``Wallace and Gromit,'' but has an appealing, close-to-the-bone
wit of its own.
</P>
<P>
   In Monday's episode, Bob panics when a handsome young dentist
with sparkling new equipment moves into an office across the street
from his. It can't help that one of Bob's dental tools resembles a
pizza cutter; the series' exaggerations often come in such small
touches.
</P>
<P>
   When Margaret chips her tooth, Bob can't find time to fix it, so
she literally crosses the street and has the new dentist take care
of her. Of course, Bob discovers her infidelity. ``You drove me to
him, you drove me to see another dentist,'' Margaret cries, bawling
great swaths of pale blue tears as she runs into the bedroom.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know I neglected your tooth,'' Bob apologizes, standing
outside the locked door. ``I was just so busy.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Bob and Margaret'' usually goes along calmly until it hits one
of those priceless sequences, its lines expressed with massive
understatement. In a future episode, Bob and Margaret play sports
with another couple, only to have one of their partners land in the
hospital, victim of a tragic badminton accident. ``We'll have to
have a rematch as soon as Ken comes out of his coma,'' Bob says
soothingly.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Each episode ends with a calamitous revelation (quite a serious
one about what the new dentist might have done to Margaret) or a
disaster about to occur. These incidents are not picked up next
time, just allowed to hover like a dark cloud.
</P>
<P>
   With ``South Park,'' ``Bob and Margaret'' and ``Dr. Katz''
(which begins a new season Monday), Comedy Central virtually
controls prime-time animation, but Fox is on its heels. That
network's most promising new series, planned as midseason
replacements next year, are animated (one with Eddie Murphy's
voice). Sounding real, it seems, may be more important than having
a human body.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `BOB AND MARGARET'
</P>
<P>
   10:30 p.m. ET Monday on Comedy Central
</P>
<P>
   David Fine and Alison Snowden, creators. ``Bob and Margaret'' is
a Nelvana Limited/Channel 4 Television Corp. co-production,
produced in association with Comedy Central and Global, a CanWest
company.
</P>
</TEXT>
