<SLUG> BC-POLITICAL-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CALIFORNIA: POSITIONING FOR 2000 AT STAKE  
 NEVADA: BOTH SIDES BLINKED IN UNION DUES SHOWDOWN  
 AN ENDORSEMENT, OF SORTS, FOR GORE  
 MIXED RESULTS ON TERM LIMITS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   California: Positioning for 2000 At Stake
</P>
<P>
   A week ago, at a fund-raising dinner in Beverly Hills, President
Clinton said that 1998 provided Democrats with the first good
opportunity in ``quite a long time'' to capture the governorship of
California.
</P>
<P>
   ``And believe me,'' he added, an edge to his voice, ``we don't
need to blow it.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton was talking about something more than simply taking back
the governor's office of the nation's most populous state. What is
at stake in this fall's contest goes well beyond that.
</P>
<P>
   The next governor of California will preside over the redrawing
of the state's congressional boundaries after the 2000 census. He
will be in a position to approve or veto or force a compromise on
whatever reapportioning plan the Legislature comes up with for the
50-odd House districts in the state, slightly over half of them now
in Democratic hands.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, political pros say, the new governor's decision on
where lines should be redrawn and what political makeup should
result in each district could help his party pick up as many as a
dozen additional House seats _ and maybe even control of the House
of Representatives.
</P>
<P>
   In no other state are the reapportionment stakes so high. And in
no other state are the Democratic and Republican national parties
pouring in as much money and effort to elect a governor and, for
that matter, a Legislature that will be on his side once
redistricting actually begins.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has told California Lt. Gov. Gray Davis, the Democrats'
gubernatorial nominee, that he will shortly be back for more
campaigning and fund-raisers. Likewise, Vice President Al Gore
plans at least three trips to the state to help out _ visits that
won't hurt him one bit with California Democrats come the next
presidential election.
</P>
<P>
   As for the Republican gubernatorial nominee, state Attorney
General Dan Lungren, he is being helped in his campaign by a number
of major party figures, some of whom also have an eye on the next
presidential race.
</P>
<P>
   Texas Gov. George W. Bush and his father, the former president,
have held no fewer than five Lungren fund-raisers. Former Tennessee
Gov. Lamar Alexander has formed a Lungren fund-raising committee.
And former Rep. Jack Kemp, the 1996 Republican vice presidential
nominee, has headlined several Lungren galas.
</P>
<P>
   Both Sides Blinked In Nevada Showdown
</P>
<P>
   There's a new twist in the struggle over whether unions should
be able to spend members' dues on political causes without first
getting written permission.
</P>
<P>
   Labor won the first skirmish earlier this month, defeating a
California ballot initiative that would have required unions to
collect permission slips before spending any dues money on
politics. Labor leaders argued that the aim of the initiative, and
all others like it around the country, was to cripple the ability
of unions to recruit members and wield influence in the political
arena.
</P>
<P>
   The initiative's supporters argued it was a ``worker
protection'' measure.
</P>
<P>
   After the California victory, unions began gearing up to fight
similar ballot initiatives and legislative proposals in Colorado,
Nevada, New Jersey, Oregon and elsewhere. But the fight had hardly
been joined in Nevada when suddenly, last Tuesday, both sides
declared a truce and retreated from the field.
</P>
<P>
   Why?
</P>
<P>
   The Nevada initiative, put forth by Republican leaders, first
ran into trouble two weeks earlier when a state judge declared it
unconstitutional on the ground that it violated the First Amendment
right of association. He ordered election officials not to put it
on the November ballot.
</P>
<P>
   The measure's supporters vowed to appeal.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, union and Democratic leaders proposed a ballot
initiative that would prohibit any state regulation of union dues
and also would require all political candidates and parties to make
full disclosure of all contributions.
</P>
<P>
   Nevadans, it seemed, were about to be treated to dueling
initiatives.
</P>
<P>
   It never happened.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, facing the prospect that the duel would eat up money
and energy that might better be spent on local, state and Federal
election contests this fall, both sides pulled back their measures,
though not without some internal bickering in each camp.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a victory for everyone when we walk away alive,'' John
Mason, the chairman of the Nevada Republican Party, said after the
truce agreement was signed.
</P>
<P>
   An Endorsement, Of Sorts, for Gore
</P>
<P>
   Even as the dues spending fight was ending in Nevada, it was
picking up momentum in New Jersey, where Gore appeared in Elizabeth
last Monday to help labor leaders raise money for the struggle. But
that's not the news from that event.
</P>
<P>
   The news is what AFL-CIO president John Sweeney had to say about
the vice president, who not too long ago was no great favorite of
labor, given his outspoken support for the North American Free
Trade Agreement and its provisions for encouraging manufacturing
and job growth beyond this country's borders.
</P>
<P>
   First, Sweeney introduced Gore as ``the business agent for
today's unions.'' Then, with Gore basking in the glow of that high
praise, Sweeney soared even higher and waxed:
</P>
<P>
   ``Al Gore is the most prominent American leader since Franklin
Delano Roosevelt to be so strong in his advocacy on behalf of
workers.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a long way to Election 2000, and one introduction does not
a Presidential endorsement make, but ...
</P>
<P>
   Mixed Results On Term Limits
</P>
<P>
   Advocates of term limits have been unusually active this year.
In just about every state they have pressed candidates, especially
congressional candidates, to pledge to serve only a limited time in
office. Those candidates who have refused to make such a vow have
been sharply chastised in costly newspaper and broadcast
advertising campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   To what end?
</P>
<P>
   Clear-cut examples of specific legislators being elected or
turned out of office are hard to come by. For every claim of
success there is at least one other claim of failure.
</P>
<P>
   And what of passage of new term-limits laws, previously an area
in which term-limits advocates have enjoyed much success?
</P>
<P>
   Consider:
</P>
<P>
   On the June 2 primary ballot in California, voters were asked to
consider an initiative that instructed members of Congress to push
for passage of a constitutional amendment to limit congressional
terms. Pending adoption of that limit, candidates would be asked to
sign pledges of support for term limits and those who refused would
be publicly identified in ballot material.
</P>
<P>
   The measure's backers conceded even before it was placed on the
ballot that it might be unconstitutional, given that courts have
said that states must not interfere with federal election
procedures. But never mind, voters were told, give the measure a
shot anyway and, come the fall, a ``superior'' substitute would be
on the ballot, one that could withstand any legal challenge.
</P>
<P>
   The June initiative passed, narrowly, and presumably it now
faces a legal challenge.
</P>
<P>
   But come November there will be no ``superior'' substitute to
vote on. The term-limits forces may have succeeded in passing an
``inferior'' June initiative but they failed to come up with the
433,269 petition signatures required to win a place on the November
ballot for the ``superior'' substitute.
</P>
<P>
   Officials for U.S. Term Limits, one of the leading backers of
the substitute, characterized the failure as a ``minor setback.''
</P>
<P>
   POLITICAL CALENDAR: Primaries will be held in Utah on Tuesday
and there will be primary runoffs that day in Mississippi, New
Mexico and South Carolina.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-21-98 1812EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
