<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-21 18:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9374 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MULAN-EVOLVE-COX     06-21 0653
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MULAN-EVOLVE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Later, Prince Charming: Disney heroines set sights on more than
men
 &HT;    By Steve Murray and Eleanor Ringel
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ In the beginning, back in 1937, there was Snow White,
with her squeaky-clean image and her squeaky-clean dream that
someday her prince would come. Never mind that she spends most of
the movie co-habitating with seven vertically challenged men.
</P>
<P>
   Then, in 1950 came Cinderella, another nice girl with a Prince
Charming fetish. And at the end of the decade, in 1959, Sleeping
Beauty, who slept her way into her prince's arms. And let's not
forget Lady, whose sexual attraction for the rakishly declasse
Tramp is dissected in great detail in Whit Stillman's latest flick,
``The Last Days of Disco.''
</P>
<P>
   Beauties all. Not necessarily brainless beauties, either. But
what did any of them really want out of life besides the right to
live happily ever after with the right guy?
</P>
<P>
   Things changed for females in the late '60s and '70s, but in the
wonderful world of Disney, change didn't come so quickly. Aside
from Miss Bianca in ``The Rescuers,'' female leading characters
were virtually banished from Disney animated features. Then, in
1989, along came ``The Little Mermaid'' and a plucky dish out of
water named Ariel. Nine years later, ``Mulan'' (which opened at No.
2 at the box office this weekend) has taken the Magic Kingdom into
a new era of Girl Power.
</P>
<P>
   Ariel
</P>
<P>
   Her movie: ``The Little Mermaid'' (1989)
</P>
<P>
   Her look: Partly fishy lass with big red hair and clam shell
push-up bra.
</P>
<P>
   Her personality: Yearning to explore the airy other world above
the ocean, even if she risks her life.
</P>
<P>
   Significant other: Prince Eric, a mopey, bland bit of royalty.
</P>
<P>
   Moral of the story: Someday you'll find your prince, but only if
you go for a makeover, like losing your tail and gills.
</P>
<P>
   Snow White, eat my dust: Doesn't sweep floors, disobeys dad and
she finds and saves her prince, not the other way around.
</P>
<P>
   Belle
</P>
<P>
   Her movie: ``Beauty and the Beast'' (1991)
</P>
<P>
   Her look: Proper French bourgeois who actually takes time
twisting her hair into a 'do, unlike these hang-loose other
heroines.
</P>
<P>
   Her personality: Yearning to be left alone by handsome, mean
Gaston, so she can read her books in peace; smart but kind.
</P>
<P>
   Significant other: The Beast, a prince transformed for
selfishness.
</P>
<P>
   Moral of the story: Sometimes a big tough guy really needs love,
because at heart he's just Robby Benson talking in a deep voice.
</P>
<P>
   Snow White, eat my dust: A dark forest wouldn't freak her out
the way it does Miss White; plus, she falls in love with the Beast
because of his soul, not his looks or lineage.
</P>
<P>
   Her movie: ``Pocahontas'' (1995)
</P>
<P>
   Her look: The original Native American Breck Girl, partial to
smartly tailored buckskin frocks.
</P>
<P>
   Her personality: Go-getting, nature-loving, maize-growing,
pro-integration gal.
</P>
<P>
   Significant other: John Smith
</P>
<P>
   Moral of the story: Honor your heritage but welcome other
cultural traditions. And never trust a blond, 'cause he'll only
break your heart.
</P>
<P>
   Snow White, eat my dust: She's more interested in what's right
for her people and her land than in landing a boyfriend; in a
Disney first, she doesn't get the guy.
</P>
<P>
   Her movie: ``Mulan'' (1998)
</P>
<P>
   Her look: Tomboyish as a bride in training, but brawny as a
soldier (thanks to padded armor and a haircut).
</P>
<P>
   Her personality: Yearning to save her family's honor _ and her
father's life _ by proving herself a worthy fighter.
</P>
<P>
   Significant other: Shang, the hunky young commander of her
military unit.
</P>
<P>
   Moral of the story: Sometimes you have to break rules to do what
you know is right.
</P>
<P>
   Snow White, eat my dust: Can you see Snow in armor, shooting a
cannon and kicking Hun butt? No, I don't think so.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
