<DOCNO> NYT19980621.0088 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-21 18:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9375 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TVSURFER-COLUMN22-COX     06-21 0494
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TVSURFER-COLUMN22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Grab yourself a seat on `Dr. Katz's' couch
 &HT;    By Drew Jubera
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Comedy Central's ``South Park'' gets its laughs and acclaim
being rude and crude. ``Dr. Katz: Professional Therapist,'' its
less-hyped animated counterpart, gets its grins being dry and
droll. Really dry and droll.
</P>
<P>
   ``Can we synchronize our watches?'' the balding, edgeless,
mildly mild Dr. Jonathan Katz (voiced by the comic of the same
name) asks his layabout, live-at-home son, Ben, over the phone,
trying to set up an important call for later in the morning. ``I
have exactly 8:24.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no watch,'' Ben answers.
</P>
<P>
   ``In that case,'' says Dr. Katz, not missing a beat, ``I'm going
to take off my watch. We're going to synchronize our wrists.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe you had to be there. But ``Dr. Katz'' is back at 10
tonight for its fifth season, squiggly and wry as ever. Dr. Katz
is, of course, a divorced New York therapist, a kind of thinking
man's Homer Simpson, for whom dysfunction is normal. Each week real
comics, in animated form (or ``squiggle vision,'' as the vibrating
line drawings are known), take a seat on Dr. Katz's office couch
and unload their problems.
</P>
<P>
   Tonight's main attraction is chain-smoking Denis Leary.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way I was brought up, two men sitting in a room discussing
things is ... interrogation,'' he tells Dr. Katz. ``I'm Irish, so
we have our own way of dealing with feelings. Basically, keep it
bottled up until you explode.''
</P>
<P>
   It's only a matter of time before ``Dr. Katz'' reaches college
cult status, like ``South Park.'' Just wait until Kenny, Stan, Kyle
and Cartman are old enough to need therapy.
</P>
<P>
   Comedy Central introduces another animated series, ``Bob and
Margaret,'' at 10:30, after ``Dr. Katz.'' It's a British import
based on the 1995 Oscar-winning short film, ``Bob's Birthday,'' and
revolves around the eccentricities of dentist Bob and podiatrist
wife Margaret.
</P>
<P>
   It's clever and sneakily nasty in an unrelenting,
don't-laugh-out-loud way (``Britain can be the best place in the
world, bad teeth-wise''). It's hard not to be impressed. It's also
hard to like this prickly, self-absorbed couple enough to want to
watch them every week.
</P>
<P>
   But like many of our favorite cartoon misanthropes (have we
already mentioned ``South Park''?), we're willing to accept that
``Bob and Margaret'' is an acquired taste _ one we may yet acquire.
</P>
<P>
   Grades: ``Dr. Katz'' A-; ``Bob and Margaret'' B
</P>
<P>
   QUICK HITS
</P>
<P>
   ABC has begun production on an American version of ``Whose Line
Is It Anyway?'' that will air later this summer. It's a takeoff on
the popular British series with comic actors performing unrehearsed
skits. Drew Carey will host. ... Tennis buffs can see early-round
Wimbledon matches at 9 a.m. each weekday this week on HBO.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: channelsurfer(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
