<DOCNO> NYT19980621.0090 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-21 18:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9378 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOWIE-COX     06-21 0645
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOWIE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    No rubber gloves, promises new talk show host Mandel
 &HT;    By Lyle V. Harris
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The interview with Howie Mandel was going great.
</P>
<P>
   He's been doing media ``phoners'' from Los Angeles to promote
the debut of his self-titled daytime talk show, and he's chatting a
mile a minute about the guests, the band, and how he's working in
the same studio that his idol, Johnny Carson, used for ``The
Tonight Show'' _ the same studio where Mandel got his big TV break
in 1984.
</P>
<P>
   Then the rubber glove question comes up and there's a pause _ a
long, uncomfortable silence that feels like all the oxygen is being
sucked out of the room Mandel's in even though he's 2,000 miles
away.
</P>
<P>
   Back when Mandel was known as a geek-a-zoid stand-up comic, he'd
put a rubber glove on his head, blow real hard and inflate it like
a balloon. Big laughs then. Not so funny now.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't put a glove on my head in 12 years,'' Mandel says
with the don't-mess-with-me resolve of someone who has completed a
12-step recovery program. ``But people are welcome to do that in
the privacy of their own homes if they want.''
</P>
<P>
   A joke. That's a good sign. But don't be fooled. This guy
doesn't sound like the wacky Mandel who played the Afro'd Dr. Wayne
Fiscus on TV's old medical drama ``St. Elsewhere'' or the cuddly
inner-child Mandel who created, and starred in two Saturday morning
kiddie shows: ``Bobby's World'' and ``The Amazing Live Sea
Monkeys.''
</P>
<P>
   No, this is Howard Mandel, the all-grown-up syndicated talk show
host.
</P>
<P>
   ``This show is giving me an opportunity to be me,'' Mandel says,
perking up again. ``I've been married 20 years and I'll talk about
what's going on in my house and in my life and with my kids. I'm
not doing gags. The stories I'll be talking about will be organic,
not produced or fake.''
</P>
<P>
   Mandel says the show will feature ``host chat'' with his studio
audience, pre-taped comedy bits, man- (or woman-) on-the-street
segments, variety acts and, of course, the requisite celebrity
guests. Today's lineup is Jennifer Aniston, Arsenio Hall and Usher.
Ted Danson, Chris Rock, Lionel Richie, Clint Black, Tyra Banks and
Paul Reiser have also been booked for the first week.
</P>
<P>
   The show's musical director is Steve Goldstein, who has scored
several films, including ``The Birdcage'' and ``Primary Colors.''
The seven-piece band also has two members of the R&AMP;B group Tower of
Power. Actress Brianne Leary was slated to be Mandel's on-camera
sidekick, but she didn't click with test audiences and has been
dropped.
</P>
<P>
   Mandel says he got hooked on the idea of hosting while filling
in on ``Live With Regis &AMP; Kathie Lee,'' the ratings-successful
boy-girl daytime tandem. Mandel says he was also inspired by
Carson, Merv Griffin, Mike Douglas, Dinah Shore and Jack Paar _ the
golden age talkers whose style and success he hopes to emulate.
</P>
<P>
   But the talk show circuit has become a graveyard of good
intentions (remember Carnie Wilson? Tempestt Bledsoe? Danny
Bonaduce?), and only a handful of hosts have done it very well or
very long.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think anybody sets out to make a bad show,'' Mandel
says. ``This format was originated by Jack Paar, and it works
because of the person sitting behind the desk. That's why we watch
(Jay) Leno and (David) Letterman.''
</P>
<P>
   Mandel has a built-in following from his days as stand-up comic
and actor, but the big question remains: Can a former rubber
glovehead ever be taken seriously as a daytime talk show host?
</P>
<P>
   ``Regardless of what you've done before, when you're spending an
hour in someone's home every day, they will decide very quickly
whether they want to be with you or someone else,'' Mandel says.
``I don't care if I'm No. 1 in my time slot or if I win an Emmy.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
