<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-21 18:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9382 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BRAVES-MAIN22-COX     06-21 0573
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRAVES-MAIN22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Braves finish series with Expos, move on to NY
 &HT;    By Jack Wilkinson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONTREAL _ Despite their denials, surely they want to be a part
of it: New York, New York, then Atlanta, Atlanta. How else to
explain how listless the Braves were for most of the weekend?
Surely, they overlooked the Expos in anticipation of tonight's
Yankee biggie in the Bronx.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, facing a reclamation project named Shawn Boskie,
Atlanta was humbled 14-1, its worst loss in four years. On Sunday,
after the encouraging Saturday night return of John Smoltz, the
Braves stumbled against another right-hander with no prior success
against Atlanta. Dustin Hermanson allowed just five hits in eight
innings and, save for Michael Tucker's solo homer, frustrated
Atlanta in Montreal's 4-1 victory.
</P>
<P>
   That denied the Braves a 15th straight series win over Montreal,
which hadn't taken a series from Atlanta since 1994. It also gave
Expos manager Felipe Alou his 500th career victory, who savored it
even more coming against Bobby Cox.
</P>
<P>
   ''What makes me happy is it was against a man I really respect,
who has never been given the credit he deserves,'' Alou said.
''It's not his fault he has a great team.''
</P>
<P>
   Not this weekend. ''Hermanson looked good,'' Cox said of a guy
who never started until last season, was 0-2 lifetime against the
Braves with a 5.40 ERA and was making his fourth start since coming
off the disabled list. Denny Neagle? He looked like he has for the
last month: Beset by bad luck, undone by one bad inning.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is how it's been going for me,'' Neagle said after losing
for the fourth time in five starts and dropping to 8-5. ''With the
exception of the Boston game, every game I've lost, with a break
here or there, I could've won. These games are frustrating.''
</P>
<P>
   Neagle's now lost as many games as he did all last season when,
at 20-5, he was the NL's lone 20-game winner. The sixth-inning,
leadoff homer by Shane Andrews was the 16th surrendered by Neagle
(seventh in his last four starts), just two fewer than he allowed
last year.
</P>
<P>
   But the third inning was decisive, when the Expos batted around
and scored three times. This after Neagle had retired the first
nine batters in order.
</P>
<P>
   ''He threw three perfect innings,'' Javy Lopez said. ''After
that, he started missing some pitches in the middle of the plate.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet it was a pitch out of the strike zone that hurt Neagle
badly. F.P. Santangelo was the first Expo to reach when Neagle hit
him to start the fourth. Santangelo advanced on a sacrifice bunt,
then scored on Ozzie Guillen's error. After Rondell White's double
(''I threw it without any conviction and left it up,'' Neagle
said), Andrews was walked intentionally to load the bases.
</P>
<P>
   Neagle got ahead of Mark Grudzielanek 1-2, then threw a good
changeup down-and-away that Grudzielanek chased and slapped for a
two-run single. ''That's what's frustrating,'' Neagle said.
''Sometimes it happens that way. You make good pitches and it ends
up that way.''
</P>
<P>
   Lopez thought the good pitch could've been even better. ''On
1-2, you've still got three pitches to walk him,'' he said. ''In
that situation, the perfect pitch is you throw it in the dirt.''
</P>
<P>
   No way. Not this weekend. ''A series is a series,'' said Cox.
''I'm going to go to New York.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
