<HEADER>
A9385 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRO     06-21 0670
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
     THE NEWS WOMEN HAVE BEEN WAITING FOR
<TEXT>
<P>
   What with baby-boomers of the female persuasion wringing their
hands, furrowing their brows and working themselves up into
frenzies over the passing years and the ebb of hormones, thank
goodness  &UR; Cybill Shepherd &LR;  is offering advice.
</P>
<P>
   The venue, of course, is People magazine. The subject is
menopause.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had quite intense hot flashes for about three months,''
writes the 48-year-old actress in a searing first-person account.
``So far this year they seem to have subsided. The people I worked
with were very helpful. ... They'd get me ice water.''
</P>
<P>
   But even women who don't have water carriers can survive. ``My
advice for women entering menopause,'' writes Shepherd, ``is to
trust your feelings.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; KISSING MINNIE DRIVER &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  A profile of  &UR; Minnie Driver &LR; , the sexy British actress whose
on-screen romance with  &UR; Matt Damon &LR;  in ``Good Will Hunting'' led to
an off-screen affair and then a very public breakup, is profiled in
the latest issue of Elle magazine.
</P>
<P>
   Driver's co-star in ``The Governess,'' a movie set to open later
this month, is  &UR; Tom Wilkinson &LR; , 50, who plays the father of her
ward, and also her secret lover. ``In amateur theatricals,'' he
told Elle, ``the Romeo and Juliet always have affairs. And it's a
tendency of the young to plunge everything into their work.'' Most
experienced actors have learned to express emotion without
experiencing it, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kissing is tremendously erotic. I've never kissed somebody and
gone away without a lingering, `What if? ...' I'm sort of used to
it, but for younger people, it's still exciting and surprising that
it's okay to kiss the beautiful stranger.''
</P>
<P>
   As to Driver, ``I hate watching her get chewed up by these
relationships. I saw something in a gossip column about her kissing
some guy at a party, and I thought, Minnie, go home, make some
Ovaltine and go to bed.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR;   &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   - In downtown San Francisco on Wednesday,  &UR; Fran Johns &LR;  saw a
``huge red and white truck complete with upended bed and a
prominent sign on the back'' that read ``International Garbage
Only.'' Now what was  &LR; that &LR;  all about?
</P>
<P>
   - More Beatles animal rights songs, as per  &UR; Johnny &LR; 
 &UR; Miller &LR; : ``Martha My Deer''; ``Penny Loon,'' ``Snake Rattle and
Roll'' and ``The Long and Winding Roe.''
</P>
<P>
   - Personals walks the plank:  &UR; Dennis Conner &LR;  has nothing to do
with America True, the America's Cup vessel being built at Pier 17;
 &UR; Dawn Riley &LR;  is captain and CEO. The fund-raiser is private, by
invitation only.
</P>
<P>
   - Ambling down Irving Street in San Francisco,  &UR; Tim Robinson &LR; 
overheard one pedestrian say to another, ``When we're taking a
shower together, smell is the last sense that comes to mind.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; - Tom Abate &LR;  attended a National Writers' Workshop a few months
ago that included an appearance by  &UR; Patricia Smith &LR; , the Boston
Globe columnist who lost her job last week after she admitted
fabricating quotes and characters. ``Take risks,'' said a brochure
description of Smith's philosophy. ``Create a new set of rules for
yourself. ... If you believe there is no room for real creativity
in journalism, then amshay on ooyay.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; - Samuel Berger &LR; , assistant to the president for national
security affairs, writes in the World Affairs Council newsletter
that the U.S. debt to the U.N. could be paid off for about $4 a
year per American, ``about the price of a Happy Meal at
McDonald's.''  &UR; David Fischer &LR; , former president of the council,
suggests an additional incentive: ``Maybe if they throw in a Beanie
Baby, we could get them to pay.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``How did Hillary miss Monica? What was she thinking? Why &LR; 
 &UR; didn't she insist on only male interns? In my White House, all &LR; 
 &UR; interns would look like James Carville. This approach has worked &LR; 
 &UR; well for the Royal Family.'' &LR;
</P>
<P>
   -  &UR; Bette Midler &LR; 's advice to wives, in Town &AMP; Country.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-21-98 1842EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980621.0095 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-21 18:43 </DATE_TIME>
