   - Personals walks the plank:  &UR; Dennis Conner &LR;  has nothing to do
with America True, the America's Cup vessel being built at Pier 17;
 &UR; Dawn Riley &LR;  is captain and CEO. The fund-raiser is private, by
invitation only.
</P>
<P>
   - Ambling down Irving Street in San Francisco,  &UR; Tim Robinson &LR; 
overheard one pedestrian say to another, ``When we're taking a
shower together, smell is the last sense that comes to mind.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; - Tom Abate &LR;  attended a National Writers' Workshop a few months
ago that included an appearance by  &UR; Patricia Smith &LR; , the Boston
Globe columnist who lost her job last week after she admitted
fabricating quotes and characters. ``Take risks,'' said a brochure
description of Smith's philosophy. ``Create a new set of rules for
yourself. ... If you believe there is no room for real creativity
in journalism, then amshay on ooyay.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; - Samuel Berger &LR; , assistant to the president for national
security affairs, writes in the World Affairs Council newsletter
that the U.S. debt to the U.N. could be paid off for about $4 a
year per American, ``about the price of a Happy Meal at
McDonald's.''  &UR; David Fischer &LR; , former president of the council,
suggests an additional incentive: ``Maybe if they throw in a Beanie
Baby, we could get them to pay.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``How did Hillary miss Monica? What was she thinking? Why &LR; 
 &UR; didn't she insist on only male interns? In my White House, all &LR; 
 &UR; interns would look like James Carville. This approach has worked &LR; 
 &UR; well for the Royal Family.'' &LR;
</P>
<P>
   -  &UR; Bette Midler &LR; 's advice to wives, in Town &AMP; Country.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service) &QL;  &LR;
