<HEADLINE>
ELWAY PARDONED FOR MISSING D.C. PARTY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TOM HOFFARTH  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Super Bowl MVP John Elway skipped a trip to the White House last
week for a knee checkup (the MRI came up clean) and a tee time at
Inverness Golf Club in Denver.
</P>
<P>
   ``John's been to the White House before,'' Broncos coach Mike
Shanahan said. ``It's not like it's his first time.''
</P>
<P>
   Is that an excuse we can live with?
</P>
<P>
   Elway's secretary, Kathy Hatch, said the absence wasn't entirely
caused by a sore knee.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got a bunch of stuff to do this week and he pretty much
decided that it was an overload to fit that White House visit in
because it wasn't required by the team,'' Hatch said. ``There are
only so many hours in the day.''
</P>
<P>
   Then again, maybe it was politics.
</P>
<P>
   Elway is an ardent Republican who reportedly has considered
running for Congress.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Clinton handled the situation with presidential
grace.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're sorry he couldn't be here,'' said Clinton, who mentioned
Elway's achievements in his remarks to the media. ``We're glad he's
OK.... Maybe the most remarkable thing about winning the Super Bowl
was the loyalty of the community and the steadfastness of John
Elway.''
</P>
<P>
   Cheerio, MJ: Kellogg had planned to issue a Corn Flakes box
featuring the NBA champion Chicago Bulls on the front, but the NBA
said the company couldn't because Michael Jordan is a spokesman for
General Mills, which makes Wheaties.
</P>
<P>
   The NBA and Battle Creek, Mich.-based Kellogg said earlier this
month they had an agreement for Kellogg to be the NBA's
breakfast-food sponsor. They planned to issue a commemorative
cereal box with the championship winner.
</P>
<P>
   Until the Bulls won. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
