<HEADLINE>
IT'S A STANDING (KOURNIK)OVATION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TOM HOFFARTH  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   For the next two weeks at Ye Olde All-England Lawn Tennis
Championships in Londontown, there will be ye young tennis starlet
Anna Kournikova as the target of sneers and jeers, yet revered by
the media.
</P>
<P>
   That's what happened last year, too. Why?
</P>
<P>
   a) 'Cause she's cute.
</P>
<P>
   b) 'Cause she knows it.
</P>
<P>
   c) 'Cause she'll probably be hanging out with that two-timer (as
in twice winner of the Stanley Cup) who maybe should be known to
the 16-year-old as ``Uncle Sergei.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe that kinda kids' stuff plays in Siberia. Maybe in England,
it plays in the tabloids. But over here, where even a simple
traffic signal knows when it's right to stop and go, we tend to get
a little uptight about these March-July relationships.
</P>
<P>
   Before jetting off to the site of some of her greatest
professional triumphs, Martina Navratilova was queried about
Kournikova's sex-appeal marketing technique and how she flaunts
herself around hockeystud Sergei Fedorov .
</P>
<P>
   ``I have had a lot of people speculate on my relationships; I
won't talk about that,'' said the ex-tennis champ working on HBO's
coverage. ``She's drop-dead gorgeous, but she hasn't backed it up
on the court yet. I do have problems with people being cocky and
arrogant when they haven't won a thing.'' . . .
</P>
<P>
   _ The oldest competitor at the X-Games in San Diego is
45-year-old street luger Steve Fernando of Van Nuys. Which seems
kinda like allowing a teen-ager with shoes into the plastic ballpit
at Chuck E. Cheese. . . .
</P>
<P>
   _ Wildly opinionated Bill Walton gave this assessment to the
Boston Globe on the three UCLA players ( Toby Bailey, J.R.
Henderson and Jelani McCoy ) who think they're headed for the NBA
in Wednesday's draft: ``Toby is an incredible athlete, but he
doesn't have a real game. J.R. is going to have trouble in the NBA
playing power forward because that is where the meanest, nastiest,
dirtiest guys play. Jelani is an incredible talent, but he hasn't
yet shown he can respond to coaching.'' . . .
</P>
<P>
   _ Adidas is the top official shoe supplier to the 32-team World
Cup soccer tournament, footing the bill for seven countries. Nike
is second with six (including the U.S.). Could have been seven, but
Indonesia didn't make the field. . . .
</P>
<P>
   _ Prediction: World Cup '98 will end up with more ties than the
post-Father's Day return counter at Macy's today. . .
</P>
<P>
   _ Our imitation of Andres Cantor livening up a golf telecast:
``It's in the HOOOOOOOOOOOOOOOOOOLE!'' . . .
</P>
<P>
   _ The Almighty Ducks proved again they're one mucked-up
!ital!or-gan-EYE-za-shun in how it clumsily handled the ouster of
Pierre Page _ the same guy who took them months and months just to
hire last offseason. Once again, Gordon Bombay waits in the Ducks'
wings to take the job that's rightly his. . . .
</P>
<P>
   _ Critique of the Kings' new unis: The players can moonlight as
waiters at Medieval Times. . . .
</P>
<P>
   _ This week's L.A. Business Journal decided Rupert Murdoch was
the wealthiest man in the city with a personal fortune of $4.9
billion. That would make Murdoch employee
</P>
<P>
   Raul Mondesi the most fortunate man in the city with a wealth of
lawyers at his disposal. . . .
</P>
<P>
   _ Someone please shoot down the latest Bud Selig trial balloons.
. . .
</P>
<P>
   _ Studio City's Eddie Frierson , star of his one-man tribute to
Christy Mathewson called ``Matty,'' throws out the first pitch of
Friday's Rangers-Giants game in S.F. In his Mathewson attire, of
course. . . .
</P>
<P>
   _ The AFI's much-yakked about list of the top 100 American
feature films was predictably short on sports-related flicks. Not
that ``The Fish That Saved Pittsburgh'' measures up to Martin
Scorsese's ``Raging Bull'' (No. 24) or Sylvester Stallone's
portrayal of ``Rocky'' (No. 78).
</P>
<P>
   How about ``The Hustler''?
</P>
<P>
   Or ``Pride of the Yankees''?
</P>
<P>
   Or ``Hoosiers''? . . .
</P>
<P>
   _ Was ``Midnight Cowboy'' about Michael Irvin ? . . .
</P>
<P>
   _ Leigh ``Show Me The Movies'' Steinberg , the agentpreneur
!ital!soooo busy these days as a theatrical technical adviser, has
started an entertainment consulting division for media projects at
his agency. The man supposedly the model for ``Jerry Maguire'' is
currently giving his two million cents' worth to Oliver Stone ,
who's making a soon-to-be-controversial NFL-themed flick called
``On Any Given Sunday,'' starring
</P>
<P>
   Al Pacino, Cameron Diaz and rapper Puffy Combs as the next Cuba
Gooding Jr. . Steinberg also appeared as himself on the HBO drama
``Arli$$'' on Sunday night. . . .
</P>
<P>
   _ QVC says it sold more than 67,000 pieces of Bulls championship
junk when the series ended last Sunday. . . .
</P>
<P>
   _ Rodman alert: The ABL signed OPI Products as its official
nail-care provider. &QL;
</P>
