<HEADLINE>
CONFERENCE TAKES ON INTERNET PRIVACY AGAIN  
 COPYRIGHT TREATY RAISES CONCERNS ON RESEARCH  
 SMALL START-UP TO OFFER FIRST HDTV BROADCASTS 
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: Mo., N.C., Wash.) (Eds: Bylines follow individual items.) 
 (bl)  
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Conference Takes On Internet Privacy Again
</P>
<P>
   If the Commerce Department's weekly conference calls are any
indication, the chief result of its summit meeting on Internet
privacy in Washington this week will very likely be frustration on
all sides.
</P>
<P>
   With nearly 75 representatives from government, industry and
civil liberties groups burning up the phone lines during marathon
sessions recently on such topics as children's privacy and
legislative alternatives to self-regulation, the dialogue has
followed a distinctly predictable pattern.
</P>
<P>
   ``Industry says, `This is what we're doing to protect privacy;
we say, `It's not enough,''' Mark Rotenberg, the director of the
Electronic Privacy Information Center in Washington, said in an
interview. ``It's kind of a nightmare actually.''
</P>
<P>
   Arguing that the growth of the Internet and electronic commerce
depends on the government's staying out of the way, the Clinton
administration has advocated a policy of self-policing to address
widespread concern by Internet users over their personal privacy on
line. But in the wake of a Federal Trade Commission report that
found the online industry had taken virtually no steps over the
last year to ensure consumer privacy, that position is getting
harder to defend.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the agenda for this week's privacy conference is
chock-full of industry panels with titles like ``Evaluating the
Effectiveness of Self-Regulation.''
</P>
<P>
   And a group of about 50 companies and associations is set to
announce the creation of an ``online privacy alliance,'' whose
members will have to take a pledge to participate in ``effective
and appropriate self-regulatory enforcement activities and
mechanisms.''
</P>
<P>
   Following the summit meeting, the Commerce Department is
supposed to submit its own report to President Clinton next month
evaluating the state of online privacy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do I expect that on the first of July we'll be able to say
effective self-regulation is in place; no, absolutely not,'' said
Becky Burr, the assistant secretary of commerce. ``But somebody
told me U.S. businesses often rally in the last few minutes of the
game.'' _ AMY HARMON
</P>
<P>
   Copyright Treaty Raises Concerns on Research
</P>
<P>
   Legislation intended to strengthen international copyright
protections in cyberspace has run into an unexpected enemy: some of
the United States' best computer-security experts.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed bill would ratify two international treaties
negotiated under the authority of the World Intellectual Property
Organization, both of which have the backing of some of the
nation's largest media companies and software publishers.
</P>
<P>
   But language in the House bill, which is expected to come before
the Commerce Committee this week, has alarmed computer security
experts, who say that House Resolution 2281 would make it illegal
for them to carry out their basic work in testing computer security
by barring attempts to break the security safeguards used to
prevent unauthorized copying of creative work published on line.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why should security products be exempt from Consumer
Reports-style analysis?'' said Bruce Schneier, president of
Counterpane Systems, a security consulting firm in Minneapolis.
</P>
<P>
   But backers of the House bill said that the proposed law was
broader than the treaty because it was intended to keep people from
undermining online copyright protection.
</P>
<P>
   The bill was sent forward by the House Commerce Subcommittee on
Telecommunications, Trade and Consumer Protection last week, and is
to be reviewed this week by the full House Commerce Committee. _
JOHN MARKOFF
</P>
<P>
   Small Start-Up to Offer First HDTV Broadcasts
</P>
<P>
   After years of high-profile planning for high-definition
television, the first regularly scheduled national HDTV broadcasts
will be by a company with a decidedly low profile.
</P>
<P>
   The start-up company, Unity Motion, based in St. Louis, plans to
transmit its first experimental programming Tuesday at a
demonstration in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to show that we really can broadcast,'' said Sean
Henry, a company vice president. ``Up to now we've just been a
small company nobody's ever heard of.''
</P>
<P>
   Unity Motion, which was founded six years ago, received a
financial infusion in February from Marion Bass Securities, a
venture capital firm in Charlotte, N.C. Using that money, Unity
Motion has ambitious plans for a direct-broadcast satellite HDTV
service.
</P>
<P>
   Starting in September and using leased space on a Telstar
satellite, the company intends to begin full-time broadcasting of
two channels of high-definition programming _ movies, sports and
other entertainment shows, from programmers still to be announced.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of 1998, the company hopes to have four to six
channels on the air and 30 within two years.
</P>
<P>
   As with all early HDTV broadcasts, receiving the service will
require real motivation on the part of the consumer. A subscriber
will need a small satellite dish and a Unity Motion receiver box
that, together, will sell for $2,495.
</P>
<P>
   These will not be compatible with other satellite television
services. Until the first HDTV sets go on sale in the fall at a
price of $7,000 or more, the only televisions capable of displaying
these or any other HDTV signals will be expensive projection TV
sets capable of showing high-resolution images.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps to give consumers a financial breather, Unity Motion
will not begin charging its monthly subscription fee of $30 or $40
until next spring. _ JOEL BRINKLEY
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
