<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-21 19:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9430 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AUSTRIA-POPE-395&AMP;ADD-     06-21 0831
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUSTRIA-POPE-395&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POPE URGES AUSTRIA'S BISHOPS TO END THEIR BICKERING 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By ALESSANDRA STANLEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   VIENNA, Austria _ Seeking to restore discipline to Austria's
deeply divided Roman Catholic Church, Pope John Paul II instructed
the country's bishops Sunday to stop their public bickering.
Without unity, the pope warned, ``the teachings of Christ dissolve
into many individual voices. In the place of harmony comes noisy
confusion.''
</P>
<P>
   Austria, which is 78 percent Catholic, is a prosperous country
swept by the kind of religious disaffection and dissent that runs
throughout Western Europe and the United States and that that is
the bane of John Paul II's pontificate in his twilight years.
</P>
<P>
   On his three-day visit, which ended Sunday, the pope's three
Masses were eagerly attended by believers, but the crowds were
small and restrained compared with the vast and jubilant seas of
humanity that greeted him on recent trips to Nigeria and Cuba, poor
nations hungry for the solace and attention of the bishop of Rome.
</P>
<P>
   The pope came on a pastoral mission to try to heal a vast rift
within the Austrian church _ and among its leaders _ that has
opened up since his last visit in 1988. The leader of the church
here, Cardinal Christoph Schoenborn spoke of the problems very
directly in his words of welcome to the pope before Sunday's Mass,
speaking of the ``conflicts in our church which have caused some
people to lose confidence in the pope and his bishops.''
</P>
<P>
   But the pope did not indulge those Catholics who for the last
few years have been demanding sweeping reform and democratization
of the church. Nor did he address the sex scandal that forced the
resignation of a cardinal and which remains a deeply contested
issue. Throughout his trip, he urged Austrians and other rich
Europeans to return to religion, calling for ``hearts that beat not
just for career and money, but for God and mankind.''
</P>
<P>
   The pope, who Sunday beatified three saints, including Restituta
Kafka, a nun who was beheaded by the Nazis, also spoke of the need
for Christians to reconcile with Jews. As he spoke to 50,000 people
assembled on Heldenplatz (Heroes Square), the site where several
hundred thousand Austrians rushed to greet Hitler after the
Anschluss in 1938, the pope reminded his audience of that day.
``Sixty years ago a man declared himself the Savior,'' he said.
``The new saints carry another message: salvation is not in man,
but in Christ.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   As he delivered his homilies, he made clear that his opposition
to issues dear to reformers has not wavered. And perhaps most
emphatically, he told the bishops of Austria, who are also divided
along ideological lines, to shape up.
</P>
<P>
   ``One bishop alone does not realize the project of Christ,'' the
pope said in a speech to the leaders of the church. ``A promising
process of dialogue can be disrupted by a premature or inadequate
involvement of public opinion.''
</P>
<P>
   The pope's remarks followed a highly public comment by one
bishop that had already riveted Austrian Catholics. At a mass
Saturday in the small town of St. Poelton, its conservative bishop,
Kurt Krenn, departed from his prepared text and offered a prayer
for Cardinal Hans Hermann Groer, who was forced to resign in 1995
amid allegations that he sexually molested young men in a monastery
20 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The scandal, which re-erupted in January after a priest made
fresh charges, was so politically stormy among Catholics that
Groer's successor, Schoenborn, announced in April that the charges
were true and apologized for Groer's actions.
</P>
<P>
   Krenn, however, remained loyal to Groer, and dismissed the
priest who made his own accusation of sexual abuse by Groer public.
Demonstrators outside the mass Saturday carried black balloons to
signal their unhappiness with Krenn.
</P>
<P>
   Even Austrians who are not actively practicing Catholics have
followed the Groer affair and Krenn's prayer for him in St. Poelton
was mentioned on most newscasts here.
</P>
<P>
   Schoenborn, who is as conservative as the pope on doctrinal
issues, has sought to make peace within Austria's church by
engaging in dialogue with Catholic dissidents. He invited leaders
of one of the more prominent lay groups, We Are the Church, to sit
in the VIP section at Sunday's outdoor mass on Vienna's Heroes'
Square. They thanked him for the invitation but declined to attend
in protest against what they view as the pope's resistance to
reforms.
</P>
<P>
   One liberal Catholic who did attend was the Rev. Eduard Fischer,
the priest who was dismissed from his parish duties by Krenn for
publicly airing his charges against Groer. He has since came as a
reporter for the dissident Catholic newsletter Ja, or yes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The pope is visiting a burning house,'' Fischer complained.
``But instead of speaking about the fire, he talks about the lovely
flowers in front of it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-21-98 1941EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980621.0123 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-21 19:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9433 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BENNETT-BROTHERS-ART-     06-21 0884
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BENNETT-BROTHERS-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 WASHINGTON: right thing.'' 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bob was the top debater at Brooklyn Prep, and Bill was known as
something of an intellectual even then, tackling ``The Iliad'' and
``The Odyssey'' as a sixth-grader. Even then, too, friends remember
Bill as a child who was deeply interested in moral issues and such
theological debates as how unfair it would be if pets were not
allowed into heaven, official Catholic teaching notwithstanding.
</P>
<P>
   Then and now, Bob Bennett seemed less interested in these
matters. And politically, he has never been comfortable declaring
himself, though he has represented Democrats and Republicans,
including former Defense Secretary Caspar Weinberger.
</P>
<P>
   He does suggest that he does not necessarily share the politics
of his best-known client. ``If Clinton were George Bush, I'd be
doing the same thing I am now,'' he said, smiling. ``Obviously, the
issues would be different.''
</P>
<P>
   These days Bob Bennett is working on fending off Ms. Jones'
appeal of her case and fighting efforts by the independent counsel
to get top Clinton aides to testify about the president's
relationship with Monica Lewinsky, a former White House intern.
</P>
<P>
   Bennett mentioned that he once represented a bookie, and saw a
certain morality even in him. ``That bookie would not give up the
book. He'd have gone to the gas chamber instead. We all choose how
we're going to be moral.''
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, Bob Bennett says, the chief difference between the
brothers is more philosophical than ideological. ``I see the world
as a very complicated place,'' he said, and rubbed his eyes. ``I
wish the world was more like what my brother wants it to be.''
</P>
<P>
   Beyond that, ``We're breaks for each other,'' Bob Bennett said,
getting a little maudlin. ``As long as the other is alive, we don't
have to worry that our family would ever want for anything if
anything ever happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite enormous material success, he clearly sees their blood
bond as a hedge against hard times. ``We're there for each other on
the important things.''
</P>
<P>
   In his own downtown office, Bill Bennett is initially more
cautious than his brother, and still shows signs of the shy child
he was, mostly avoiding eye contact.
</P>
<P>
   Lately, he said, he has had more reason to worry about his big
brother than vice versa. ``The Clintons bother me and what happens
to people around them worries me,'' Bill Bennett said. ``It's risky
business.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bennetts' politics seem to have shifted since Bob talked
Bill out of joining the anti-war Students for a Democratic Society
in college. But the cultural differences between the two are
reflected in their families. Ellen, Bob's wife, who was dressed
casually for an interview in her kitchen, said their daughters were
``pretty liberal'' and still trying to convert Uncle Bill.
</P>
<P>
   Elayne, Bill's wife, who has a warm, Southern sensibility and a
more formal bearing, served pear tart and tea and said: ''Our boys
wear a tie to school every day, Catholic school. We're afraid of
popular culture. We restrict television and monitor rock music. I
never saw `Seinfeld,' and I don't want my kids to watch `The
Simpsons.'''
</P>
<P>
   Bill Bennett sees himself as a ``public advocate, a public
philosopher on some of the things out there that I believe matter
in the long run,'' he said, adding, ``I do not see myself as Mr.
Virtue.''
</P>
<P>
   He refers to his role in relation to his brother's: ``As a
parallel to Bob, who likes to defend people in trouble, I like to
defend principles that are in trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   He has spent many months saying Clinton should resign if he had
an affair with Ms. Lewinsky. But only a few weeks ago, he said, he
decided to write a book about how the whole mess had lowered
America's moral standards, after reading a newspaper article about
a group of Republicans in Naperville, Ill.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were apparently sitting around saying, `What does this
matter to me?' I said, `This is ridiculous!' These are Republicans,
who should know better, taking on this pseudo-intellectual,
European, learned nonsense and it made me mad. There should be
outrage!''
</P>
<P>
   He says he is writing the book to counter the cynicism and moral
slippage that are sure to take root if the defense of Clinton's
reported bad behavior goes unanswered. Both brothers said their
relationship would survive this, too. But there are strains over
the Clintons and other matters. Bill once took offense, for
example, when Bob called him ``Mr. Virtue'' on television.
</P>
<P>
   And close as they are, there have always been topics considered
off-limits. One night years ago, when Bill Bennett was 32 and still
unmarried, the telephone rang, and it was his brother. He remembers
the conversation like this: ``He said, `Is there anything you want
to ask me about sex?' He was worried that he had not done his duty
as an older brother. It was very sweet, very guilty, very Bob. I
told him, `Thanks, I'm fine.'''
</P>
<P>
   Now, Bill Bennett asks an interviewer about his brother, looking
for an answer to what some people consider the ultimate personal
question: ``Does Bob believe in God?'' Well, he is not practicing,
Bill is told, but beyond that, he did not say. Suddenly, Bill
Bennett is beaming.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe,'' he said, `I'll call and ask him if he has any
questions about God.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
