<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-21 20:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9455 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VH1-MEDIA-2TAKES-NYT &LR;      06-21 0698
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VH1-MEDIA-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A MUSIC CHANNEL FOR BABY BOOMERS WITH MORTGAGES
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV.: A photo for use with this story is being sent to NYT
photo clients. Non-subscribers may make individual purchase by
calling 212 556-4204.) 
 (ja) 
 By BILL CARTER    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When John Sykes took over as president of the cable channel VH1
in 1994, he had a theory:
</P>
<P>
   ``All the baby boomers, and all those people who started out
watching MTV in 1980, did not stop listening to music. They grew up
and bought new stereos and put CD players in their cars, and they
were spending $100 on a weekend to see the Eagles reunion concert.
But nobody on television was serving that audience.''
</P>
<P>
   That included VH1, which was originally devised to fill that
mission but instead had scraped by for more than a decade as what
Sykes called ``the bastard stepchild of MTV.''
</P>
<P>
   VH1, which is owned by MTV Networks, a unit of Viacom Inc., had
established almost no identity with television viewers; its
programming was a bizarre mix of oldie videos (``a lot of Julio
Iglesias,'' Sykes said), dusty sitcom reruns (``WKRP in
Cincinnati'') and fruit-smashing stand-up comedy acts (endless
episodes of ``Gallagher'').
</P>
<P>
   The channel started in 1985 with the purpose of staving off
competition for MTV. That year, Ted Turner had started a competing
music channel, so MTV Networks offered VH1 free to cable operators,
killing off the threat. But the channel's identity as a separate
music network was never firmly established.
</P>
<P>
   In the four years since Sykes took over, VH1 has found a formula
that has significantly increased its ratings and driven up profits.
Indeed, VH1 has the highest concentration of advertisers' most
desirable viewers, those 18 to 49. As a result, advertisers from
American Express to Lexus have added VH1 to their buying plans.
</P>
<P>
   As a sign of VH1's success, an array of musicians, from Mariah
Carey to the Rolling Stones, have appeared on the channel in live
concerts. And it even did a show called ``Bill Clinton, Rock and
Roll President,'' and now claims the nation's First Television
Viewer as a regular supporter and fan.
</P>
<P>
   The formula that turned VH1 around was basic: pure music and
music-related programs for adults. As Sykes put it, ``What I
figured we could do was own music'' for adults, ``because that was
something we could do better than anybody else.''
</P>
<P>
   The pure-music format still means videos but with a different
edge: newer artists like Jewel, Paula Cole and Sarah McLachlan who
are favored more by adults than by teen-agers and innovative
formats like ``Pop-Up Video,'' which brought computer-style
information bites to the video genre.
</P>
<P>
   It also means documentary-style programs on the background of
music artists and their work, highlighted by the channel's most
popular series, ``Behind the Music,'' which examines the personal
stories of recording stars and their albums; ``Storyteller,'' which
describes how hit songs came to be written, and ``Legends,''
profiles of recording stars.
</P>
<P>
   The channel also loaded up on concerts and other events, like
its annual fashion awards. It attracted its biggest audience ever
in April with its ``Divas Live'' concert featuring six star female
performers: Mariah Carey, Celine Dion, Gloria Estefan, Aretha
Franklin, Carole King and Shania Twain.
</P>
<P>
   An even better measure of the channel's surging growth is
offered by Tom Freston, the chairman of MTV Networks, who sees VH1
as the hottest channel in his company's portfolio. ``It is growing
faster on a percentage basis than either Nickelodeon or MTV,''
Freston said. ``It's almost the sky's the limit now for VH1.''
</P>
<P>
   Such an assessment is a stark reversal from the channel's
prospects only about 18 months ago, when things were so rocky for
VH1 that it was being kicked off numerous cable systems to make
room for other channels. ``They were at a low ebb,'' said Bill
Marchetti, an analyst with Paul Kagan Associates, a firm that
analyzes the cable industry. ``If they didn't make a lot of right
moves right then, they were going to start having a tough time
getting renewals from some cable systems.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the United States' largest cable operator,
Tele-Communications Inc., had already dumped VH1 from more than one
million homes to accommodate several channels in which it owned a
financial interest, including Fox News, Animal Planet and Home and
Garden. Fortunately, Sykes said, VH1, with its new adult-music
format, had managed to build up some loyal fans by then, both in
the television audience and in the music industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``We held a protest in Denver,'' Sykes said, ``with people like
John Mellencamp, Jewel and Don Henley. These artists said, `We need
a place to get our music heard.'''
</P>
<P>
   The outcry from viewers and artists eventually got VH1 back on
all the systems that dropped it, and many more besides. In the last
three years, the channel has spent $20 million in programming
improvements and extended its subscriber base to more than 62
million homes from 49 million. ``That was the turning point,''
Sykes said. Freston said if those first moves to drop VH1 from
cable systems had not been overturned, ``The whole asset value of
the channel could have vaporized.''
</P>
<P>
   Now that asset value is highly prized by MTV Networks because
VH1 has an almost ideal business plan. ``It's a niche business,''
Sykes said. Ratings are still modest. The prime-time average has
more than doubled in the last two years, but that means a rise to
only a 0.4 rating from 0.18. (For VH1, each rating point represents
620,000 homes. MTV averages about a 0.7 rating, but in a larger
number of homes.)
</P>
<P>
   ``But in the cable world,'' Sykes said, ``with our low overhead,
moderate program costs and economies of scale, you can be in a
business like music for television viewers. You can superserve that
audience and make money.''
</P>
<P>
   And VH1 is making money. In fact, Sykes confidently notes, ``We
alone are making more in profits than any broadcast network except
NBC.''
</P>
<P>
   The reason this somewhat startling development can be true is
that neither CBS, ABC nor Fox earned much money _ if any _ this
year. So the $42.5 million in profit for VH1 for 1998, as estimated
by Paul Kagan Associates, looks good by comparison. The results for
MTV shows the potential for a cable channel, with the channel
making about $250 million during the same period.
</P>
<P>
   But VH1 is looking good by comparison in several areas,
including its overall appeal to viewers between 18 and 49, the
favorite group of most advertisers. According to Nielsen Media
research, VH1 has the highest concentration of those viewers _
about 88 percent of its viewers fall in that range _ in all of
cable.
</P>
<P>
   Sykes sees VH1's growing success as confirmation of his theory
about how the generation of music fans who grew up in the 1960s and
'70s refused to relinquish their proprietary interest in music.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our parents more or less gave up their dominance of the
record-buying business when they got into having children and
mortgages,'' Sykes said. ``But for the baby-boom generation, there
has always been a passionate connection to music.''
</P>
<P>
   Sykes, who began his career as an MTV executive in the 1980s,
left in 1986 to take various positions in the music industry. From
that perspective he noticed a change going on. ``There had always
been a perception in the music industry that adults didn't
matter,'' he said. ``But I noticed that adults were buying more
records than their kids. And they had Visa cards to use, not their
allowances.''
</P>
<P>
   But the adult audience was not going to watch MTV. In Freston's
words, ``They couldn't stand the music on MTV,'' with its mix of
rap, alternative and hard rock. Once VH1 responded to adults'
continuing passion for music, Sykes said, it was on its way. ``The
adult audience today almost feels elitist toward music,'' he said.
``It feels like it has always had the best music, the music
influenced by the war in Vietnam, the music that established
trends. And now, probably for the first time in history, we're
seeing music cross over from adults to kids.''
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton fits the description of a baby boomer with a
continuing passion for music, Sykes said. He has several personal
letters from the president attesting to his interest in the
channel's programming. (The president was especially taken by a
series of specials VH1 did on the 20th anniversary of the death of
Elvis Presley, Sykes said.)
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also enthusiastically supported the channel's campaign
called ``Save the Music,'' which raises money for school music
programs, partly through donations of old instruments. Clinton
donated an old saxophone, which went to an inner-city Washington
high school.
</P>
<P>
   Having moved in the last three years to what he called
``second-tier status'' among cable channels, Sykes said, the next
step is ``to jump up to the first tier.'' He defined the second
tier as channels like Comedy Central and Lifetime, which have more
than 50 million homes and climbing ratings. The top tier, he said,
are the dominant channels of cable, like ESPN, CNN and MTV, with 65
million to 73 million homes and regular programs with strong
support.
</P>
<P>
   ``The upside for us is getting to where MTV and Nickelodeon are
in the next few years,'' Sykes said. ``We're at a different point
in our lifeline. We've been around since 1985, but for most of
those years we were doing nothing. We're sort of where MTV was in
the early 1980s. The real upside is creating the kind of brand
awareness that MTV and Nick have now.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
