u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IRAN-POLITICS-315&AMP;ADD     06-21 1257
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRAN-POLITICS-315&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IRAN'S PARLIAMENT AND PRESIDENT CLASH OVER ONE OF HIS ALLIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By ELAINE SCIOLINO   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEHRAN, Iran _ In a high-stakes political battle filled with
recriminations and rage, Iran's Parliament voted Sunday to dismiss
one of the closest allies of Mohammad Khatami, the reform-minded
president.
</P>
<P>
   Khatami swiftly retaliated. He made Abdullah Noori, the ousted
minister of the interior, a vice president.
</P>
<P>
   Parliament is controlled by Khatami's enemies. Its action Sunday
is the most serious political setback to his presidency since his
landslide victory 13 months ago as well as graphic proof of
Khatami's limited room for maneuver in Iran's Islamic Republic.
</P>
<P>
   The vote comes just just three days after Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright warmly praised Khatami and the reforms made
since he took office and held out the prospect of eventual
normalization of relations with Iran.
</P>
<P>
   The vote, 137-117 with 11 abstentions, came in a secret ballot
after several hours of impassioned debate in which Noori was
accused of arrogantly dismissing officials who did not share his
politics, fostering an unstable economic environment and putting
the country's security at risk.
</P>
<P>
   The vote was as much an attack against Khatami as it was against
Noori, and it is part of a wider campaign led by conservative
members of the clergy to discredit officials loyal to the
president.
</P>
<P>
   The parliamentary session was broadcast live on radio and later
on television as millions of Iranian viewers were awaiting the live
broadcast of the World Cup soccer match between the United States
and Iran at 11 p.m. Both opponents and supporters of Noori stepped
up to the lectern in the center of the parliamentary hall to air
their views.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the current trend continues, the result will be something
like Lebanon of a few years ago, or Yugoslavia,'' said Mohammad
Reza Bahonar, a deputy speaker of Parliament. ``Mr. Noori's
attitude is dangerous to the political future of the country.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In another angry speech, Marzieh Vahid-Dastjerdi, an
obstetrician and representative from Tehran who was dressed in the
traditional black chador, accused Noori of replacing 1,700
officials, primarily because they ``were not thinking like you.''
She also attacked Noori's definition of freedom, saying, ``For us,
freedom doesn't mean that counterrevolutionary groups can do
whatever they want and create anarchy.''
</P>
<P>
   In support of Noori, Majid Ansari, a member of Parliament from
Tehran, accused the minister's enemies of exaggerating Iran's
troubles as if ``Iran is on the verge of war.''
</P>
<P>
   Noori sat stone-faced during the speeches before offering a
defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do not claim I never made a mistake,'' he said. But he
accused his enemies of a plot to alienate Iran's young people from
the Islamic revolution and the clergy.
</P>
<P>
   Noori was reflecting the position voiced repeatedly by Khatami
and his supporters that what is at stake is nothing less than the
soul of the nation. According to this line of thinking, unless Iran
becomes freer at home and more open to the outside world, it will
lose the allegiance of the generation that has been born in the 19
years since the monarchy was overthrown.
</P>
<P>
   Khatami has therefore committed himself to the creation of a
``civil society'' and the ``rule of law'' at home and has reached
out to improve relations with both the Arab world and the West.
</P>
<P>
   But Khatami is fiercely opposed by those clerics _ and their
followers _ who believe that the core beliefs of the revolution are
being sacrificed.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Parliament does not give me the vote of confidence, I will
thank God that he has lifted this heavy responsibility from my
shoulders, and I will see this as God's mercy,'' Noori said in his
speech. ``And if I get the vote of confidence, I will be energized
once again.''
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``Whether Abdullah Noori remains or not, until the
last second of my life I will remain the servant of the system, the
revolution and the leadership.''
</P>
<P>
   Members of Parliament cast white ballots to dismiss Noori,
purple ballots to keep him and yellow ballots to abstain. Then Ali
Akbar Nateq-Noori, the Speaker of Parliament, announced in sober
tones, `` Abdullah Noori failed to win a vote of confidence.''
Several of the members shouted, ``God is great!''
</P>
<P>
   Nateq-Noori had been the front-runner for president and lost in
an upset to Khatami.
</P>
<P>
   Although Khatami acknowledged that Parliament had the right
under the Constitution to dismiss Noori, he reiterated his
determination to give the people the freedoms they hold under the
law. ``I and my administration are very serious about this
principle,'' he said. ``Of course, it has costs which must be paid,
just like building a bridge or a factory.''
</P>
<P>
   In introducing the dismissal motion last month, 31 members of
Parliament accused Noori of ``creating tension in society, giving
provocative interviews and speeches in different provinces and
appointing inexperienced people to managerial posts in the
ministry.''
</P>
<P>
   Noori, 49, a mid-ranking cleric from Isfahan, has been an
outspoken proponent of Khatami's commitment to impose a rule of law
and has come under fire for issuing permits to allow groups to
conduct peaceful demonstrations.
</P>
<P>
   Under the constitution, the country's spiritual leader,
Ayatollah Ali Khamenei, and not the president, controls the
judiciary, as well as the military, radio and television and the
intelligence and security services.
</P>
<P>
   But Khatami has encouraged Noori to challenge decisions by the
judiciary _ particularly the arrest of Tehran Mayor Gholamhossein
Karabaschi, who is on trial on corruption and embezzlement charges.
The trial is broadcast on television in the evenings.
</P>
<P>
   Noori has also strongly supported Karabaschi and has openly
criticized the chief of the judiciary, Ayatollah Mohammed Yazdi,
for arresting the mayor in April without telling Noori.
</P>
<P>
   He said at the time, ``When the mayor of Tehran, who is a member
of the Cabinet, is arrested without informing the interior minister
or even the president and some public media resort to
rumor-mongering; when the mayor, with all his experience, is
prevented from having any visitors and an arrest warrant that is
totally inconsistent with the charges is issued for him; when
propaganda campaigns against the mayor and his colleagues are
launched for several consecutive months from every side and he
remains silent, like a wronged person, in the interest of the
state, what hope can an ordinary citizen have that the law will
defend his rights?''
</P>
<P>
   After several thousand people demonstrated in favor of the
mayor, he was released on bail.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, Khatami defended Noori, calling him ``one of the
strongest ministers in the Cabinet.'' The President predicted that
Noori's ``absence from the Cabinet will entail massive damage for
the government and the country.''
</P>
<P>
   In a direct affront to Parliament, Khatami on Sunday cited
Noori's ``capabilities'' and created a job for him: vice president
for development and social affairs. The job keeps Noori in the
Cabinet and does not require Parliament's approval.
</P>
<P>
   In another sign that he had no intention of surrendering to
Parliament, Khatami appointed Mostafa Tajzadeh, a deputy minister
of the interior, as the acting minister. Tajzadeh, a staunch
supporter of the president, was also criticized Sunday by some
members of Parliament.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
