<SLUG> BC-LEWIS-CARROLL-EXHIBIT-605&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE MAN WHO TURNED SENSE INTO CHARMED NONSENSE
</HEADLINE>
   (ja) 
 By EDWARD ROTHSTEIN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Then comes this declaration: ``Nobody is despised who
can manage a crocodile.''
</P>
<P>
   And, as if in an afterthought: ``Illogical persons are
despised.''
</P>
<P>
   All of which is perfectly plausible. So what, Lewis Carroll asks
in one of his books about symbolic logic, is the proper conclusion?
</P>
<P>
   Such are the slight amusements that I recall thinking about on
those leisurely childhood ``golden afternoons'' like the one
Carroll invoked at the beginning of ``Alice's Adventures in
Wonderland.'' But in place of Alice's rabbit hole or looking glass,
her flamingo croquet mallet and the promise of Mock Turtle Soup, I
had recourse to Carroll himself, spinning out fractured syllogisms
or oddly twisted homilies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Be what you would seem to be,'' the Duchess sagely advised
Alice. ``Or, if you'd like to put it more simply, never imagine
yourself not to be otherwise than what it might appear to others
that what you were or might have been was not otherwise than what
you had been would have appeared to them to be otherwise.''
</P>
<P>
   Exactly.
</P>
<P>
   Which is what came to mind when visiting the exhibition ``a k a
Lewis Carroll,'' at the Morgan Library through Aug. 30: the way in
which Carroll transformed advice and sentimentality into perfectly
sensible nonsense, leaving in its wake a kind of unsettling
dizziness, or even, to put it less mildly, a form of nausea.
</P>
<P>
   Somehow, amid the Morgan's memorabilia and exotica _ the
souvenirs of Disney's ``Alice'' movie, the ``Alice'' illustrations
that Guinness once used to advertise its brew, a translation of
``Alice'' into Pitjantjatjara (the aboriginal language of South
Australia) in which the rabbit became a kangaroo and the screaming
baby a bandicoot _ there was Carroll himself. Or at least enough of
him to awaken a childhood recollection of his strangely packed
mixtures of rationality and subversion.
</P>
<P>
   Looking at his postcard written in mirror script or seeing the
photo he took of his Lolita-muse, Alice Liddell, seductively got up
as a beggar-waif, it is clear just how little he was what he seemed
to be. He could have been a version of Alice, unable to respond
confidently when challenged by the hookah-smoking Caterpillar with
``Who are you?''
</P>
<P>
   By now the paradoxes of his life have entered literary
mythology. The mathematician Charles Lutwidge Dodgson, an Oxford
don, was reported to have been quite a dull lecturer. But when he
adopted a pseudonym, he created exuberant fantasies for children
that leave the chalk board and lecture hall far behind.
</P>
<P>
   He was eminently respectable, a lifelong bachelor and a close
family friend of the college's dean; but he was also almost
obsessively infatuated with the dean's prepubescent daughters,
particularly Alice Liddell, who, at the age of 10, was the
inspiration for his Alice books. And while in his diaries there are
traces of the stern moralist grimly recording his struggles with
unspecified temptations, in his books he turned all moral lessons
on their heads.
</P>
<P>
   That overturning of sense and sensibility was almost an
obsession of the Alice books. Carroll would take a trite poem with
its period parental advice (``Speak Gently! It is better far/To
rule by love than fear'') and transmute it into a grotesquerie:
``Speak roughly to your little boy/ And beat him when he sneezes!''
He would take a familiar kitschy warning against laziness (``'Tis
the voice of the sluggard'; I heard him complain,/`You have wak'd
me too soon, I must slumber again.''') and turn it into nonsense:
``'Tis the voice of the Lobster: I heard him declare/`You have
baked me too brown, I must sugar my hair.'''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   These burlesques of familiar Victorian commonplaces must have
once caused as much uneasiness as they do in Alice when she hears
them recited by the denizens of Wonderland. Some hint of the effect
can now be gotten from David Del Tredici's ``Alice'' compositions,
many of which set these verses in ways both fantastical and
nightmarish. His latest setting, given its premiere by the New York
Philharmonic last month, was of ``The Spider and the Fly,'' a
Victorian morality tale for young virgins. (```Will you walk into
my parlor?' said the spider to the fly.'') A fly resists the
spider's seductive offerings of fine, thinly spun sheets on which
to rest, but finally succumbs to blunt flattery.
</P>
<P>
   Del Tredici treats this as a miniopera, exaggerating the scale,
so it becomes a scene like one witnessed by Alice in one of her
many changes in size. As a result, the poem's solemn piety is
dissolved into a kind of wistful amusement at something from
another universe. Carroll dissolved it even more completely:
</P>
<P>
   ``Will you walk a little faster?'' said a whiting to a snail.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a porpoise close behind us, and he's treading on my
tail.''
</P>
<P>
   This is sleight of hand of a very high order, mocking moral
convention while apparently just creating nonsense. Something is at
stake in this satire, something that may be connected to the
unhappiness his biographer, Morton Cohen, finds in Carroll's life.
It may have arisen, in part, from Carroll's inability or
unwillingness to reconcile the disruptive looking-glass world with
the tautly controlled order of his own.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen points out one occasion when some kind of disturbing
fantasy may have even broken through the veneer. Something took
place during late June 1863, after Alice had already inspired
Wonderland, that led to a nearly complete break between Carroll and
the Liddells.
</P>
<P>
   Was it some sort of inappropriate behavior involving Alice?
(Cohen suggests a premature marriage proposal.) Or was it something
far less respectable, (which Cohen does not think too plausible)?
We will never know: The journal page on which Carroll had recorded
his transgression was neatly excised by a niece who found the
revelation too shocking.
</P>
<P>
   But whatever the excision, the dark judgment is in the ``Alice''
books: the little girl who is mistaken for a serpent; the Queen who
keeps shouting, ``Off with his head,'' the overturned jury box of
rodents and lizards. Carroll created a children's literature that
discarded any pretense of simple moral lesson or rosy pleasantries,
reaching back to the eeriness of the Mother Goose rhymes or the
Grimm fairy tales.
</P>
<P>
   Carroll's heirs range from P.L. Travers, who created a
ruthlessly unsentimental Mary Poppins, to Maurice Sendak, whose
painterly images of dream worlds can be more unsettling to adults
than to children.
</P>
<P>
   But Carroll also tamed the irrationality by giving his nonsense
logical form. The effect in our own era of fierce conventions can
be bracing. Forget the issues of being and seeming, of propriety
and guilt, of threats and recriminations. Carroll offers
alternative advice:
</P>
<P>
   ```The time has come,' the Walrus said,
</P>
<P>
   `To talk of many things:
</P>
<P>
   Of shoes and ships and sealing wax
</P>
<P>
   Of cabbages and kings
</P>
<P>
   And why the sea is boiling hot
</P>
<P>
   And whether pigs have wings.'''
</P>
<P>
   Incidentally, the correct conclusion is that babies cannot
manage crocodiles.
</P>
</TEXT>
