<HEADER>
A9494 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-INTERLEAGUE-LADN     06-21 1015
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-INTERLEAGUE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INTERLEAGUE PLAY A HIT WITH FANS, NOT PLAYERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ERIC NOLAND  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Designated hitters, wild cards, night games at
Wrigley, ownership by conglomerate.
</P>
<P>
   Baseball convention has been turned on its ear, but the game
continues to thrive _ in spite of, or precisely because of, these
innovations.
</P>
<P>
   Over the next four nights in Southern California, a clamorous
statement will be made for the continuance of still another
wrinkle: interleague play.
</P>
<P>
   It used to be that the area's fans could harbor only the
faintest hope of a Freeway World Series between the Dodgers and
Angels. During the first 36 years of these teams' co-tenancy of the
region, it never had the slightest glimmer of fruition.
</P>
<P>
   But interleague play, launched as a two-year experiment last
season, delivered the next best thing: games between the Dodgers
and Angels that actually meant something. And the fans responded
about as expected.
</P>
<P>
   Over the next four nights, the teams will participate in a
home-and-home exchange _ two games in Anaheim, beginning tonight,
followed by two in Dodger Stadium _ and officials from both clubs
say they are expecting robust crowds throughout.
</P>
<P>
   For the game's players, who will vote later this summer on
whether to continue interleague play, it presents an unmistakable
message: This thing is good for business.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a player, I don't like it,'' said veteran relief pitcher
Mark Guthrie of the Dodgers. ``But if it sells seats, I guess
you've got to like it.''
</P>
<P>
   It does, indeed, sell tickets. Throughout the major leagues,
last year's interleague games represented a 20 percent attendance
boost over the averages for intraleague play. This season's first,
brief burst of interleague action, two weeks ago, reflected hikes
of 15 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Locally, the numbers last year were dramatic. The Angels
averaged 20,953 for American League games and 29,152 for six
interleague contests (a 39 percent increase), and for two home
games with the Dodgers they logged their largest and fourth-largest
gatherings of the year.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers drew an average of 40,320 for National League games
and 47,019 for eight interleague dates (a 17 percent boost). They
actually drew better for Seattle, Texas and Oakland than they did
for the Angels, but their average for two games with the Angels
(43,691) certainly wasn't shabby.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like it,'' Dodgers executive vice president Fred Claire said
of interleague play. ``It obviously has added a very interesting
and exciting dimension to our game....
</P>
<P>
   ``It did create the two-game series, which was absolutely brutal
for everybody. The concept is there, but there is work to be
done.''
</P>
<P>
   The work will involve convincing players that this innovation
can be retained without turning travel schedules inside-out.
``We've got to cut it down to where we're not playing two-game
series every time we go out on the road,'' said Angels first
baseman Cecil Fielder. ``That is very difficult.''
</P>
<P>
   The number of miniseries has been reduced _ the Angels have 17
this year, as opposed to 26 last year; the Dodgers have 12 this
year, compared with 25 in '97 _ but the issue remains a serious
stumbling block for the players' approval, said union chief Donald
Fehr.
</P>
<P>
   Some players, as a result, take a nihilist view of the future of
interleague play. ``I've talked to a lot of players, and nobody
likes it,'' said St. Louis' Mark McGwire. ``I don't see it being
passed.''
</P>
<P>
   Major League Baseball, however, feels it will soon allay the
concerns over fractured travel itineraries. ``We'll have a schedule
to the union by the first of July,'' said spokesman Richard Levin.
``I think that schedule will reflect fewer two-game series by a
considerable amount. I think it will satisfy those concerns.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, baseball mulls over additional modifications to
interleague play, some of which could be reflected in the new
schedule.
</P>
<P>
   One option, which could drastically reduce the number of
two-game series, would involve teams facing a limited number of
teams from an opposing division. In the west, for example, the
Dodgers might play only Seattle and the Angels one time around, and
catch Oakland and Texas in the next season.
</P>
<P>
   Another would involve a rotating, three-year tour of the
interleague divisions: West one year, East the next, Central the
next.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think you've got to mix up the divisions,'' said Colorado's
Dante Bichette, whose team has no natural regional rival. ``If we
see Anaheim and Seattle every year, that's going to get old. I'm
sure the fans (in Denver) would like to see the New York Yankees.
Then it kind of remains fresh. If it gets old, the fans will stop
coming.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite its popularity, interleague play is certain to generate
its share of controversy. If the Chicago Cubs and San Francisco
Giants are pursuing the same wild card, for example, an argument
likely will arise that the Cubs are facing much weaker opponents in
the AL Central than are the Giants in the AL West.
</P>
<P>
   But if baseball elects to continue on this course, it will
simply have to weather the interleague quirks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the owners and the union are feeling it's a good thing
_ not a good thing for us, but a good thing for the fans,'' said
Fielder.
</P>
<P>
   Added Angels player representative Tim Salmon: ``I look at it
from a standpoint that you always wonder what it's like to play
some of these National League teams.... I like it. It kind of makes
things exciting.''
</P>
<P>
   Especially when the exhilaration has civic undertones, as will
be the case this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``It gets back, to me, to the feel of what Pacific Coast League
games used to be like _ the Angels and the Hollywood Stars,'' said
the Dodgers' Claire, referring to the Triple-A days in Los Angeles
before the Dodgers moved here from Brooklyn 40 years ago. ``It's
great. I know the players feel it. It's an added dimension of
excitement.''
</P>
<P>
   And, by all indications, another breath of fresh air for
baseball.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-21-98 2044EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
