<SLUG> BC-GLF-OPENNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AZINGER SHOOTS OPEN-LOW 65
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ It was too little too late for Paul Azinger, who
carded the lowest score of this year's U.S. Open in relative
obscurity Sunday. His 5-under-par 65 was one shot better than Payne
Stewart's first-round effort, but all it got Azinger was a return
invitation to next year's event at Pinehurst, N.C.
</P>
<P>
   Azinger's round featured eight birdies and only 25 putts, the
last of which was a curling 30-footer on the 18th hole that he
couldn't believe dropped. When his ball disappeared in the cup,
Azinger dropped his putter and raised his hands to the heavens. ``A
miracle,'' is what he called it.
</P>
<P>
   Before teeing off in the third group of the day, Azinger called
his score, correctly as it turned out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was talking about a 65,'' Azinger said. ``It was kind of a
fluke that I got it.''
</P>
<P>
   Azinger's score was seven shots better than the best he could
muster the first three days, begging the question: Was the course
playing easier Sunday or was his collar just looser? Nerves,
Azinger said, what nerves?
</P>
<P>
   ``You've been listening to (golfer and outspoken TV announcer)
Johnny Miller,'' Azinger said with a smirk.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was swinging better today,'' he said. ``I had better timing,
better rhythm.''
</P>
<P>
   Azinger's subpar round was one of six recorded Sunday. Of those,
only winner Lee Janzen's 68 came from any of the final 13 twosomes.
</P>
<P>
   Coulda shoulda: Tiger Woods, the 1997 Masters champion,
effectively plugged his title hopes at the par-4 second, par-3
third and par-4 fourth holes at the Olympic Club's Lake Course.
</P>
<P>
   Woods, 22, covered those 1,055 yards of high-end real estate in
a combined 8-over-par, which looms large considering he finished at
plus-10 after a closing round of 73 that included a three-putt
bogey at No.18.
</P>
<P>
   ``I made good swings,'' Woods said. ``But the balls would land
in the fairway and end up in the deep rough.''
</P>
<P>
   That wasn't really Woods' problem on the second and fourth holes
as he hit five of eight fairways. But when he got to the greens, it
was another story. He two-putted the two holes seven times out of
eight.
</P>
<P>
   Woods might talk around it _ whistling through the graveyard, as
it were _ but his putting clearly is killing him; for the week he
required 33, 32, 30 and 31 putts, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hit a lot of lips that didn't go in,'' Woods said. ``I just
missed some putts. The greens were spongy and bouncy. That was a
problem for everyone.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin unimpressed: By way of comparison, Woods' onetime
Stanford teammate Casey Martin played holes No. 2, 3 and 4 in
3-over par en route to impressing everyone, it seems, except
himself. He closed with a 72 to finish in a tie for 23rd at plus-11
in his first U.S. Open.
</P>
<P>
   Martin, who was born with a rare circulatory disorder in his
right leg that makes walking painful, became the first golfer to
use a cart in a U.S. Open. But he'd rather you remember him as a
player, not a pioneer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a lot more game than I showed,'' said Martin, who
narrowly missed qualifying for the PGA Tour in December and is a
regular on the minitour sponsored by Nike. ``I realize I can play
with these guys.''
</P>
<P>
   Happy birthday: Amateur Matt Kuchar gave himself a great 20th-
birthday present, draining a long par putt on the 72nd hole that
was as good as an RSVP to next year's Open. The putt capped a 74
that gave Kuchar a four-day total of 9-over-par and a share of 14th
place with Azinger, Jesper Parnevik and Jim Furyk. The top 15 and
ties automatically receive return invitations.
</P>
<P>
   Kuchar's finish was the best by an amateur since Jim Simons' tie
for fifth in 1971.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
