<HEADLINE>
CULTURE NOTES: FAREWELL TO A CHORUS LEADER; MUNICH OPERA FESTIVAL;
DANCING UNDER THE STARS; AFRICAN MUSICIANS ON TOUR 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Minn., Ill., Mass.)  (lb) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It's hail and farewell at 8 on Monday night at
Carnegie Hall, where the New York City Gay Men's Chorus will usher
in Gay Pride Week with a concert that bids goodbye to Gary Miller,
its founding director, who is retiring after this season.
</P>
<P>
   He will be succeeded by Barry Oliver, former director of the
Denver Gay Men's Chorus and for the last two seasons the pianist
for the 206-member New York group. Monday night's concert, ``Look
to the Rainbow,'' will revisit Miller's 18 years with the chorus
through a retrospective of his favorite selections from previous
concerts. Information: (212) 247-7800.
</P>
<P>
   Bavarian Nights
</P>
<P>
   MUNICH, Germany _ Names don't always tell the story. The Munich
Opera Festival, which begins on Friday and runs through July 31,
also includes ballet, theater and concerts. There will be 15
operas, seven ballets, eight evening song recitals and an
avant-garde program called Festival Plus.
</P>
<P>
   A production of Wagner's ``Tristan und Isolde,'' led by Zubin
Mehta, the new musical director of the Bavarian State Opera, opens
on June 30. Song recitals feature Cecilia Bartoli, Montserrat
Caballe and Margaret Price; the Bavarian State Ballet program
includes two premieres. Festival Plus includes the Munich premiere
of Eugene O'Neill's ``Hairy Ape.'' Information:
011-49-89-2185-1024.
</P>
<P>
   Meaningful Thing
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The nights are long, the stars are out, and Midsummer
Night Swing returns, offering a chance to dance on the Fountain
Plaza at Lincoln Center from Wednesday to July 25. The event opens
with a tribute to Kansas City's blues and jazz by Dennis Mackrel
and his Manhattan Symphony Jazz Orchestra, with guests Kevin
Mahogany, vocalist, and reedman Frank Weiss. Coming attractions
include jump blues and swing, salsa, rumba, waltz, fox trot and
more. Information: (212) 875-5766.
</P>
<P>
   Continental Linking
</P>
<P>
   In 1978, Mamadou Konte, a Senegalese immigrant living in Paris
wanted to familiarize the French with African culture through music
and dance. His performances caught the eye of Chris Blackwell, the
founder of Island Records, and landed in the United States in 1993
as a touring sampler of African music called Africa Fete.
</P>
<P>
   This year's event features established and rising African music
stars like Salif Keita and the Wanda Band from Mali and the United
States; Papa Wemba and Molokai from the Democratic Republic of
Congo, Cheikh Lo from Senegal and Maryam Mursal from Somalia.
</P>
<P>
   The 20-city North American tour reaches Minneapolis on Thursday,
Champaign-Urbana, Ill., on Friday and Boston on Sunday. Africa Fete
arrives in New York on July 5 as a free attraction of the
Summerstage series in Central Park. Information: (888) 438-68742;
enter artist code 2145.
</P>
</TEXT>
