<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-NOTEBOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EMOTIONS BEGIN TO SURFACE ABOUT SERIES WITH BRAVES AND METS
</HEADLINE>
   (ja) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEVELAND _ Two weeks ago, even two days ago, many of the
Yankees played down the games they would play in the next seven
days: four against the Atlanta Braves, who have the best record in
the National League, and three against the Mets. But on the eve of
the coming series, emotions have begun to surface.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be pretty special,'' said Joe Torre, the
Yankees' manager. ``Especially the weekend with the Mets. That's
going to be electric. It's going to be loud; it's going to be
boisterous. I anticipate security will be increased.''
</P>
<P>
   Several players feel that the Yankees, a team having a great
season, will have an opportunity to play other good teams in a
playoff-type atmosphere. October-style baseball at the summer
solstice.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees will play host to the Braves on Monday (Atlanta's
Greg Maddux will start against Andy Pettitte) and Tuesday, and then
fly to Atlanta on Wednesday for two games at Turner Field.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got the best record from the American League, the best
record from the National League,'' said the reliever Jeff Nelson,
``and the possibility, if everything goes well, that we could meet
in the World Series.''
</P>
<P>
   Torre does not like interleague play. He feels that if the
Yankees and Braves meet in the post-season, the midseason games
will have robbed the World Series of the mystery that used to be
inherent in October. ``You had teams that really didn't know much
about each other, feeling each other out,'' Torre said.
</P>
<P>
   But now there is some information to be gleaned from the
interleague games. Nelson, for instance, will probably be matched
against the Braves' right-handed-hitting Andres Galarraga in
late-inning situations. ``Maybe I'll learn something about him,''
Nelson said. David Cone, too, has not faced Galarraga since the
slugger went to Colorado, and he is curious about what has changed
in Galarraga's swing since the days when Cone pitched for the Mets.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Brosius played for Oakland this season, and even in spring
training he had never had the chance to face Maddux, Tom Glavine,
et al. ``This will be a good chance for me to get a feel for
them,'' Brosius said.
</P>
<P>
   Said Torre: ``It's important that you play every team tough. You
don't want anyone to manhandle you _ that could be a psychological
factor in the future.''
</P>
<P>
   The series with the Mets, Nelson said, ``is just as big as any
other, and probably as big as the World Series, as far as George
Steinbrenner and New Yorkers are concerned.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Torre: ``I've been on both sides of the fence, and it means
a lot to ownership on both sides to beat the other team.
</P>
<P>
   ``I look forward to the Mets to get it over with. That's going
to be a spectacle. I will be happy when that's over with.''
</P>
<P>
   As it stands, the earned run average leaders in the respective
leagues will pitch against each other on Friday _ the Yankees'
Hideki Irabu against the Mets' Al Leiter. Bobby Jones and Masato
Yoshii of the Mets are scheduled to pitch against Pettitte and
Orlando Hernandez, respectively, in the final two games of the
series.
</P>
<P>
   The Umpire's Earring
</P>
<P>
   Joe Torre related a story about John Shulock, the umpire who was
behind home plate in spring training when Cleveland's Jaret Wright
hit Luis Sojo and broke his hand. Shulock was wearing an earring
that day, which drew the attention of Torre and Indian Manager Mike
Hargrove before the game. ``What's that all about?'' Torre asked,
for Shulock may have become the first umpire with an earring.
</P>
<P>
   Shulock explained that he had made a deal with his daughter. If
she earned excellent grades, he would wear an earring for a month.
She got the grades.
</P>
<P>
   After Sojo was hit, Shulock went to Hargrove, concerned about
the bad blood brewing. Then, with emphasis, Shulock said, ``I'm
going to stop this right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Hargrove mused dryly, ``I don't think you're going to stop it
wearing that earring.''
</P>
<P>
   Roster Developments
</P>
<P>
   Some updates on matters that could impact the Yankees' roster:
</P>
<P>
   _ Bernie Williams, on the 15-day disabled list with a sprained
right knee, began working out on an exercise cycle this weekend. If
all goes well, Joe Torre said, he will begin jogging and running on
Monday. Williams is eligible to come off the disabled list on
Friday, when the series with the Mets is to begin, and some of his
teammates believe he will return to the lineup sometime during the
weekend. Torre, who has said he does not expect Williams to be back
until after the All-Star Game break, is more skeptical.
</P>
<P>
   _ Mike Stanton still does not know anything more about the
appeal of his suspension. As it stands, he is scheduled to start
serving his suspension on Wednesday, when the Yankees will be
playing the third of their four games with the Braves.
</P>
<P>
   _ Jeff Nelson had an ice pack strapped to his lower back in the
clubhouse Sunday, treating stiffness that apparently has been
bothering him for the last week or so. Nelson's problem is not
considered serious, and Torre said he should continue to be
available to pitch.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
