6-21 -- Paul Kocher, head of Cryptography Research, a four-man
consulting firm, holds a smart card and a modified reader he
developed to help decipher the digital code of the cards, in order
to make them tamperproof. For his part, Kocher, who at 25 is
already a well-known expert in code breaking, says, ``As the
expertise becomes more widely available, the threats will become
more than academic.'' (Peter DaSilva/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) NEW YORK -- June 21, 1998 -- VH1-MEDIA, 6-21 -- John
Sykes, the president of VH1, has focused the cable channel on music
and music-related programs for adults, including ``Pop-Up Video,''
which brought computer-style information to the video genre. ``It's
a niche business,'' says Sykes. ``Our parents more or less gave up
their dominance of the record-buying business when they got into
having children and mortgages,'' he says. But for the baby boom
generation, there has always been a passionate connection to
music.'' (James Estrin/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) NEW YORK -- June 21, 1998 -- NYC-OPERA-KELLOGG-2, 6-21 --
Adam Klein, in the New York City Opera's production of ``Marco
Polo'' at the New York State Theater at Lincoln Center. In the
continuing debate over the reasons for the dwindling of classical
music audiences, there is the notion that new audiences are waiting
to be tapped and that new repertory is one way to tap them. ``I'm
willing to lose money on student discounts in 1998, in order to
build an audience for 2008.'' says Paul Kellogg, the general and
artistic director of the New York City Opera. (Sara Krulwich/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) NEW YORK -- June 21, 1998 -- NYC-OPERA-KELLOGG, 6-21 --
Paul Kellogg, the general and artistic director of the New York
City Opera. In his career, Kellogg, 60, has taken more risks than
most, emboldened by his belief in untapped audiences. ``People are
out there who don't know Puccini's 'Boheme' from Britten's 'Paul
Bunyan,''' he says. ``And they're just as likely to come to the
Britten, if they think that it be fresh and intriguing.'' These are
the people who, in other areas, Kellogg adds, first gravitate to
new movies, and new plays, before looking to the past. ``And I
think I'm reaching them.'' (Sara Krulwich/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
</P>
