<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving Sunday 6/21/98. Photo clients
will automatically receive these photos via AP's PhotoExpress or
may download them from either the Wieck Photo Database in Dallas at
972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at 305-448-8411.
Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) NEW YORK -- June 21, 1998 -- IMMIG-ASYLUM, 6-21 --
Sivajini Kadambarathnam, 35, right, and her 13-year-old son,
Rajakumar, recently reunited, after being in separate detention for
months after arriving from Sri Lanka. Because no children are
allowed in the Queens detention center in New York, Rajakumar was
sent to a center for juveniles in Miami. ``I cried and cried and
cried,'' says Mrs. Kadambarathnam. In New York, asylum seekers are
routinely kept in detention for months until a judge hears their
case. (Philip Greenberg/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) MONTEREY, Calif. -- June 21, 1998 --
CALIF-MONTEREY-TOURISM-2, 6-21 -- Developers want to build hotels,
malls and parking garages in Cannery Row, but preservationists say
that new development, including a four-story shopping plaza planned
for the center of the row, threatens the last vestiges of the old
life. Cannery Row first came to the attention of the National Trust
for Historic Preservation last year, during a battle over the fate
of the San Xavier Warehouse, one of the few remaining buildings
with a direct link to the canning industry. Peter DaSilva/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) MONTEREY, Calif. -- June 21, 1998 --
CALIF-MONTEREY-TOURISM-1, 6-21 -- Neal Hotelling, a
preservationist, standing along the Monterey Cannery Row coast
line. Hotteling, saved the old San Xavier Warehouse on Cannery Row,
from developers who sought to tear it down last year. Further
frustrated by the city's planning process during the battle,
Hotelling nominated Cannery Row for National Trust's annual listing
of endangered places. (Peter DaSilva/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) JUNIK, Yugoslavia -- June 21, 1998 -- KOSOVO-REBELS, 6-21
-- While Yugoslav troops in Kosovo have artillery and tanks, these
ethnic Albanian rebels are armed with rifles and ride a tractor.
Rebels vow to fight to the death, and their leaders insist that
they can defend their positions. The United States, in an effort to
stay the hand of Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic, has
threatened NATO intervention unless the soldiers are withdrawn from
the province and negotiations with a moderate ethnic Albanian
leader, Ibrahim Rugova, are resumed. (Wade Goddard/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) PHOENIX -- June 21, 1998 -- CENTENARIANS-2, 6-21 --
Centenarians attending a recent party in Phoenix. Standing from
left, Lloyd Botimer, 103, Merle McEathron, 102, Lenore Schaeffer,
101, and Paul Pair, 100. Seated, from left, were, Florence Thiele,
100, Minnie O'Donnell, 100, Essie Brown, 105, Lezetta Huber, 100,
and Ira Baldwin, 102. Centenarians are proportionately the United
States' fastest-growing age group, with projections that by the
middle of the next century, more than 800,000 Americans will be
over 100. (Jeff Topping/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) PHOENIX -- June 21, 1998 -- CENTENARIANS-1, 6-21 -- Lloyd
Botimer, 103, holding some of his prized medals, including one from
the Senior Olympics (in center of medal box) in 1994, is among the
growing ranks of centenarians in relatively good health who are
changing American attitudes on aging. Centenarians are
proportionately the United States' fastest-growing age group, with
projections that by the middle of the next century, more than
800,000 Americans will be over 100. (Jeff Topping/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) BOSTON -- June 21, 1998 -- SMITH-GLOBE-MEDIA-B&AMP;W, 6-21 --
Patricia Smith, a Boston Globe metropolitan region columnist,
dismissed because of fabrications in her work. The disclosure that
Ms. Smith had concocted people and quotes in at least four columns
earlier this year was particularly dramatic, given that it became
public just a week after The New Republic concluded that Stephen
Glass, a staff writer, fabricated all or part of 27 of the 41
articles he wrote for the magazine in two and a half years. Still,
editors say incidents of fakery remain few. (Stan Grossfeld/Boston
Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) SAN FRANCISCO -- June 21, 1998 -- SMART-CARD-SECURITY,
6-21 -- Paul Kocher, head of Cryptography Research, a four-man
consulting firm, holds a smart card and a modified reader he
developed to help decipher the digital code of the cards, in order
to make them tamperproof. For his part, Kocher, who at 25 is
already a well-known expert in code breaking, says, ``As the
expertise becomes more widely available, the threats will become
more than academic.'' (Peter DaSilva/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) NEW YORK -- June 21, 1998 -- VH1-MEDIA, 6-21 -- John
