<SLUG> BC-BOX-OFFICE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FANS CONSPIRE TO MAKE `X-FILES' WEEKEND BOX OFFICE KING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVE McNARY  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- ``The X-Files'' transformed itself impressively
from small to big screen with an estimated $31.3 million at 2,626
theaters nationwide during the Friday-Sunday period, studio sources
said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   20th Century Fox's eerie action-drama easily beat a solid
showing from ``Mulan,'' Disney's 36th animated feature, which had
$23 million at 2,888 sites.
</P>
<P>
   ``X-Files,'' with stars David Duchovny and Gillian Anderson as
FBI agents probing the paranormal implications of a Dallas building
explosion, posted the seventh-highest June opening ever and
performed in line or slightly better than forecasts.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're thrilled,'' said Tom Sherak, head of Fox's domestic
movie arm. ``This is one of those peaks in the peaks and valleys of
the business.''
</P>
<P>
   The executive said ``X-Files'' drew equally between men and
women. Strongest support came from young males, with more than 75
percent saying they would recommend the movie, Sherak said.
</P>
<P>
   Publicity for ``The X-Files'' stressed that the film would
resolve major questions raised during the five seasons of the TV
series. The key challenge for the studio will be to draw non-fans
of the series, Sherak said, noting that one-quarter of its weekend
audience came from that group.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said ``X-Files'' and ``Mulan'' _ both launched amid
mixed reviews _ had performed well amid strong holdover
competition.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fox and Disney have to be happy with the openings,'' said
Arthur Rockwell of Drake Capital Securities. ``Both of these were
somewhat risky projects in terms of widespread audience appeal.''
</P>
<P>
   Robert Bucksbaum, head of Reel Source tracking service, said
``X-Files,'' which carried a $63 million price tag, should wind up
with $125 million to $140 million domestically. He also said its
success won't necessarily lead to more movies based on TV shows.
</P>
<P>
   `` &UR;  &LR; `X-Files' is pretty unique because most other TV properties
do not have the constantly changing locales you need to take the
show to the next level and make a successful movie,'' Bucksbaum
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mulan,'' based on a Chinese folk tale of a young woman posing
as her father to fight an invasion, beat last year's $21.5 million
opening of Disney's previous animated project, ``Hercules,'' and
the $22 million total taken in after six weeks by Warner Bros.'
animated ``The Quest for Camelot.''
</P>
<P>
   The debut signals that Disney's status as the kingpin of
animation is likely to continue even amid stepped-up efforts by
rivals.
</P>
<P>
   Bucksbaum said ``Mulan'' drew well among adult women and should
go slightly past ``Hercules' &UR;  &LR; '' $100 million domestic total. The
movie, which carried a $90 million production cost, is expected to
perform well in overseas markets and generate solid profits.
</P>
<P>
   Paramount's third weekend of ``The Truman Show'' came in third
with $12.4 million at 2,911 theaters, giving the comedy-fantasy
more than $85 million in 17 days. Disney's second weekend of ``Six
Days, Seven Nights'' followed, with a respectable $10.5 million at
2,579 theaters, to go past $34 million in 10 days.
</P>
<P>
   Warner's third weekend of ``A Perfect Murder'' finished fifth
with $7.3 million at 2,755 locations. ``The top holdover films have
very respectable legs,'' Rockwell said.
</P>
<P>
   Sony's second weekend of the teen-comedy ``Can't Hardly Wait''
came in sixth with a disappointing $3.9 million at 1,987 sites as
it lost more than half its debut audience. Fox's fourth weekend of
``Hope Floats'' followed with $3.1 million at 1,872 theaters to top
$44 million.
</P>
<P>
   Sony's fifth weekend of ``Godzilla'' continued its fast fade in
eighth with $3 million at 2,337 theaters, followed by Paramount's
seventh weekend of ``Deep Impact'' with $2.7 million at 1,972
sites. The latter is the top grosser among movies released in 1998
with $133.1 million, giving it 79th place on the all-time domestic
list behind ``The Rock'' at $134 million.
</P>
<P>
   It's probable that ``Deep Impact'' will outgross ``Godzilla,''
now with $129.2 million at 83rd place on the all-time list, behind
``An Officer and a Gentleman.''
</P>
<P>
   Rounding out the top 10 was Disney's sixth weekend of ``The
Horse Whisperer'' with $2.4 million at 1,852 theaters to reach
nearly $63 million.
</P>
<P>
   The weekend's other major opening, Miramax's romantic comedy
``Hav Plenty,'' flopped with $1.1 million at 1,413 theaters as
moviegoers ignored Scot Cherot's tale of a tough-luck
African-American writer in New York.
</P>
<P>
   The weekend also marked the first in 27 that Paramount's
``Titanic'' finished out of the top 10. The epic still grossed a
respectable $1 million at 810 sites and has now taken in $585.5
million after 185 days.
</P>
<P>
   ``Titanic'' leads ``Star Wars'' as best domestic grosser by $124
million.
</P>
<P>
   Overall business was about equal to the same weekend last year
when ``Batman &AMP; Robin'' opened with $42.9 million, followed by ``My
Best Friend's Wedding'' with $21.7 million in its debut.
</P>
<P>
   ``The X-Files'' will face competition during the upcoming
weekend from Fox's opening of ``Dr. Dolittle'' with Eddie Murphy
and Universal's action-comedy ``Out of Sight'' with George Clooney.
New Line will re-release a restored version of ``Gone With the
Wind'' in about 200 theaters.
</P>
</TEXT>
