r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FEES-BANKS-SFCHRON &LR;      06-21 1088
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FEES-BANKS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FEE FRENZY _ CUSTOMERS CAN STEER CLEAR OF BANK CHARGES 
</HEADLINE>
   By PETER SINTON  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
U.S. banks are making record profits, and one reason is because
they're imposing more and higher fees on customers.
<TEXT>
<P>
   There is a ``fee frenzy,'' notes Bob McKinley, president of RAM
Research Corp. which tracks the credit card industry. ``Many
consumers are paying less in interest payments but they are getting
nickeled and dimed to death by fees.''
</P>
<P>
   For example:
</P>
<P>
   _ The average fee for a bounced check is now $21.36, up from
$20.80 last October, according to a March survey of 350 U.S. banks
by Bank Rate Monitor.
</P>
<P>
   _ Eight of the Top 10 banks charge noncustomers who use their
automated teller machines, and 55 percent of all U.S. banks impose
such surcharges, up from 48 percent in October.
</P>
<P>
   _ Late payment and over-the-limit fees on credit cards have each
jumped from an average of $13 to about $20 in just 18 months,
according to RAM Research.
</P>
<P>
   Some big banks including Fleet, First Union and Mellon now
charge as much as $25 to close a credit card account. Others charge
a $15 dormancy fee on accounts that are inactive for six months. If
you get a cash advance on a credit card, expect to pay up to 5
percent of the withdrawn amount in fees.
</P>
<P>
   Banks still make more money on interest income _ the spread
between what they charge on loans and what they pay on deposits _
than on customer fees.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; But the interest-rate spread is narrowing, as banks face
growing competition from brokerage firms and mutual funds for
customer assets.
</P>
<P>
   To gain and retain customers, banks are offering promotional
interest rates. That has helped lower the interest-rate spread to a
seven-year low of 4.06 percent.
</P>
<P>
   To make up for smaller spreads, banks are raising old fees and
coming up with new ones. As a result, fee income is rising four
times faster than interest income and now accounts for nearly 40
percent of bank income compared to about 32 percent a decade ago.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; On balance, banks are still raking it in. In the first quarter
of this year, U.S. bank profits soared 10 percent over the previous
year to a record $15.9 billion, according to the Federal Deposit
Insurance Corp.
</P>
<P>
   With sophisticated computer systems, banks can now track the
profitability of each account and each customer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Banks want all customers to pay their way,'' McKinley
explained. ``They are chipping away at grace periods and looking
for freeloaders and deadbeats.''
</P>
<P>
   This makes financial sense but it hasn't exactly enhanced the
image of bankers.
</P>
<P>
   The percentage of customers who were ``very satisfied'' with
their banks declined to 54 percent last year from 65 percent in
1994, according to a Gallup poll commissioned by the American
Bankers Association.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR; Consumers were particularly offended by fees. Only 12 percent
of bank customers strongly agreed that fees paid are for ``good
value'' received. And 60 percent of those who don't use a bank
cited fees as a major reason for taking their business elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Since most of us do use banks, here are some steps you can take
to avoid fees.
</P>
<P>
   _ Look at your choices.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Despite all the mergers, there are still more than 9,000
commercial U.S. banks. There also are savings and loans,
brokerages, mutual funds and other options for financial service.
</P>
<P>
   The 300 biggest banks often offer greater convenience and bigger
ATM networks than their smaller competitors &UR; . &LR;  But on average, they
impose 15 percent higher fees for deposit accounts than smaller
banks, according to U.S. Public Interest Research Group.
</P>
<P>
   Not one of the 50 largest U.S. banks offered any of the 10
cheapest checking accounts, Bank Rate Monitor reported last month.
</P>
<P>
   Banks that offered the most expensive accounts in March were
Citibank of San Francisco and NationsBank, which recently agreed to
buy Bank of America, according Florida-based Bank Rate Monitor.
</P>
<P>
   _ Play by the rules and read the fine print.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are plenty of financial land mines, but there are also
ways around them,'' said McKinley of RAM Research. He and others
advise paying bills on time, not going over credit limits and
following other procedures to avoid fees.
</P>
<P>
   Marin building contractor William Kopiecki said he reads monthly
statements carefully and raises a ruckus if there's a problem. He
recently noticed that it took eight to 11 days for two checks he
wrote totaling $15,500 to be credited to his account at MBNA after
they were debited from his account at Citibank. After spotting the
long lag and complaining to Citibank, he was assured he would get
much of his lost interest returned.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unless you complain, they're going to try to have the maximum
float with your money,'' said Kopiecki. ``I guess eternal vigilence
is the cost of financial liberty.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Only pay for services you need.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, if you rarely visit a teller, opt for an account
that offers unlimited checking, low minimum balance requirements
and low or no monthly fees as long as you bank by ATM, phone or
personal computer.
</P>
<P>
   If you have one of these accounts and do end up using a live
teller when you could have used an ATM, you'll pay a fee that is
usually about $3 but could be as much as $9.50, according to Bank
Rate Monitor.
</P>
<P>
   Even for full-service accounts, banks will often reduce or
eliminate fees if you maintain multiple accounts, keep a minimum
balance like $1,000 in your checking account or sign up for direct
deposit of your paycheck or Social Security payments.
</P>
<P>
   _ Use plastic wisely.
</P>
<P>
   Credit card users who do not pay off their monthly balances
should take advantage of promotional or ``teaser'' rates. When the
teaser rate expires and the rate shoots into double digits, switch
to another credit card or try to negotiate a lower rate on your
existing one.
</P>
<P>
   The best credit card strategy is to pay off your bills each
month, thereby benefitting from use of the money (or float) during
the free grace period and no interest or fees.
</P>
<P>
   ``Baby Boomers are getting smarter; they're looking for a free
ride,'' said McKinley. ``That's not the way it used to be.'' Almost
40 percent of credit card customers are now ``convenience'' users
who pay off their bills each month. That's up from 29 percent six
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Web sites that carry information on checking and credit card
rates and fees include Bank Rate Monitor (www.bankrate.com), RAM
Research (www.ramresearch.com) and Consumers' Checkbook
(www.checkbook.org).
</P>
</TEXT>
