<SLUG> BC-GLF-NOTEBOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOTEBOOK: MONTGOMERIEHAS ANOTHER UNPLEASANT EXCHANGE
</HEADLINE>
  (See also GLF-USOPEN and GLF-ANDERSON-COLUMN)  
(ja) 
 By CLIFTON BROWN    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ It was a disappointing tournament for Colin
Montgomerie, who was heckled by fans throughout the week.
Montgomerie finished at 11 over par, though he did shoot 69 Sunday.
However, Montgomerie had another unpleasant exchange with a fan
during Sunday's round.
</P>
<P>
   ``I seem to be blamed for winning the Ryder Cup, but I had 11
strong individuals with me as well,'' said Montgomerie, who helped
Europe defeat the United States last September in Spain. ``It's
always the minority that are more vocal than the majority,
unfortunately.''
</P>
<P>
   Montgomerie insisted that this week's problems would not kill
his love for the U.S. Open.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always said I really enjoy this tournament, and I always
will,'' Montgomerie said. ``It's a real mental battle. You get
rewarded for good shots, and you definitely get penalized for bad
ones. I'm a great fan of that and always will be.''
</P>
<P>
   By the time Montgomerie started to play well Sunday morning, he
was already out of contention. So his quest to win a major
continues.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a very difficult week,'' Montgomerie said. ``I found
out what I was doing wrong on the practice tee this morning, which
is a bit late. My alignment was wrong. Now I'll look forward to the
British Open.''
</P>
<P>
   A Course Favorite
</P>
<P>
   Paul Azinger's 65 Sunday was the best round of the tournament.
He was able to take advantage of an early-morning tee time. Though
he did not contend, Azinger said he hopes the U.S. Open returns to
the Olympic Club.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the United States Golf Association were ever to go to a
four or five-course rotation, you would like to see this on the
rotation,'' Azinger said. ``Maybe this, Pebble Beach, Shinnecock
and Winged Foot. I think all the players, for the most part, really
like this course.''
</P>
<P>
   His Best Birthday
</P>
<P>
   Matt Kuchar, the 1997 U.S. Amateur champion, shot a 74 Sunday
and finished tied for 14th. At 9 over par, he was the best among
the amateurs.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the hardest course I've ever seen,'' said Kuchar, who
celebrated his 20th birthday Sunday. ``I wanted to see how high I
could finish. I wanted to see my name on the leader board. This has
been a good birthday, a lot of fun. It's the most memorable one
I've ever had.''
</P>
<P>
   Woods Not Discouraged
</P>
<P>
   Casey Martin (11 over), the first player to compete in the U.S.
Open using a cart, finished tied for 23rd _ and second in driving
distance (291.3), to John Daly (295.6). Tiger Woods finished tied
for 18th at 10 over par. Woods will continue to hear criticism that
his game is not made for Open courses, but he was not discouraged.
</P>
<P>
   ``The putter wasn't there this week,'' Woods said. ``I didn't
play that well. But I hung in there on the course that was very
difficult.'
</P>
<P>
   Putts Fail Price Again
</P>
<P>
   Nick Price made a strong bid to win his fourth major
championship, but settled for fourth place after shooting a 73
Sunday, to finish 5 over par for the tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just couldn't make any putts,'' Price said. ``It has been
like that for four months. But I feel confident that I'm not that
far away. If I start making them, I can get on a streak like I was
in '93 and '94. I had a lot of birdie opportunities, but when
you're missing putts, it puts you on the defensive, and it's hard
to make up ground. But all and all it was a good week, very
encouraging. I'm looking forward to the rest of the year.''
</P>
</TEXT>
