<SLUG> BC-NY-SCHOOLS-CHANCELLOR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NYC SCHOOLS CHIEF SEEKS 2 MORE YEARS ON CONTRACT 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By JACQUES STEINBERG   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Seeking to break the city school system's recent
pattern of 11 leaders in 15 years, Schools Chancellor Rudy Crew
will soon ask the Board of Education to consider a two-year
extension to his contract, which is due to expire in July 1999.
</P>
<P>
   If the board agrees, which is considered likely, Crew's tenure
would be three months shy of six years. That would make him the
longest-serving chancellor in the 28-year history of the position
and the longest-serving chief schools executive _ the position was
known as superintendent before 1970 _ since William Jansen, who led
the schools for 11 years, from 1947 to 1958.
</P>
<P>
   Crew said Friday that he had ruled out staying beyond six years,
a milestone he would reach in October 2001, because he did not
intend to work with a mayor other than Rudolph Giuliani. Giuliani
is barred by law from seeking a third term in the next mayoral
election, in November 2001.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think after that period of time, a new mayor comes in and is
going to want to work with his or her own chancellor,'' said Crew,
who has enjoyed a close political alliance, and the occasional
after-hours cigar, with Giuliani.
</P>
<P>
   By law, it is the independent, seven-member board, and not the
mayor, that selects the chancellor. But although the mayor appoints
only two board members, mayors, because they approve the board's
budget, have always had a central role in filling the chancellor's
job.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview Friday, Giuliani said he would urge the board to
``keep the chancellor for as long as we can.'' Crew, whose annual
salary of $195,000 has remained constant since he was appointed in
October 1995, said he expected to seek a raise in coming
negotiations with the board.
</P>
<P>
   In the tumultuous search to replace Chancellor Ramon Cortines
after he announced his resignation in June 1995, Crew emerged as a
compromise choice only after the board majority and Giuliani had
eliminated each other's leading candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Board president William Thompson, a vocal supporter of Crew, did
not return calls to his home and office Friday. The four-year terms
of Thompson and the other six board members expire June 30. But he
and four other board members are expected to be reappointed. They
and two new board members are expected to take up the matter of
Crew's contract after they are seated July 7.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
