<HEADLINE>
FRANK TRIPPETT, 71, WRITER AND EDITOR 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Frank Trippett, a writer, reporter and magazine editor, died
June 18 at the Sound Shore Medical Center in New Rochelle, N.Y. He
was 71 and a resident of Larchmont, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   The cause was heart failure, his son, Robert, said.
</P>
<P>
   From 1961 to 1991, Trippett was an associate editor of Newsweek,
a senior editor of Look magazine, a freelance writer and editor and
then a senior writer and essayist for Time magazine. His writing
won awards from the American Bar Association and the American
Political Science Association.
</P>
<P>
   He studied at the University of Mississippi and elsewhere, and
served in the Navy in World War II and in the Army in the Korean
War. He worked on newspapers in the South before joining Newsweek.
</P>
<P>
   Besides his son, Robert, of Silver Spring, Md., he is survived
by his wife, the former Betty Timberlake; a son, John, of Danbury,
Conn.; two daughters, Bess Rathbone of Larchmont and Nan Widdop of
Tallahassee, Fla.; a brother, Bernard, of Dayton, Ohio, and nine
grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
