<SLUG> BC-METS-MARLINS-475&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
METS CALL FRANCO IN EARLY TO BEAT MARLINS 3-2
</HEADLINE>
   (ja) 
 By JASON DIAMOS    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ There was no way Bobby Valentine would have called on
John Franco this early before.
</P>
<P>
   But the bases were loaded with nobody out in the eighth inning
of a one-run game, the rest of Valentine's bullpen was struggling
and the Mets were trying not to become the first team to be swept
in a three-game series by the Florida Marlins this season. So the
Mets manager summoned his closer and hoped for the best.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bobby's comment to me was, `We have to put John in, and we
need him to pull a Houdini act,''' Bob Apodaca, the pitching coach,
said. Thirteen pitches and one nearly botched double-play ball
later, Franco pumped his left fist and sprinted off the mound to
end the inning. He had pulled off his own version of the Great
Escape.
</P>
<P>
   For an encore in the ninth, the 37-year-old left-hander shook
off a lead-off walk to hold Florida scoreless and close out his
16th save. He had just preserved a 3-2 victory for the Mets to snap
a four-game losing streak.
</P>
<P>
   Franco's heroics before a Father's Day crowd of 30,673 at Shea
Stadium enabled Al Leiter (9-3) to win his sixth consecutive start.
And should the Mets advance to the playoffs for the first time in a
decade, Sunday's victory might well be remembered long after this
season is over.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe this was our hump game,'' Franco said after the Mets had
won for only the fourth time in their last 10 games, all against
the salary-challenged Marlins and Montreal Expos. ``Maybe we needed
this wake-up call. We have played some teams we should beat. But we
haven't. This could be a little kick in the pants, to say, `Hey,
let's get going.'''
</P>
<P>
   The Mets needed something. They are having almost as much
trouble scoring as the U.S. soccer team is in France. Leiter, who
is now 5-0 pitching after a Mets defeat, probably felt fortunate
that he left after seven innings and 120 pitches with a 3-2 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Even though they were facing 21-year-old Joe Fontenot, who had
an 8.14 earned run average entering the game, the Mets needed a
two-strike wild pitch with Leiter at-bat to tie the game at 2-2 in
the fifth. Their winning rally in the seventh consisted of a Brian
McRae single, a Rey Ordonez sacrifice and a two-out single by
Edgardo Alfonzo.
</P>
<P>
   Fontenot (0-5) allowed just five singles in seven innings.
</P>
<P>
   John Hudek began pitching the eighth for the Mets by allowing
single to Todd Zeile. Cliff Floyd greeted Dennis Cook with a
single, Derrick Lee walked and like that, the bases were loaded.
Out went the call for Franco.
</P>
<P>
   ``It could have been the bottom of the ninth, with the bases
loaded and no outs,'' said Franco, who barely had enough time to
warm up. ``Hopefully, I won't have to come through that situation
again the rest of the year.''
</P>
<P>
   Apodaca said: ``This is by far the earliest we have ever brought
Johnny in. ``And today he saved our bacon.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   On his way in from the bullpen, Franco had envisioned a
best-case scenario: He would induce John Wehner into a comebacker
to the mound, which would trigger an easy pitcher-to-home-to-first
double play. But even the best-laid plans run into glitches. On
Franco's first pitch, Wehner grounded right back to him. But with
all the time in the world, he bounced his throw to catcher Mike
Piazza.
</P>
<P>
   ``I alligator-armed it,'' Franco said. ``As soon as I threw, I
turned around because I didn't want to look.''
</P>
<P>
   Piazza, who reacted like a hockey goalie, had no such choice.
``He just kind of chunked it, like you chunk a wedge shot,'' Piazza
said. ``He just threw it right into the ground. I don't even know
if it made the dirt.'' Somehow, Piazza was able to avert disaster.
He fielded the short-hop and tagged Zeile out at the plate for the
first out.
</P>
<P>
   Sensing that he had allowed a golden opportunity to slip through
his hands, Franco held his head in his hands on the mound.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm known for making things difficult,'' Franco said. ``I'm
just happy I got out of it.''
</P>
<P>
   He did so by striking out Mike Redmond and then the left-handed
hitting Mark Kotsay, pinch-hitting for Fontenot. Franco nearly flew
off the mound, so badly did he want to celebrate what he had just
done with the rest of his teammates.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think attitude filters down from the top, whether it's an
organization a corporation or a bullpen,'' Valentine said. ``He's
at the top. His attitude filters down. I really think that can be
part and parcel of everyone else stepping up.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
