A9755 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-COL-BUDGET-NYT &LR;      06-21 0760
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-COL-BUDGET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: YOU SAY PRIVATE, I SAY PUBLIC 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By ELIZABETH KOLBERT   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It is just after 3 o'clock on a recent afternoon and
the Hamilton Fish Park branch library on the Lower East Side is
beginning to fill with children. First come the older ones, who
stride in purposefully, with knapsacks full of homework. Then come
the very young ones, who have clearly been sent to the library
because it is safer than sending them home to an empty apartment.
</P>
<P>
   The library does seem safe _ there is a guard posted by the door
_ and before the children arrive, at least, the books and chairs
are in order. But it is hard to ignore the general shabbiness.
Paint is peeling and the tables are beaten up. The public bathrooms
are under repair, blocked off by sheets of plastic.
</P>
<P>
   Asked when he expects the repairs to be completed, one librarian
answers sardonically, ``We don't.''
</P>
<P>
   The next day, also at roughly 3 o'clock, well-heeled visitors
are streaming into the Museum of Modern Art. In the sculpture
garden, there are German tourists drinking $2.50 espressos, while
in the gift shop, there is a long line at the cash register, and in
front of Picasso's ``Les Demoiselles d'Avignon,'' so many
fascinated _ or at least footsore _ fans have gathered that there
is no more room on the bench.
</P>
<P>
   The museum's wealth is everywhere apparent, indeed virtually on
display. On the second floor, just before you reach Monet's
waterlilies, is a model for a planned expansion, which would,
according to the accompanying description, ``radically reinvent''
the way the Modern presents its collection. Its price tag: $650
million.
</P>
<P>
   In their ugly budget battle, Mayor Rudolph Giuliani and Peter
Vallone, the City Council speaker, haven't made much secret of
their heartfelt desire to humiliate each other. When you cut not
just the City Council's ``member items,'' but also its own
operating budget, as the mayor recently tried to do, it is clear
that the personal really is the political.
</P>
<P>
   Mixed up in all this wonderfully spiteful and vindictive
squabbling, there is something like a philosophical difference. In
their wrangling, the council and the mayor are consistently at odds
over the basic question of what private institutions should expect
from the public and vice versa.
</P>
<P>
   After almost five years in office, Giuliani has made it clear
that he expects public institutions to start pulling their own
weight, and he has encouraged them to seek out private money to
perform basic services like street cleaning and park maintenance.
This year he proposed expanding this concept to the public
libraries, cutting funds they had expected to use to buy books and
pay librarians and urging them to raise the amount from private
sources.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think public-private partnerships have been a very valuable
resource for making institutions more independent,'' he said,
defending his proposed cuts to libraries like the Hamilton Fish
branch.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the mayor has been unusually generous to some
of the city's most glamorous private enterprises, from rich Wall
Street firms to the even richer New York Yankees. Just as he was
cutting about $15 million from the city's libraries, he was
offering about $65 million to help the Modern finance its ambitious
expansion.
</P>
<P>
   Against the mayor's boundary-blurring style, the members of the
City Council have _ out of principle, political calculation or
sheer inertia _ defended the old pattern. When they got the mayor's
budget, they promptly cut the money for the Modern and restored
funds for the libraries. They have also very vocally opposed the
mayor's plans to finance a new Yankee Stadium, and spoken up for
such mundane services as garbage collection and recycling.
</P>
<P>
   As the battle stands now, the City Council _ somewhat improbably
_ seems to be winning. When the mayor came back with his recent
vetoes, he left in the $15 million the council had added back for
the libraries. But he could not on his own put back money for the
Modern.
</P>
<P>
   When the council overrode his vetoes, it put back yet another $7
million for the libraries and nothing for the Modern.
</P>
<P>
   It remains to be seen whether the Masters of the Universe who
serve on the museum's board can somehow bend the council to their
will. But that the Modern's expansion will, in any case, move
forward is probably a safe bet.
</P>
<P>
   As to whether the bathroom in the Hamilton Fish library will be
working again any time soon, that's another matter.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
