<SLUG> BC-NY-ELECT-ESPADA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ESPADA SAYS INDICTMENT WILL NOT HINDER CAMPAIGN TO REGAIN STATE
SEAT 
</HEADLINE>
  (ja) 
 By JONATHAN P. HICKS    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ While an indictment might typically signal the
downturn of a politician's prospects, Pedro Espada Jr., a former
state senator from the Bronx, says that his campaign to regain his
old job in Albany will only be energized following his arraignment
on charges of Medicaid fraud.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is nothing that will keep me from waging a vigorous
campaign,'' Espada said in an interview Friday. ``Anyone who has
ever known me understands that when I feel an injustice has been
done, I get up and hit harder and harder.''
</P>
<P>
   Espada, who operates a health clinic in the Bronx, was arraigned
on Wednesday with two of his employees on charges that they
illegally diverted $221,000 in Medicaid money to his failed 1996
re-election campaign and that of his son, Pedro Gautier Espada,
then an assemblyman.
</P>
<P>
   The indictment came a few days after Espada, long a political
foe of the Bronx Democratic Party organization, announced that he
would reverse an earlier decision to stay out of politics and would
run against state Sen. David Rosado to regain his old seat. Espada
has denied the fraud charges and said that they were politically
motivated.
</P>
<P>
   That allegation, several Bronx politicians and political
strategists said, may have influence with the electorate. Michael
Nieves, a political consultant who has worked with several
Democratic candidates in the Bronx, said that Espada ``will almost
certainly spin this in a way where he is the victim, taking on the
big, bad Democratic machine.''
</P>
<P>
   ``And that's a way to motivate people,'' Nieves added.
</P>
<P>
   Espada's indictment also came just days after Espada revealed a
videotape his son had secretly made, recording a conversation on
May 23 between his son and Rosado. In that tape, Rosado boasted of
the Democratic Party's ability to influence the Bronx district
attorney, Robert Johnson, to drop the investigation if Espada
pledged not to run for state Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Espada also said he holds several audiotapes of conversations
between himself and at least two other politicians, including
Assemblyman Roberto Ramirez, the Bronx Democratic leader. Espada
would not disclose the contents of the tapes of Ramirez, saying
only that the Bronx party leader had ``better be careful about what
he denies.''
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Espada played an audio recording of a conversation
between state Sen. Larry Seabrook and Sandra Love, an employee of
Espada's clinic who was also indicted on fraud charges. On the
tape, Seabrook said he had been the target of investigations that
he described as being motivated by the county Democratic
organization.
</P>
<P>
   Seabrook had planned to run for Congress this year against Rep.
Eliot L. Engel. But after meeting with Ramirez, Seabrook two weeks
ago announced that he had changed his mind and would run for
re-election instead.
</P>
<P>
   Seabrook said at the time that he had not raised enough money or
registered enough voters for his campaign to have been successful.
Seabrook did not return telephone messages on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The elder Espada has said that he and Ramirez, the Democratic
chairman, had agreed that Ramirez would use his influence to
prevent the Bronx district attorney from investigating the clinic
if Espada would refrain from running against Rosado.
</P>
<P>
   Ramirez has denied that there was a deal to that effect with
Johnson, and the district attorney has maintained that political
considerations were never a factor in his investigations. Rosado
has said that he had lied in his taped conversation to serve his
own political purpose _ to eliminate Espada as a potential
opponent.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Espada said his family's campaign operation had begun
in earnest. In addition to his own campaign, his brother, Jose
Espada, is running for the Assembly seat now held by Ruben Diaz Jr.
And Espada's son, the city councilman, is running against Rosado
for the position of Democratic district leader.
</P>
<P>
   Both Diaz and Rosado are gearing up for what is likely to be a
passionate battle with the Espadas.
</P>
<P>
   ``The court will decide whether there was any wrongdoing,'' Diaz
said. ``But if the Espadas are running in the primary, you can't
take them lightly. They have a presence in the area that cannot be
taken for granted.''
</P>
</TEXT>
