<HEADER>
A9769 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-WELFARE-CUTS-990(2     06-21 1030
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-WELFARE-CUTS-990(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAYOR'S NEW STRATEGY MAKES IT HARDER TO GET WELFARE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By RACHEL L. SWARNS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ For years, the poor, the hungry and the jobless have
poured into the squat welfare office on Bergen Street in Brooklyn
where city workers tried to ease the pangs of poverty with
government checks. But today, the primary goal at the office, as a
city manual for the workers states, is to discourage people from
applying at all.
</P>
<P>
   People who push through the smudged glass doors are told to look
for jobs, not welfare, and to lean on relatives, not city charity.
Those who insist on seeking public assistance must hunt for as many
as 20 jobs before getting a formal interview. And two months after
workers began delivering the new message in Brooklyn and at another
office in Queens, the number of welfare applications there has
plummeted.
</P>
<P>
   While 60 percent of the people who walked into those two offices
once ended up on welfare, fewer than 10 percent land on the dole
now, city officials said. It is too early to say whether the
staggering decline can be maintained or replicated citywide, but
the Giuliani administration's strategy will soon transform the
lives of needy adults and children all across New York City.
</P>
<P>
   The policy shift, which is to be adopted by all city welfare
offices over the next nine months, signals the expansion of Mayor
Rudolph Giuliani's efforts to steer the city away from its
traditionally liberal approach to the needy as he increasingly
emphasizes self-reliance over government dependence.
</P>
<P>
   ``People shouldn't have welfare anymore,'' said Mark Hoover, a
deputy commissioner at the city's Human Resources Administration,
which runs the city welfare programs, during a meeting with
officials from community groups earlier this month. ``What they
should have is work and work opportunities.''
</P>
<P>
   But the city manual describes employment as a ``secondary
goal.'' The ``primary goal,'' it says, is diverting people from
applying for public assistance while at the same time offering
stopgap subsidies like rent assistance and food stamps.
</P>
<P>
   And it remains unclear whether the people discouraged from
applying for welfare actually find jobs or simply languish in
poverty. City officials declined to release those statistics,
saying they were now analyzing them.
</P>
<P>
   Tightening access to welfare is increasingly popular across the
country, but the strict, systematic approach is new for a city that
has focused more recently on moving welfare recipients into
workfare. Over the last three years, the number of welfare
applications approved citywide has held steady at about 55 percent,
city records show.
</P>
<P>
   But in January, when Giuliani outlined the priorities for his
second term, he vowed to transform welfare offices into ``job
centers'' where the poor would be steered toward jobs, not
government checks. City officials said the plan would ultimately
reduce welfare applications across the city and strengthen poor
communities with its renewed emphasis on work.
</P>
<P>
   In the neighborhood surrounding the Boerum Hill office in
Brooklyn alone, for instance, the strategy is expected to reduce
the welfare rolls by 30 percent over the next three years.
</P>
<P>
   Advocates for the poor, who like several former welfare
officials were stunned by the dramatic drop in applications, fear
that city workers are concentrating less on jobs than on
discouraging people from applying for welfare. They say
discouraging poor, unskilled people is easier than helping them
find jobs in New York City, where the unemployment rate is 7.7
percent, compared with the national rate of 4.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a bogus policy designed to reduce the welfare rolls,''
said Helen Lee, a staff attorney at the Legal Aid Society, who has
begun monitoring the job centers along with other lawyers for the
poor. ``We're afraid needy people aren't getting welfare when they
need it.''
</P>
<P>
   But city officials say that many people find jobs and that those
who need welfare get it. Even those who leave the centers without
jobs or welfare often go home with food stamps and Medicaid that
will help stabilize their lives while they search for work, city
officials say.
</P>
<P>
   Once applicants learn that they must show proof of a daily job
search before obtaining welfare, and once they hear that welfare
recipients must sweep streets or answer telephones in exchange for
their benefits, many decide they would rather struggle on their
own, city officials say.
</P>
<P>
   ``More people are successfully finding jobs and making other
choices than before,'' said Hoover, who worked as a welfare
administrator in Wisconsin, which reduced the number of welfare
applications with a similar strategy. ``We feel that families are
going to benefit from this.''
</P>
<P>
   While the debate between city officials and advocates for the
poor remains unresolved, welfare applicants continue to find a
dizzying new world behind the dingy cement walls of the Greenwood
Job Center in Brooklyn.
</P>
<P>
   The caseworkers call themselves financial planners. And the
applicants, called job seekers, watch videos describing job
openings at nursing homes, restaurants and drugstores as they wait
in pink and gray plastic chairs for their interviews.
</P>
<P>
   ``Welfare is time limited,'' signs on the walls say in a pointed
reminder to all who come. ``A job is your future.''
</P>
<P>
   In the old days, people filled out welfare applications on the
first visit and waited at home until the formal eligibility
interview, which was scheduled for about five days later. Today,
job seekers cannot fill out applications until the second visit,
and they must search for work before the eligibility interview and
during the month or so while the application is assessed.
</P>
<P>
   All the while, financial planners help clients explore
``alternatives for independence,'' telling mothers to seek child
support, urging former soldiers to apply for veterans benefits,
requiring laid-off workers to file for unemployment benefits and
assessing whether relatives or churches can help them.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Damaris Ferrer, 22, her pregnant belly bulging beneath her
T-shirt, was told to consider relying on her mother, who has
supported her with a $537 monthly Social Security check since Ms.
Ferrer left her job as cashier in October. After learning about the
strict job-search requirements, Ms. Ferrer decided to do just that,
at least until the baby is born and she can find another job.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was hoping for some help,'' she said last week. ``But I'm
just going to stay with my mother until she throws me out.''
</P>
<P>
   Valerie Rodriguez, an 18-year-old mother, said she also left
Greenwood without being allowed to apply for welfare, food stamps
or health insurance last week. It was her second visit, she said,
and she was told to come back for a third.
</P>
<P>
   But her brother, a waiter who supports Ms. Rodriguez and her
2-year-old son with his $180 weekly check while she studies for her
high school equivalency exam, decided it would be easier for him to
find a second job than for his sister to get public assistance.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been struggling on our own for all this time,'' said Ms.
Rodriguez, her ponytail swinging and her nose-ring sparkling as she
shrugged away the worry in her older brother's eyes. ``I guess
we'll just keep struggling.''
</P>
<P>
   In the eyes of city officials, they are success stories, women
who considered their options and chose to avoid the culture of
dependency. Advocates for the poor, however, question whether
people who find it too cumbersome to apply for help can be truly
considered successes.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Rodriguez, for instance, who never applied for free health
insurance, plans to rely on Tylenol and prayer, since she has
neither a job nor Medicaid to cover her medical expenses.
</P>
<P>
   But city officials emphasize that poor people will get needed
services if they agree to abide by the new guidelines, and
emergencies will be addressed immediately. And some welfare
applicants support the city's strategy, including Franklin Conde,
40, who is unemployed and now searching for work under the new
strict rules.
</P>
<P>
   ``This will motivate you,'' said Conde, who applied for welfare
after being unable to find work as an engineer's assistant.
``Whoever established this program is on the right track.''
</P>
<P>
   Welfare specialists say there is little research to dispute or
support that contention, and say city officials should track people
who opt not to apply for welfare to determine whether they find
jobs or languish in poverty. City officials say they plan to do
that, but they have been reluctant in the past to track people who
have left the welfare rolls.
</P>
<P>
   Without careful research, the welfare specialists say, it will
be difficult to determine whether the plan empowers the poor or
makes desperate lives more miserable.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to be open to the possibility that the city is right,
that welfare is bad, that dependency breeds more dependency and
robs people of self-sufficiency,'' said Gordon Berlin, a senior
vice president of Manpower Demonstration Research Corp., a
nonprofit group that evaluates the impact of welfare policy.
</P>
<P>
   ``But you also have to be open to the idea that they're wrong,''
said Berlin, who was responsible for budget and policy at the Human
Resources Administration under Mayor Edward Koch in the late 1980s.
``And if they are, people will have less income, less support, less
stable housing. If they are really stretched thin, then children
and families can get hurt.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-21-98 2323EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
