<DOCNO> NYT19980621.0235 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-21 23:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9774 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOC-LEBRETON-COL-TEX     06-21 0871
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-LEBRETON-COL-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. BLEW CHANCE TO ADVANCE SPORT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GIL LEBRETON 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Satan,'' just like in Matthew's gospel, was foiled again
yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   Hopefully for U.S. soccer, this humbling won't end up in
someone's sermon 2,000 years from now.
</P>
<P>
   For the proud niche of soccer fans in the United States, there
should be comfort in knowing that their grand game did not disgrace
the nation yesterday in Lyon, France.
</P>
<P>
   No. By the time that the clock ran out on Iran's 2-1 victory,
much of the American viewing audience was either (A) napping or (B)
watching golf on TV.
</P>
<P>
   Ten years of trying to pick up the game by its kneesocks, of
bidding for and then successfully staging the '94 World Cup, of
trying to build a U.S. team that could earn respect on the world
stage _ and this is what they get?
</P>
<P>
   In Iran, where they once referred to us as ``The Great Satan,''
the victory prompted midnight prayers and dancing in the streets.
The Iranians scored two goals, but huge points more for their
sportsmanship and the heart that they showed.
</P>
<P>
   Here at home, alas, it was hard to swallow. In terms of a future
_ read ``corporate dollars'' _ the defeat may not have delivered a
death blow to soccer in this country. But at the moment, consider
it down and bleeding.
</P>
<P>
   For one day, soccer had the U.S. viewing audience mostly to
itself. People who didn't know a soccer ball from a frozen ham
suddenly had a storyline they could sink their teeth into. A Ted
Koppel kind of game. To a lot of Americans, still, mention of Iran
brings back memories of the hostage crisis, the Ayatollah Khomeini
and U.S. flags being burned in the Tehran streets.
</P>
<P>
   And what? You said Team USA was heavily favored?
</P>
<P>
   You bet they watched.
</P>
<P>
   But it was more of the same, wasn't it? The U.S. players'
inability to put the ball in the net turned into a night of
frustration. They hit the crossbar. They hit the goalposts _ three
times. And now, after one more World Cup match, they will hit the
road.
</P>
<P>
   Spare the e-mails, please. They've become trite.
</P>
<P>
   After I penned a fairly light-hearted piece 12 days ago, teasing
how the World Cup gets lost in the U.S. translation, I received a
spate of electronic dispatches rife with name-calling and
high-handed piety.
</P>
<P>
   Ron Pitney of Arlington wrote, ``Your refusal to learn the game
amounts to intellectual bankruptcy and until you take the time to
really understand the `game within the game' you really should
limit your comments to those sports you understand!''
</P>
<P>
   Ah, yes, the ``game within the game'' of soccer. At least two of
the e-mail writers claimed that soccer is now the preferred sport
of ``intelligent people,'' and thus they understood perfectly why
only they grasped its nuances _ and, apparently, I didn't.
</P>
<P>
   While they were memorizing Chaucer, I suppose, they must have
missed the fact that nowhere in the earlier column did I say I
didn't like soccer, the apparent Official Game of Mensa. I simply
strove to make points about the World Cup's lack of scoring,
particularly the U.S. team's. And while praising World Cup '94 for
its success, despite the rest of the world's skepticism, I noted
how the great event still doesn't captivate the same throngs on our
shores.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, I think I was on the same mailing list as Salman
Rushdie.
</P>
<P>
   ``You people are morons if you can't see that soccer is HUGE
with an educated segment of the population,'' read one of the
unsigned notes.
</P>
<P>
   I give up. What don't we morons understand?
</P>
<P>
   There's offsides. There's corner kicks. There are yellow cards
and red cards. Soccer is not rocket science. As has been proven
many times at the World Cup, the coaches don't even need to speak
the players' language.
</P>
<P>
   The best e-mail comment, as it turned out, came from a truly
erudite gentleman named Norm Biven. He called my attention to the
commercial that Nike is running during the Cup telecasts. It shows
the defending world champs from Brazil stuck during a flight delay
at the Rio airport. They begin playing with the soccer ball, while
a samba from Sergio Mendes plays in the background.
</P>
<P>
   They and the ball go through X-ray machines, under taxiing jet
wings, down baggage ramps, before the world's best player, Ronaldo,
finishes with a footwork exhibition that would make the
Globetrotters envious. The punch line is that Ronaldo gets to the
terminal gate, kicks _ and clangs it off the metal post.
</P>
<P>
   The kids watching frown. Ronaldo shrugs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just because Ronaldo's shot clangs off the post at the end
doesn't make it any less entertaining,'' Biven wrote. ``It's not
the scoring. It's the samba, silly.''
</P>
<P>
   I know. But again, thanks to days like yesterday, it gets lost
in the translation.
</P>
<P>
   Americans love underdogs, but they enjoy winning more. The samba
is fine, but the preferred tune, last time I checked, was ``We Will
Rock You.'' Tennis' Davis Cup was big once here, too _ until the
United States started losing it.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. soccer blew it big time yesterday. It doesn't take a genius
to see that it's going to be a tough four years.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; tagtop:Gil LeBreton, (817) 390-7760
 &LR; tagbottom:''lebreton\Nstar-telegram.com''
</P>
</TEXT>
