<HEADER>
A9775 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-LABOR-HOSPITAL-500     06-21 1283
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-LABOR-HOSPITAL-500&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONTRACT PROMISES JOB SECURITY FOR 50,000 HOSPITAL WORKERS
</HEADLINE>
   (ja) 
 By STEVEN GREENHOUSE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Thirty-five private hospitals and nursing homes in
New York City reached a tentative agreement Sunday that provides
far-reaching job-security provisions for 50,000 workers despite the
wrenching upheaval in the city's health-care industry.
</P>
<P>
   At a time when many experts are estimating that New York's
hospitals have to cut their work force by 15 percent over the next
five years, the agreement reduces pressures for layoffs by tapping
the union's pension plan to finance an unusual early retirement
program.
</P>
<P>
   The 40-month contract, negotiated by 1199, the National Health
and Human Service Employees Union, provides for diverting more than
$135 million from the union's overfunded pension plan to finance
the early retirements _ most payments would be $25,000 in cash _ to
encourage at least 3,000 hospital workers to retire early.
</P>
<P>
   This early retirement plan was made possible, both sides
acknowledged, by the Wall Street boom, which fattened the pension
plan's reserves, and by some unusual bargaining.
</P>
<P>
   Dennis Rivera, 1199's president, announced the contract Sunday
after two days of nonstop negotiations with the League of Voluntary
Hospitals, a group of 35 private nonprofit institutions including
Beth Israel, Montefiore, Mount Sinai, Presbyterian and St.
Vincent's hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   As in the current contract, the new agreement virtually bars
layoffs of workers hired before Sept. 17, 1992, saying they can be
laid off only if the institution closes or is in perilous financial
condition. Union officials estimate that the rule applies to 75
percent of the union's workers at the hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   If workers hired after that date are laid off, they are to
receive, with the help of unemployment insurance, 80 percent of
their pay for two years _ up from 18 months in the current
contract. In addition, they are given the right to the first job
opening for which they are qualified at any of the 35 institutions.
</P>
<P>
   ``This contract will offer virtual job security,'' said Rivera,
who said that the contract provides no-layoff guarantees to more
employees than any other multi-employer contract in the nation. He
predicted that if any less experienced workers were laid off,
almost all would be able to find other jobs in league institutions
within two years.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides said the agreement would enable the hospitals to
reduce employment gradually, and thus become more efficient and
keep costs for patients under control.
</P>
<P>
   After the negotiations were completed at 10:30 Sunday morning,
Rivera was visibly exhausted in a news conference at 1199's
headquarters on West 43rd Street, saying at one point that he
needed to sit down. The union's 150-member negotiating committee
unanimously approved the agreement Sunday, and the 50,000 workers
are scheduled to vote on it over the next two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   In announcing details of the agreement, Rivera said he was
calling off plans for the 50,000 workers to go on strike on June
30, the day their current contract expires.
</P>
<P>
   The new contract covers laundry, housekeeping and food workers,
custodial staff and X-ray and laboratory technicians _ as a group
they average $30,000 a year in wages. The contract provides for a 3
percent raise for the first year, an $1,800 lump sum bonus in the
second year and a 3 percent raise over the contract's last 16
months.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Appearing beside Rivera at the news conference, Bruce McIver,
president of the hospitals league, said: ``Neither of us got
everything we wanted. There was a lot of compromise.'' Nonetheless,
the hospitals obtained several important concessions, including a
bonus rather than a wage increase in the second year.
</P>
<P>
   The Wall Street boom has created hundreds of millions of dollars
in overfunding in the pension plan, whose assets are invested in
stocks and bonds. Thanks to that overfunding, the contract gives
the health-care institutions more than $100 million in savings in
their pension contributions.
</P>
<P>
   The hospitals will not have to make any contributions for 10
months to the pension plan and during the rest of the contract will
pay 6.25 percent of payroll in pension contributions, down from
6.75 percent at present.
</P>
<P>
   McIver insisted that the contract was not overly generous and
would not create an undue strain on the hospitals. ``A 6 percent
wage increase over 40 months isn't bad,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Rivera said he was proudest of the contract's job-security
provisions, predicting that other health-care unions around the
nation would seek to match them. He noted that for the first time,
part-time workers hired before September 17, 1992, would be covered
by the strong no-layoff language.
</P>
<P>
   ``Management told us for months that it needed to lay off
thousands of our members, that the employment-security provisions
in our old contract could not stand,'' Rivera said. ``In fact, with
this contract, we have won improved security guarantees, the
biggest early retirement package in our history, as well as
increases in wages and health coverage.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the new contract, the workers will no longer have to make
co-payments or any other payment to their dental plan. They already
do not have to pay premiums or make co-payments in their basic
health insurance plan.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement provides for the hospitals and nursing homes to
contribute a total of $60 million a year to a retraining and job
security fund, which will be used to retrain laid off workers and
pay them the equivalent of 80 percent of their wages for two years.
That $60 million will come largely from money the hospitals save on
pension contributions. The job security fund, although at far
smaller levels, was first set up in the contract negotiated in
1992, while the no-layoff provisions were first negotiated in the
1994 contract.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, Rivera said that in negotiations, he had
originally pushed to extend the no-layoff clause to cover more
workers but that management had sought to reduce the coverage. He
said he dropped his demand when management insisted that in
exchange it be given the right to lay off experienced workers when
hospitals merge.
</P>
<P>
   Under the new early-retirement program, workers 62 years old
with 20 years on the job will be entitled to a full pension, but
under the current contract, they must have 25 years.
</P>
<P>
   As further incentive, workers 62 years old with 20 years on the
job, or 65 with five years on the job, are being offered not just a
full pension but also a $25,000 one-time payment and health
insurance until they qualify for Medicare,
</P>
<P>
   Workers as young as 55 would be offered $25,000 payments and
varying combinations of health-care and pension coverage to accept
early retirement.
</P>
<P>
   Negotiators estimated all these measures would cost $135 million
to $150 million and would persuade 3,000 to 3,700 workers to retire
early.
</P>
<P>
   The union made no headway toward one of its chief goals, a
promise from the hospitals not to fight its effort to unionize
thousands of workers at the hospitals' satellite clinics throughout
the metropolitan area.
</P>
<P>
   Negotiators for both sides acknowledged that they felt
considerable pressure to reach an agreement before the June 30
contract expiration. Hospital executives wanted to avoid the burden
of running their institutions during a strike. Union officials
feared that some hospitals might order large-scale layoffs of
long-time workers once the present contract contract expired and
left them without protection against layoffs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
