<HEADLINE>
STEWART, LEHMAN CAN'T STAY ON COURSE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIMMY BURCH 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The Olympic Club added to its U.S. Open legacy
yesterday when another 54-hole leader stumbled down the stretch and
lost the tournament.
</P>
<P>
   For those counting at home, the course is now four-for-four in
producing dramatic, comeback winners at the Open. The latest to
fall, Payne Stewart, added his name to a list that also includes
Ben Hogan (1955), Arnold Palmer (1966) and Tom Watson (1987). All
were reeled in at Olympic by players with fewer career victories on
the PGA Tour.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd say the golf course won. The golf course lived up to its
reputation,'' Stewart said after flushing a four-stroke lead in the
final round and losing by a stroke to Lee Janzen.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart joined Tom Lehman, his final-round playing partner, as
the two sympathetic characters in the latest Olympic melodrama.
</P>
<P>
   Unable to control his driver down the stretch, Stewart hit his
fewest number of fairways (six) and greens in regulation (nine) of
any round during Open week while ballooning to a 74. Lehman, a
sentimental favorite who was playing in the final group at the Open
for a fourth consecutive year, fell short once again in his Open
quest with a closing 75.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said \RSaturday\S that if I played the type of game Payne
Stewart can play, I'd be standing here with the trophy. And I
didn't do that,'' Stewart said. ``Plus, Lee Janzen shot 68 on a day
when nobody else in contention could break par. He deserves to win.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm disappointed. But this isn't going to change my life. I
didn't play well enough to win. It's as simple as that. And it
won't take me very long at all to get over this. I'll still be able
to sleep tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   Lehman indicated he may be missing a few winks for the
foreseeable future because he was ``irritated with myself'' after
falling short in the Open for a fourth consecutive year. The failed
54-hole leader at the past three Opens, Lehman began yesterday's
final round four strokes in back of Stewart and never made a
birdie.
</P>
<P>
   He placed fifth, which comes on the heels of finishes of third
(1995), second (1996) and third (1997).
</P>
<P>
   By his calculations, Lehman never gave himself a decent birdie
chance until the 11th hole. Then, he failed to capitalize on three
in a row.
</P>
<P>
   ``By the time I made bogey on 14, I knew I was history,'' Lehman
said. ``For the last two days, I've had the hardest time reading
the greens. I could never tell if we were going uphill or downhill.
Therefore, I never came close to making one.''
</P>
<P>
   Lehman left the course displaying a unique mix of iron-willed
determination and heart-tugging frustration.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I can keep playing this well in this tournament for the
next four or five years, I think I'm going to win one. Or two, or
three or four,'' Lehman said. ``But the last thing I want to do
right now is play golf. This is a big tournament and I'm
disappointed. I'm a little bit irritated with myself. It's very
frustrating to go through this again, I'll be honest with you.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
