<HEADLINE>
CLARK ON A ROLL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHNNY PAUL 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ Will Clark's reaching 100 runs batted in this
season remains a distinct possibility for the Rangers first
baseman.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be nice, but that's not something I came into the
season looking to do,'' said Clark, who entered last night's game
against the Angels with 42 RBI through the Rangers' first 73 games.
``Obviously, it's going to be tough when you've got a guy hitting
in front of you on pace to drive in 190.''
</P>
<P>
   Right fielder Juan Gonzalez no doubt diminishes the likelihood
of Clark reaching that plateau for the first time in the past seven
seasons. Clark drove in 116 runs for the San Francisco Giants in
1991.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Clark _ who hits primarily fifth in the Rangers'
lineup _ is on pace to drive in 93 runs this season.
</P>
<P>
   Rangers manager Johnny Oates utilized Clark as his designated
hitter last night for the second consecutive game. Clark continues
to experience discomfort in his left elbow.
</P>
<P>
   ``His left arm is not 100 percent,'' Oates said. ``We're getting
ready to go to a National League park \RWednesday\S, so I thought
this was a good time for this. It's just precautionary. I could
have played him at first base \Rlast night\S.''
Oliver ready The Rangers expect left-hander Darren Oliver to make
his scheduled start Friday against the Giants in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Oliver, whom the Rangers placed on the 15-day disabled list June
13 (retroactive to June 11) with a muscle strain in his left
shoulder, experienced no discomfort during yesterday's medical
rehabilitation start for Triple-A Oklahoma.
</P>
<P>
   Oliver, who did not figure in the decision in the RedHawks' 6-5
loss to Memphis, surrendered only two hits and one walk during five
scoreless innings.
Van Poppel a go Oates reiterated yesterday right-hander Todd Van
Poppel will start Thursday against the Arizona Diamondbacks in
Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   One catch exists: Van Poppel will be required to hit in the
National League ballpark.
</P>
<P>
   ``I asked him today how much he's been hitting lately,'' Oates
said. ``We'll give him a crash course when we get home.''
No local TV Last night's game was the Rangers' first regular-season
game not televised since Sept. 11, 1996, at Toronto. The 7 p.m.
start time interfered with ESPN's exclusive telecast window that
affects road-game telecasts.
Briefly Right-hander Tanyon Sturtze, who underwent arthroscopic
surgery to repair a tear in his right rotator cuff in February,
made his first appearance this season Saturday for the Rangers'
rookie affiliate in the Gulf Coast League. Sturtze allowed three
runs _ two earned _ on three hits, including a home run, and two
walks during two innings.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers entered last night's contest without a stolen base
during their past 12 games. That represents their longest streak of
the season without a stolen base.
Farm report Triple-A Oklahoma (Pacific Coast League): Left-hander
Ricky Pickett (1-1) earned the victory in relief as the RedHawks
(39-27) beat Memphis, 8-6, Saturday in 11 innings. Outfielder Marc
Sagmoen went 2-for-6 with two RBI.
</P>
<P>
   Double-A Tulsa (Texas League): Second baseman Warren Morris went
2-for-4 with two RBI, and center fielder Ruben Mateo homered as the
Drillers (34-41) defeated Jackson, 6-2, Saturday. Right-hander
Danny Kolb (4-9, 5.00) allowed only two runs during eight innings
for the victory.
</P>
<P>
   Class-A Savannah (South Atlantic League): The Sand Gnats (35-39)
lost both games in Saturday's doubleheader of seven-inning games
against Augusta. First baseman Travis Hafner went 1-for-2 with a
double and a run scored during an 8-2 loss in the first game, and
center fielder Anthony Fisher went 2-for-3 with two RBI in an 8-1
defeat in the second game.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
