<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHAYS-PROFILE-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHRISTOPHER SHAYS: GOP MAVERICK PUSHING CAMPAIGN FINANCE BILL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Conn., Mass., Ohio, Ind., N.Y.)   (bl)  
 By JAMES DAO   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ To all the world, this would seem to be Rep.
Christopher Shays' moment in the sun.
</P>
<P>
   He is chief spokesman and rabble-rouser on the hot congressional
issue of the summer, his bill to toughen campaign finance laws.
Good-government groups, Democrats and editorial writers are calling
him a hero for defying his party leadership, which wants to kill
his legislation. Even critics say that martyrdom, if it comes to
that, may only increase his stature.
</P>
<P>
   So why does he seem so anguished?
</P>
<P>
   ``My melancholy nature is because I'm in a position I don't like
to be in,'' Shays, from Stamford, Conn., said last week. ``I am a
Republican who can't be proud of how my Republicans are conducting
themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Shays has become the reluctant general in an uprising he helped
ignite. For much of his 11 years in Congress, he has been an
iconoclastic champion of reform and moderate causes, challenging
the conservatives who control his party on issues from abortion to
gun control to the minimum wage. But his party credentials never
seemed in doubt.
</P>
<P>
   Until now. With the party expecting a fierce fight this fall to
retain control of the House, Shays has allied himself with
Democrats behind legislation that many Republicans believe will
strip away their party's fund-raising advantages. And so, the
murmured questions about his loyalty and back-room calls for his
punishment have grown louder.
</P>
<P>
   It is a position Shays does not seem to relish, even though
taking shots at the party seems like good politics for moderate
Republicans these days.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've seen some Republicans who are amused by being able to put
their thumb in the eye of the party,'' said Rep. John Kasich,
R-Ohio, who is one of Shays' closest friends in the House. ``Chris
is never that way. He feels bad whenever he's at odds with the
party.
</P>
<P>
   ``But,'' Kasich added, ``feeling bad doesn't stop him from doing
what he thinks is right.''
</P>
<P>
   At issue is a bill sponsored by Shays and Rep. Martin Meehan,
D-Mass., that would ban ``soft money,'' which is used for party
expenses like voter registration drives and can be collected in
unlimited sums, in Federal elections. The measure would also
restrict campaign-related advertising by groups like the Christian
Coalition, the National Rifle Association and unions.
</P>
<P>
   The bill has placed the Republicans in an exquisite bind. Party
leaders oppose it because it would curb practices that helped them
win control of Congress four years ago. But blocking an overhaul of
a system that many voters seem to consider out of control will also
hand Democrats a major issue this fall as they try to trim the
Republicans' 11-vote majority in the House.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he continues on this so-called reform, he is going to
endanger the Republican Congress that has done more to reform the
federal government than any other entity,'' said John Feerhery, a
spokesman for House Majority Whip Tom DeLay, R-Texas, who is
leading the fight against Shays' bill.
</P>
<P>
   The leadership has settled on a strategy to weaken, or at least
stall, the bill by allowing debate on more than 200 amendments.
Friday, Shays and his allies beat back the first of those
amendments, but they acknowledged that it is far too early to
declare victory.
</P>
<P>
   Shays has tried to play on his leadership's anxieties about
November, warning them that the Republicans are more likely to lose
seats if they kill his bill than if they surrender fund-raising
advantages. ``Some Republicans feel that I am advocating something
that hurts the party,'' he said. ``I feel vociferously that I am
helping to save the party.''
</P>
<P>
   But that argument seems only to anger some Republicans. Indeed,
at the urging of conservatives, House Speaker Newt Gingrich
recently warned Shays, who heads the government Reform and
Oversight's human resources subcommittee, and other Republicans
that they will lose their committee assignments if they help the
Democrats dictate debate on campaign finance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even people who admire Chris' independence think this isn't a
good time to put the party in a box, right before the election,''
said Rep. Mark Souder, R-Ind., who is friendly with Shays. ``It's
helping to fuel some pressures internally to take committee
assignments away from people like him.''
</P>
<P>
   Shays, 52, hardly seems the type to lead an uprising. He is
soft-spoken and oddly modest for a politician. He allows staff
workers to interrupt and contradict him. He does not mind saying,
``I don't know.'' And he insists on calling his bill Meehan-Shays,
though everyone else knows it as Shays-Meehan.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is not by nature a maverick,'' said Rep. Barney Frank,
D-Mass. ``He's a cheek turner. But on campaign finance, he ran out
of cheeks.''
</P>
<P>
   But he is also stubborn _ piously so, some critics say. Shays
often talks about how his opponents are ``morally wrong.'' And as a
member of the Connecticut state Legislature 13 years ago, he served
six days in jail on a contempt charge when he refused to retreat in
a confrontation with a judge he considered corrupt.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he comes to a decision, he comes to it from a strongly
religious background,'' Rich Galen, executive director of GOPAC,
the Republican political action committee, said of Shays, a
Christian Scientist. ``And once he does, he is absolutely confident
it is the right decision.''
</P>
<P>
   Shays does not talk much about campaign finance when he is at
home in the 4th District, which stretches along Long Island Sound
from Greenwich to Bridgeport. But his socially moderate,
independent-minded Yankee Republicanism clearly plays well there.
His predecessors in the House, Lowell Weicker and Stewart McKinney,
were cut from similar cloth. And Shays has won most of his races
handily.
</P>
<P>
   His centrist politics reflect the mixed nature of his district.
On a recent weekend at home, Shays spent an afternoon helping to
build a house in a poor neighborhood of Bridgeport with Habitat for
Humanity, then spoke before the Darien Republican Club in a house
that is expected to sell for more than $2 million once construction
is finished. He ended his tour at a fund-raising event for a health
clinic that serves low-income children from Stamford.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a real human being,'' Andrew McBride, a former health
official in Stamford, told the crowd. ``Even though he happens to
be a Republican.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Newt Gingrich is not a popular figure in the district. In 1996,
Democrats cut Shays' share of the vote to 60 percent, from 74
percent in 1994, and almost defeated his Republican colleague from
New Britain, Rep. Nancy Johnson, largely by linking them to the
speaker.
</P>
<P>
   But often in defiance of his own aides, Shays has remained an
ardent Gingrich loyalist. Even as he has bashed the Republican
leadership on campaign finance, he has been careful to blunt
attacks of Gingrich personally.
</P>
<P>
   Shays says he became a fan of Gingrich after he and his wife of
30 years, Betsi, heard him speak in Connecticut in 1991. ``We
thought, `My God, we agree with 90 percent of what he said,'''
Shays recalled. ``When he is inspired, when he focuses on his
positive hopes and dreams for our country, he can be a genius.''
</P>
<P>
   Shays became an early advocate of the Contract With America,
defended Gingrich during a 1995 ethics investigation, and was one
of the first people to warn the speaker of plans of a coup against
him by conservatives last year. Such fidelity has gained him
nothing, Shays says.
</P>
<P>
   ``He will not reward me as his friend,'' Shays said, ``but he
will certainly punish me as his opponent.''
</P>
<P>
   Connecticut Democratic leaders, who plan to attack Shays' ties
to Gingrich again this year, say he has tried to play both ends
against the middle, supporting fiscally conservative policies that
have hurt his district while attacking Republicans on issues like
campaign finance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I view Chris as a great opportunist who is kind of a
chameleon,'' said Edward Marcus, chairman of the state Democratic
Party.
</P>
<P>
   Reared in Darien, Shays has been a Republican for as long as he
can remember. But he supported George McGovern in 1972 out of
revulsion with Watergate and the war. And though he voted for
Richard Nixon in 1960, it was John F. Kennedy's message of public
service that inspired him to join the Peace Corps in 1968 along
with his wife, Betsi. Mrs. Shays is now a seventh grade social
studies teacher in New Canaan; the couple have an 18-year-old
daughter, Jeramy.
</P>
<P>
   After two years teaching English in Fiji, Shays returned home
and applied to be a conscientious objector against the war in
Vietnam. He was turned down, but was never drafted. If he had been,
``I would have gone to jail before I would have gone to serve,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Though it angers him to hear Republicans question his loyalty,
Shays seems to go out of his way to tell colleagues that he cares
about his party. During a chance encounter in the Capitol last week
with Rep. Bill Paxon, R-N.Y., who is helping the party candidate in
a special election in New Mexico on Tuesday, Shays said: ``I sent
two checks for $500. I wanted you to know I was concerned.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he would ever change parties, Shays bristled.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I go down, I am going down as a Republican,'' he said. ``If
anything, I feel even more strongly the need to fight back.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
