<SLUG> BC-GLF-OPEN-NOTES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AZINGER CLOSES STRONG
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIMMY BURCH 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Paul Azinger finished with a flurry, bagging
eight birdies in the final round and shooting a 65, lowest score
during any round at the 1998 U.S. Open.
</P>
<P>
   Azinger hit 11 greens in regulation and needed just 25 putts to
move from 55th to 14th place in the tournament, at 9-over.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you can shoot that kind of score, you take it no matter
what day it is,'' Azinger said. ``I wish I'd played better early in
the week, but I didn't.''
</P>
<P>
   Azinger said he came into yesterday's round with 65 as a goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt if I shot 65, I might finish in the top 15. I knew that
would get me back into the tournament next year,'' said Azinger,
who reached his goal of a berth in the 1999 Open when several
front-runners backtracked during the afternoon. ``I really woke up
thinking about a 65. It's pretty amazing I shot it.''
Martin misses Masters invite Casey Martin took three bogeys and no
birdies on his back nine in the final round, costing him a chance
to finish in the top 16 and earn a berth in the 1999 Masters.
Instead, Martin's final-round effort of 72 left him at 11 over and
in 23rd place in his Open debut.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to get into the Masters, but that's the way it
goes,'' said Martin, a disabled golfer who became the first player
in Open history to compete while using a golf cart. ``I played well
but not my absolute best. I think I have more game than what I
showed.''
</P>
<P>
   As for special memories of the 1998 Open, Martin said: ``The way
I was treated by the galleries, with everyone rooting for me. At
times, I got goosebumps ... because people were so supportive.
That's what I'll take as special from this week.''
Kuchars party on U.S. Amateur champ Matt Kuchar will always
remember his 20th birthday, which he celebrated yesterday by
draining an 18-foot par putt on the final hole to seal a berth in
the 1999 Open. He did so on Father's Day, with father/caddie Peter
Kuchar carrying the clubs in Matt's Open debut.
</P>
<P>
   The putt gave Kuchar a share of 14th place and an automatic
berth in the 1999 Open. The top 15 finishers receive automatic
berths the ensuing year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a higher goal. I wanted to see how high I could get my
name up on the leader board,'' Matt Kuchar said. ``But it's
outstanding to ... get to come back.''
</P>
<P>
   Peter Kuchar said: ``I couldn't think of a better Father's Day
present. If the next 20 years are as good as the first 20, we're in
for quite a ride.''
Struggling home Fort Worth resident Mark Brooks split six of 14
fairways and hit just five greens in regulation during a closing
round of 76. Both figures stood as tournament lows for Brooks, who
finished 57th, at 18-over par.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hit some good shots and a lot of bad ones. It's been a tough
week,'' said Brooks, who finished two strokes behind defending
champ Ernie Els (16 over).
</P>
<P>
   Els, who closed with a 76, downplayed the back injury that has
plagued him since he withdrew from last week's Buick Classic.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to blame my play on my back. My putting is what
let me down more than anything,'' said Els, who needed 33 putts
yesterday and averaged 32.5 putts per round. ``Plus, this is the
toughest golf course I've ever played in an Open. You couldn't do
anything wrong this weekend and shoot par.''
</P>
<P>
   British Open champ Justin Leonard finished at 14 over but closed
with a birdie and six pars down the stretch during a round of 71
that matched his best of the tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ``I leave here with a little better taste in my mouth,'' Leonard
said. ``But I still didn't make any putts.''
Briefly One day after driving the green at the 288-yard seventh
hole to set up a two-putt birdie, John Daly five-putted the seventh
green in yesterday's final round. Included was a backhand miss from
less than a foot that capped a quadruple-bogey eight. Daly closed
with a 78 and finished 17 over.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Perry, on the overall experience of Open week at the
Olympic Club: ``You make the cut and go, `I've got to go through
two more rounds of this?' This course doesn't turn men into boys.
It turns men into children. It makes us pros look like
15-handicappers.''
</P>
<P>
   Tiger Woods, after finishing 10-over with a closing 73: ``I've
never had to hit cuts and draw off every tee to keep it in the
fairway before. I think I learned something this week. I hit the
ball better than I scored.''
</P>
</TEXT>
