<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-21 23:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9785 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-R-SMITH-GLOBE-MEDIA-5     06-21 1061
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-SMITH-GLOBE-MEDIA-570&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORS REFLECT ON FABRICATIONS BY GLOBE COLUMNIST 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass., Ill., Calif., N.Y.)   (Repeating to add photo note.)  
(ART ADV: Photo of Patricia Smith is being sent to NYT photo
clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(mk) 
 By ROBIN POGREBIN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   News that The Boston Globe had asked last week for the
resignation of Patricia Smith, a metropolitan region columnist,
because of fabrications in her work, prompted self-examination at
other newspapers around the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes us rethink for sure,'' said George Langford, the
public editor at The Chicago Tribune, who acts as the newspaper's
ombudsman. ``It certainly sharpens your antennae. I suppose that's
about the only good thing I can see coming out of it, because it
certainly is very damaging to all of us.''
</P>
<P>
   While fact-checking departments have long been a tradition at
some magazines, daily newspapers have largely relied on their
reporters when it comes to accuracy. Because of the pressures of
daily deadlines and the volume of copy coursing through a newsroom
in any given night, newspapers say they have no choice.
</P>
<P>
   ``We learned that these organizations inevitably depend on
trust,'' said Robert Kaiser, managing editor of The Washington
Post, alluding to the case of Janet Cooke, a reporter who admitted
to creating a composite of an inner-city youth for an article that
won the Pulitzer Prize. ``If there is a system that can guarantee
things of this kind can't happen, I haven't heard of it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have such a system, and I guess I think that the
Patricia Smith episode may be evidence of why there's no point in
it really,'' Kaiser continued _ ``why it can't work.''
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, Joseph Lelyveld, the executive editor of The New York
Times, said, ``We operate from a position of trust in our
reporters.''
</P>
<P>
   To the extent that newspapers have safeguards, editors say,
these are their many levels of editing. Langford said the Chicago
Tribune's first line of defense was its ``source'' editors, editors
who deal with content. After that, Langford said, articles go
through the copy desk.
</P>
<P>
   At The Wall Street Journal, the managing editor, Paul Steiger,
said an article could go through a varying number of editors,
depending on its importance and where it will run in the paper. ``A
page one story can have five, sometimes six, levels of editors,''
he said. ``Small, inside news stories will have two.''
</P>
<P>
   While columnists have more room to offer their opinions or
analysis, Steiger said, ``The checking process is the same.''
</P>
<P>
   Marshall Loeb, editor of The Columbia Journalism Review,
suggested that newspapers consider instituting fact-checking
procedures for particular kinds of articles. ``A newspaper would be
well served if it had available some fact checkers to examine and
raise questions about certain complicated and controversial stories
or series of stories,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The disclosure that Ms. Smith had concocted people and quotes in
at least four columns earlier this year was particularly dramatic,
given that it became public just a week after The New Republic
concluded that Stephen Glass, a staff writer, fabricated all or
part of 27 of the 41 articles he wrote for the magazine in two and
a half years.
</P>
<P>
   But editors say incidents of fakery remain few. Leo Wolinsky,
managing editor for news at The Los Angeles Times, said about 10
years ago a reporter was dismissed after making up quotations that
he contended came from a news-agency dispatch. (It turned out that
the reporter had altered the wire story to include the fabricated
quotes.) Wolinsky said another reporter was dismissed for
plagiarizing from a script for public television.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In response to the Globe incident, Wolinsky said Michael Parks,
the editor of The Los Angeles Times, had asked his staff to reflect
on the situation at their early-morning meeting. ``He asked us to
think about what we're doing and whether we're on the right path,''
Wolinsky said.
</P>
<P>
   Wolinsky, as well as several other editors interviewed, said
they were surprised to learn that Matthew Storin, editor of The
Globe, a New York Times Co. newspaper, had established a
spot-checking system of columnists a couple of years ago. ``That's
something I didn't know took place anywhere,'' Wolinsky said.
</P>
<P>
   Edward Seaton, president of the American Society of Newspaper
Editors, said his organization was about to come out with a study
that examined the extent to which newspaper credibility had
declined. ``Newspapers have declined more than other media,''
Seaton said. ``We're concerned about that.''
</P>
<P>
   In a recent informal study on corrections, the society found
that 21 newspapers had formal procedures for finding out how an
error occurred and 35 had informal procedures.
</P>
<P>
   Seaton also said that the society was reviewing its decision to
give a distinguished-writing award to Ms. Smith earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   The Smith case, coupled with the Glass incident, has prompted
publications to speculate about what would drive a reporter to
cross the bright line from fact into fiction. Was it the pressure
to produce, to stand out, to sustain a heady level of success?
</P>
<P>
   ``There certainly is more pressure these days to make newspapers
more compelling to readers,'' Wolinsky said. ``Everybody wants to
be special and everybody wants their stories to be talked about and
read, and the truth about it is most people don't have such
scintillating quotes. And if they could make it up themselves, it
would read a lot better.''
</P>
<P>
   Although editors generally said the Smith and Glass cases had
not prompted them to change their policies, several said these,
along with the frenzied Monica Lewinsky coverage, had made them
more cautious. ``We're more circumspect today,'' Langford of The
Chicago Tribune said. ``The downside is just too great.''
</P>
<P>
   But no matter how careful, editors insisted, a newspaper cannot
completely prevent such violations. ``Absent some kind of Draconian
_ `give me a photograph and the driver's license of everyone you've
quoted,''' Kaiser of The Washington Post said, ``someone who had
the inclination to do this sort of thing could probably get away
with it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
